<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Tobacco Co. Faces $1.05B Payout  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PADUCAH, Ky. (AP) -- U.S. Tobacco Co., the nation's largest snuff
tobacco company, will have to pay $1.05 billion to its top rival
after a federal jury ruled it had violated antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   After a monthlong trial, the jury deliberated for almost four
hours on Tuesday before setting damages at $350 million against
Greenwich, Conn.-based U.S. Tobacco. Under federal antitrust laws,
the damages were automatically tripled.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Tobacco said it would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Conwood Co., based in Memphis, Tenn., had sought $500 million
when it filed the lawsuit in U.S. District Court two years ago. It
holds about 13 percent of the snuff market with its top-selling
Kodiak brand.
</P>
<P>
   Conwood alleged that U.S. Tobacco, which controls about 79
percent of the smokeless tobacco market with such products as
Copenhagen and Skoal, used illegal tactics to monopolize an
industry in which profit margins are as high as 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies accused each other of removing display racks from
stores, making under-the-table cash rebates to win retailers and
holding strategy sessions to plot out how to eliminate the other
from the lucrative retail-checkout market.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors found that U.S. Tobacco monopolized the market by
controlling prices or excluding competition or both.
</P>
<P>
   Snuff users place a pinch of shredded tobacco between their lip
and gum. They tend to be young and middle-aged white males.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the nation's smokeless tobacco is grown in western
Kentucky, where the trial took place. Conwood has a plant in
Bowling Green, and U.S. Tobacco has one in Hopkinsville.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are extremely disappointed by the jury's verdict,'' Vincent
A. Gierer Jr., chairman and chief executive of U.S. Tobacco, said
in a prepared statement. ''We believe that the plaintiff failed to
prove its case under applicable law, especially in light of the
voluminous evidence which clearly shows that U.S. Tobacco and
Conwood compete in a highly competitive marketplace. We also
believe that the size of the award was completely unjustified given
the evidence presented at trial.''
</P>
<P>
   David Simpson, Conwood's general counsel, would not comment
other than to issue a statement confirming the verdict. The company
issued a statement Wednesday saying, ''The jury's findings were
fully and completely supported by the record.''
</P>
<P>
   Conwood attorneys accused U.S. Tobacco of spreading rumors that
Conwood's snuff contained stems and was stale. Conwood also alleged
that U.S. Tobacco controlled point-of-sale advertising and often
inserted its ads over Conwood's own sales displays in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Point-of-sale advertising is vital to the tobacco industry
because of heavy state and federal limitations on media
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for U.S. Tobacco did not deny trying to control the
market but said the company's practices failed to meet the litmus
test of antitrust violations.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the company argued that exclusionary rack
practices were not illegal under other parts of antitrust law and
some allegations merely constituted ordinary business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Experts testified that Conwood made $1 billion in profits during
the 1990s and U.S. Tobacco earned more than $5 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
