<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parents, religious group upset by student lecture series onhomosexuality  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) -- David Nosanchuk loved a good debate to stir
things up. The student-organized lecture series started at Ithaca
High School in his memory has certainly accomplished that this
year.
</P>
<P>
   School officials this week received two petitions signed by more
than 400 people upset with this year's topic, ''Being Gay in
America.'' On Monday and Tuesday, small groups of protesters even
picketed the high school.
</P>
<P>
   Principal Susan Strauss said there were no protesters Wednesday
as the weeklong lecture series continued with a debate on gays in
the military and a critical discussion of Vermont's proposed law to
allow ''civil unions'' between gay couples by Jamiel Terry, the son
of Operation Rescue founder Randall Terry.
</P>
<P>
   It is the 16th year for the lecture series, which was started in
1984 in honor of Nosanchuk, who was senior class president when he
accidentally drowned. Strauss said Nosanchuk was known for his
passion for wanting to explore different perspectives on debated
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Each year the series is designed by a volunteer student
committee that solicits input on topics of interest from other
students. In the past, topics have included the military draft,
AIDS, genetics, civil liberties, the impact of advertising, gender
roles and Latin American affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the most controversial thing that's come up. I'm sure
that in past years that some of the others have caused controversy,
just not to this extent,'' Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Jean and David Owens presented school officials with a petition
Monday containing the signatures of 300 parents. The petition said
only that the signers were opposed to the topic.
</P>
<P>
   The Owenses said there should have been discussion with parents
to make sure there was a balance of opinions in the series and that
students understood that they did not have to attend the lectures.
</P>
<P>
   The Owenses have no children presently attending the school,
although they have three children who are graduates and one
daughter who will enter the school next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss said the series clearly offers various viewpoints and
has never been mandatory for students.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think people did not take the time to learn about the
preparation and the process. They just reacted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 140 people signed a petition from the Family
Alliance for Cultural Tolerance, a group composed of members from
several area churches. Among their objections, the religious
coalition said it was upset over the ''lack of tolerance of views
and values of many parents, students and taxpayers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
