<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Hurt in Four-Horse Accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Harness driver George Brennan
received stitches in his face Wednesday night after being involved
in a four-horse spill during the third race at the Meadowlands
Racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan cut his face and was disoriented after being sent to the
ground when his horse, Kittyhawk, fell in a chain reaction that
started after another horse fell.
</P>
<P>
   He was treated at Hackensack Medical Center. Track spokeswoman
Amy Silver said he would be released Wednesday night. She
attributed his disorientation to the shock of the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''The trauma of the accident just had him a little confused
right when he went down,'' she said. ''He's conscious and he's
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers Luc Ouellette, Ron Pierce and David Miller were also
involved in the accident, which started when Ouellette's horse,
Mega Laugh, threw a shoe and fell.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and his pacer, Picasso's Filly, fell, causing Brennan and
Kittyhawk to fall, followed by Pierce and Ah Rumba.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan was the most seriously hurt. Pierce slightly injured his
left heel, while Miller and Ouellette had some scrapes and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four pacers, only Picasso's Filly had a slightly injured
hind leg, which was not considered serious. The other horses were
scraped and bruised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
