<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders can't agree on where the center of the universe is  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- While they did not pass a state budget this
week, as they are supposed to do under the state constitution, the
two top figures in the state Legislature did address a
philosophical question.
</P>
<P>
   As in: Where is the center of the state?
</P>
<P>
   State Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver accused Senate Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno of being fixated on his district and local
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senator Bruno ... thinks this state revolves around places
like Troy and Schenectady and Saratoga,'' Democrat Silver said.
''The reality is, the economic activity which drives this state
happens to be located in downtown Manhattan. A lot of the school
districts are funded as a result of what takes place down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver happens to represent a district located in downtown
Manhattan which includes Wall Street. Republican Bruno is from
upstate Rensselaer County, which includes Troy.
</P>
<P>
   Verbal sparring between Silver and Bruno usually begins this
time of year as the legislative leaders begin rounding into form so
they can throw the real rhetorical haymakers when state budget
negotiations get hot and heavy.
</P>
<P>
   But Silver's jab was a little sharper than usual.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it suggests that upstate-downstate frictions are
never far below the surface in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   For another, it hints at some legislators' views of Bruno's
benevolence to his constituents, especially since he became
majority leader in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno has been a tireless advocate for the 43rd Senatorial
District and for the nearby city of Albany, where many of his
constituents work for the state.
</P>
<P>
   He has made sure hundreds of state jobs have been relocated to
Troy, the biggest city in his district. He championed a state
bailout package to bring Troy back from the brink of bankruptcy. He
has provided state grants and other aid programs to encourage
companies to locate or expand in his district. He has aided
colleges, promoted cultural facilities, even championed a boost in
the size of purses offered for thoroughbreds running at the nearby
Saratoga Race Course, which he likes to attend each August.
</P>
<P>
   In smaller ways, Bruno has seen to it that scores of community
groups have benefitted from ''member item'' grants that Legislature
hands out.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Bruno has taken care of the 43rd Senatorial District
in a way that powerful legislators have done since legislative
bodies first formed political blocs and elected representatives to
watch out for their interests.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, acquiring the ability to produce for their districts is
one of the chief reasons that legislators strive for jobs like the
majority leader's -- that and the higher stipend, bigger staff,
feeling of power, state car, access to state aircraft, control over
patronage jobs and all the other things that go with being a
legislative leader in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Silver says he wants to deliver a gem of a project
to Manhattan in the form of a Second Avenue subway line. It would
pass through the speaker's 62nd Assembly District.
</P>
<P>
   Silver suggested he will hold up passage of a new state budget
if it does not contain a commitment to build the subway project.
</P>
<P>
   Silver's promotion of the subway had Bruno questioning where the
speaker believes the center of his world is.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really laugh when I heard him talk about Troy when he is out
there, literally saying, 'I'm holding up the budget because I want
$13 billion for a Second Avenue subway which terminates in my
district,''' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno insists he is taking Silver's comments in stride as part
of Albany's time-honored spirit of political rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just flailing around and saying things,'' Bruno said.
''One day he calls me this, another day he calls me that. I know
Shelly well enough to know he doesn't mean any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno, by the way, is in no way apologizing for any of the
things his position as majority leader has helped produce for his
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am very proud of what we've done in our district,'' he said.
''I'm going to continue to advocate for things in my district, just
as he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's colleagues are well aware of that.
</P>
<P>
   When Troy Mayor Mark Pattison appeared before the Senate's
Cities Committee on Feb. 29 to ask for more state aid, chairman
Frank Padavan, a Queens Republican, told the mayor, ''You don't
have any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Troy is one big member item,'' the senator said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko first covered state government for The Associated
Press in 1981. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
