<DOCNO> APW20000330.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> As oil prices climb, Long Islanders look to the sun  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- A plan by the Long Island Power Authority
to get solar energy panels installed on 10,000 rooftops in the next
decade is winning praise from at least one longtime nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Gordian Raacke, executive director of the Citizens Advisory
Panel, conceded that his watchdog group has been critical of LIPA
in the past, but said Wednesday he enthusiastically endorsed the
solar energy effort.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, it's interesting that we're doing this now when
there is a crisis regarding fossil fuel prices,'' he said. ''The
price of sunlight is still free. ... We will not have to rely on
OPEC or anyone else to tap into this resource.''
</P>
<P>
   The LIPA effort is part of the national ''Million Solar Roofs''
initiative that President Clinton began three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to be the center, the capital, of solar energy in New
York state and one of the places in the nation that can be a model
for this new technology,'' said Richard Kessel, chairman of LIPA.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a great opportunity to emphasize renewable
technologies,'' he said. ''The more renewable technologies we can
initiate, the more solar roofs we have on Long Island, the fewer
power plants we have to build, the fewer emissions we have to
poison our environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The solar panels are actually a collection of photovoltaic
cells, made of a semiconductor material -- usually silicon -- that
produce an electric current when exposed to light. The cells can be
created in various sizes and shapes to meet the power requirements
of a specific building.
</P>
<P>
   LIPA officials said the cost of installing solar panels to
create enough electricity for a typical house is between $10,000
and $12,000. LIPA provides low-interest financing and other
discounts and the state offers a partial tax credit to defray
installation costs.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is also required by law to buy back any unused
electricity created by the solar panels, LIPA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its solar energy promotion, LIPA held a lottery last
year and picked 30 homes from a pool of 5,000 entries to receive
free solar panel systems.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Saul, a homemaker and mother of two from Melville, was
among the winners and has had no complaints since the system was
installed in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really haven't had any problems,'' she said. ''People say
they don't look bad, some people say they look like skylights on
the roof.''
</P>
<P>
   Saul's home was installed with only two panels -- not enough to
power her entire split-level ranch -- but enough to provide her with
an anticipated $120 in annual savings on her electric bill, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think solar energy is an alternate source that we should
definitely take advantage of,'' said Bruce McCauley, a retired
junior high school teacher from East Setauket who also won the LIPA
lottery. He said the cost of the panels will have to come down
before solar energy gains wider acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sort of like the first computers that came out,'' Raacke
said. ''Prices are still very high because there's still a very
small market. These things are still being assembled by hand. ...
Once that market gets going, mass production is going to bring down
prices considerably. That's when the broad public is going see it
installed on their rooftops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 0049 </TRAILER>
