<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, March 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Third Child in Train Collision Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TENNGA, Ga. (AP) -- A deadly train crash that ripped a school bus off its
wheels claimed a third victim Wednesday. Amber Pritchett, 9, one of seven
students on board the bus when it was struck at an unprotected rural crossing
early Tuesday, died Wednesday night a spokeswoman for T.C. Thompson Children's
Hospital in Chattanooga, Tenn., said. Kayla Silvers, 6, and Daniel Pack, 9, were
killed when the CSX freight train smashed into their Murray County school bus at
about 50 mph, ripped the bus from its chassis and dragged it 100 feet down the
track.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Status Revocation Delayed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Federal officials have delayed revoking Elian Gonzalez's
temporary status until Friday. Immigration officials and the boy's great-uncle
met for five hours Wednesday and are planning to meet again tomorrow. Just hours
ago, Cuban leader Fidel Castro announced that the 6-year-old's father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, is ready to travel to Florida to retrieve him. It was the first
time anyone has said the boy's father would be willing to stay in the United
States during the legal process.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iran, Mexico To Boost Oil Output
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- After first refusing to join its OPEC colleagues in
an agreement to increase oil production, Iran reversed course Wednesday, saying
it will pump more to keep other producers from taking away its market share.
Mexico, one of the leading oil producers not in the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, also plans to increase output. At a White House news
conference today, President Clinton said the OPEC agreement should reduce both
home heating costs and gasoline prices over the next few weeks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Judge Rules Clinton Violated Privacy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Resurrecting an impeachment controversy, a federal judge
ruled Wednesday that President Clinton ''committed a criminal violation of the
Privacy Act'' by releasing personal letters to undermine the credibility of one
of his accusers. Clinton immediately disputed the decision, saying he
reluctantly released the letters two years ago because ''it was the only way I
knew to refute allegations'' by Kathleen Willey of an unwanted sexual advance.
U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth, a Republican appointee, concluded the
president and three top White House lawyers disregarded an earlier court ruling
in making Willey's letters public in the midst of the Monica Lewinsky scandal in
1998.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Wants Withdrawal Safeguard
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel wants international intervention to ensure a quiet
border in case its withdrawal from Lebanon is done without an agreement with
Syria, Foreign Minister David Levy said Wednesday. Israel TV reported that
Israel agreed to a U.S. request to delay a campaign to enlist international
support for three weeks, apparently to avoid alienating Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon, in last-ditch efforts to renew peace talks. A summit Sunday
in Geneva between President Clinton and Syrian President Hafez Assad failed to
bring about a resumption of the peace talks, stalled since January.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Keeps Focus on Education
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- George W. Bush, reaching out to women and political
moderates, kept up his focus on education Wednesday and suggested that support
for abortion rights wouldn't necessarily disqualify any potential running mate.
Bush, the expected Republican presidential nominee, toured a charter school that
he said showed how his proposal for alternatives to failing schools could work.
New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman, mentioned by some as a possible vice
presidential choice, accompanied him. While saying he had not made any running
mate lists, Bush spoke warmly of Whitman when reporters asked about her chances,
even though he opposes abortion and she favors abortion rights.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose moderately Thursday after the morning
session. The Nikkei gained 101.76 points to 20,808.41. On Wall Street Wednesday,
the Dow Jones industrial average rose 82.61 to close at 11,018.72.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Knicks Defeat SuperSonics 110-95
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Allan Houston led a balanced attack with 19 points and Marcus
Camby added 18 points and a career-high 19 rebounds Wednesday as the New York
Knicks rolled to a 110-95 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics. The Knicks dealt
the Sonics their fifth straight homecourt loss, which equaled the third-longest
home losing streak in Sonics history.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
