<HEADLINE> Sharpton sues RNC for libel  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Rev. Al Sharpton says he has no problem
with Republicans calling him bad names -- but ''murderer'' should
not be on that list.
</P>
<P>
   The activist minister filed a $30 million libel lawsuit
Wednesday against the Republican National Committee and its
chairman, Jim Nicholson. Sharpton claims the GOP libeled him by
saying he had incited riots and protests that led to deaths in
Crown Heights in 1991 and Harlem in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton was himself sued for slander for accusations he made in
the Tawana Brawley case years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a right to call me names, they have no right to
accuse me of a crime,'' Sharpton said outside RNC headquarters in
Washington, where he announced the filing of a lawsuit in U.S.
District Court in Washington. ''To accuse me of murder is
slander.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans stepped up their attacks on Sharpton after Democrats
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Al Gore met privately with him as they
courted black voters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said Wednesday that he stands by his statement,
published in the Washington Post on March 11 as a letter to the
editor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Sharpton is no civil rights leader. He is a hatemonger, an
anti-Semite and a racist, and for him to be a political partner of
Al Gore and Hillary Clinton ... is shameful,'' the RNC leader said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sharpton set off four nights of rock and bottle throwing
attacks on Jewish homes culminating in a mob surrounding a young
Talmudic scholar Yankel Rosenbaum and stabbing him to death,''
Nicholson wrote in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton is familiar with the libel law. Steven Pagones, a
former Dutchess County prosecutor, sued Sharpton, Alton Maddox and
C. Vernon Mason for naming him as one of Brawley's attackers in
1987. A grand jury determined that the teen had fabricated her
claims that she was abducted and raped by a group of white men.
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-month trial, a jury in Poughkeepsie in 1998
ordered Sharpton to pay Pagones $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said Wednesday he has not paid Pagones because the
verdict is still being appealed. But he said he might use parts of
Pagones' case against him as a precedent for his own case.
</P>
<P>
   ''So in many ways Steve Pagones may end up a good thing for
me,'' Sharpton said, adding that he could use any money won from
the RNC to pay off Pagones.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones said Wednesday that Sharpton should drop his case.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Sharpton should have learned anything it's that truth is an
absolute defense,'' he said. ''I don't think the RNC said anything
that was inaccurate or false.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
