<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman backs harsher penalties for violations  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The focus in this year's presidential race on
reforming campaign finance laws should convince Congress that the
least it can do is enforce the laws that already exist, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman told fellow lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn, the Connecticut Democrat
is pushing legislation that would make some violations of the
Federal Election Campaign Act felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, violations of the campaign act are misdemeanors. The
bill would also create guidelines for federal judges to sentence
defendants convicted of a felony.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we are trying to do is provide prosecutors in really
egregious situations -- not run-of-the-mill situations -- with the
tools to do something,'' Thompson told the Senate Committee on
Rules and Administration Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A campaign finance violation would only be a felony if it was
committed knowingly and willfully and the offense involved at least
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is targeted at someone who is more or less in the
business,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, introduced in November, grew out of both senators'
frustration with the outcome of investigations into fund-raising
practices in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Those investigations focused on people who had allegedly infused
foreign money into a political campaign or used unwitting straw
donors to hide the true source of money.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think all of us believed that the people who did those
things in 1996 would be prosecuted and appropriately punished,''
Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, only three of the 12 people who were convicted or
pleaded guilty in those scandals received jail time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic fund-raiser John Huang received fines, community
service and probation after pleading guilty to conspiracy. Huang
brought in $1.6 million in questionable donations that were later
returned.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's friend, Yah Lin ''Charlie'' Trie, was
sentenced to a few months of home detention followed by probation
after pleading guilty to causing others to make false statements to
the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Huang, Trie and others were convicted or pleaded
guilty doesn't eliminate the need to make illegal fund-raising a
felony itself, with its own punishment, Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's because when it comes time for sentencing, judges have
to turn to the federal sentencing guidelines, which still often
bring light sentences because there is no guideline on campaign
finance violations,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 0111 </TRAILER>
