<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Women and minorities underrepresented on state boards  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN, 
o0193nyc--
r n PM-CT--State-Minorities ConnBjt 600 03-30 0674
PM-CT--State-Minorities, Conn Bjt, 600   
Report: Women and minorities underrepresented on state boards   
jcstfrhpr   
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A report from the Secretary of the State
shows women and minorities continue to be underrepresented on
Connecticut boards and commissions.
</P>
<P>
   More than half such panels lack any appointed minority members,
Secretary of the State Susan Bysiewicz reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five percent of boards and commissions reported no
Hispanic members. White women showed some progress in increasing
their membership on the boards, but women overall remain
underrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   ''Progress toward diversity has been uneven at best,'' Bysiewicz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Betancourt, executive director of the Latino and Puerto
Rican Affairs Commission, said he was deeply disappointed by the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot conceive of a democratic system that is
disproportionately excluding an important sector of the population
from participating in the development of policies that affect us
all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Dickens, commissioner of the African-American Affairs
Commission, also expressed concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously there is an underrepresentation of African Americans
on state boards,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland, who is responsible for some of the
appointments, has a staff member whose job is to recruit people for
such boards, said spokesman Dean Pagani.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a situation the governor takes very seriously,'' Pagani
said. ''The governor agrees that more appointments of women and
minorities have to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   The report did not provide specifics of appointments by the
governor and legislative leaders. Pagani said he did not have
statistics either and could not say whether Rowland would take
additional measures in light of the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously the report reflects the need for more progress,''
Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader George Jepsen, D-Stamford, said he
tries to ensure diversity in making appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Especially on the more important commissions, I certainly try
to ensure there is female and minority participation,'' Jepsen
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report covers 1,997 appointed members of 203 state boards,
commissions, committees and councils. The bodies have a wide range
of functions including agriculture, state colleges, economic
development, Indian affairs, mental health and special education.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bodies have regulatory authority and quasi-judicial
functions.
</P>
<P>
   A little over 34 percent of appointed members of the boards were
women; about 51 percent of the state population is female. Blacks
make up 8.8 percent of the population but 6.6 percent of the
appointed members; about 8.5 percent of the population is Hispanic,
but they account for only 2.7 percent of the appointees, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Legislature required appointing authorities to make
a good faith effort to ensure the appointments reflect the gender
and racial diversity of the state, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   Including members appointed to boards by virtue of an office
they hold, female appointments increased from 27.7 percent in 1993
to 33.7 percent in 1999, according to the report. But that progress
was limited to white females, according to Leslie Brett, executive
director of the Permanent Commission on the Status of Women.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need all of our voices in state government,'' Brett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic representation, including ex-officio members, was 2.5
percent in 1999, an improvement over 1.5 percent in 1993 but down
from 3.4 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The report does not attempt to explain why the inequities exist.
It does note that many positions are unpaid, and that the posts
often have specific membership requirements which significantly
limit the pool of eligible appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Bysiewicz said the legislature should review whether the 1993
law is working. She also suggested posting vacancies on the
Internet because the public is often unaware of the openings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
