<HEADLINE> Bill to revise law banning campfires sent to governor  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Doug Krofina couldn't imagine a camping
trip without a campfire.
</P>
<P>
   So he breathed a sigh of relief when the Legislature voted
Wednesday to revise a law that inadvertently banned all open fires,
including ones for roasting marshmallows.
</P>
<P>
   ''The campfire is a focal point for scouts; you sing songs,
strengthen friendships,'' said Krofina, an executive for the
Connecticut Yankee Council of the Boy Scouts of America in the New
Haven area. ''It would have been devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved unanimously in both chambers, amends a law
designed to protect air quality and ban unsafe burning. The law was
passed last session and took effect Oct. 1, but it was months
before anyone realized its unintentional result.
</P>
<P>
   Scouting groups and campground owners flooded the Legislature
with calls and letters, saying the law would destroy their
activities. They asked for changes before the onset of warm weather
and the height of camping season.
</P>
<P>
   Violators faced fines up to $25,000 per day from the state
Department of Environmental Protection for polluting the air. But
DEP officials had said the law would be nearly impossible to
enforce and unlikely affect any Scout leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Legislature acted quickly to revise the law. The
Senate moved it to the top of the agenda Wednesday and the House
acted on it soon after.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was sent to Gov. John G. Rowland, who was expected to
sign it into law today. The measure would take effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was never any intention on the part of the Legislature
to interfere with scouting or camping,'' said state Sen. Eileen
Daily, a Westbrook Democrat who sponsored the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the thing we really wanted to react to immediately,''
said state Rep. Patricia Widlitz, D-Guilford, who raised the bill
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The law also came under fire from farmers, who were prohibited
from burning brush and required instead to dispose of it in wood
chippers or at transfer stations -- both costly and time-consuming
options.
</P>
<P>
   Fire marshals complained because the law required them to issue
all burning permits. Many municipalities had relied on local
burning officials to handle the paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill scouts, campers and school groups would be able
to hold campfires and bonfires without permits as long as they are
conducted safely.
</P>
<P>
   Fire marshals would still have to issue permits for commercial
burning, such as at landfills, but municipalities could appoint
local officials to approve fires by farmers and homeowners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
