<HEADLINE> Lawmaker pulls amendment to derail mall  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Legislative opponents to the proposed New
Haven mall say they will now look to the courts to block the
construction project.
</P>
<P>
   After about 45 minutes of debate Wednesday in the House, Rep.
James Amann yanked an amendment intended to repeal $28 million in
state funding for the Galleria at Long Wharf.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris DePino, R-New Haven, who has rallied legislative
support for the mall, said he was confident the measure would have
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Amann said he withdrew the amendment after consulting with
lawyers for Westfield America, the corporate owner of malls in
Milford, Trumbull, Meriden and Enfield. Westfield has argued that a
mall in New Haven will suck too much money from their shopping
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Amann said it was ''premature'' to push the amendment with about
a dozen court cases pending against the mall construction project.
Most of the lawsuits are being paid for by Westfield.
</P>
<P>
   Amann and other anti-mall lawmakers said they won't hesitate
bringing out another amendment to stop the project.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Moira Lyons, D-Stamford, said she won't allow
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not bringing it up again,'' Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   A Superior Court judge ruled last week that the state Office of
Policy and Management cannot issue it's final approval for the
project until he decides whether there should be a new public
hearing on the proposed mall.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can't take a victory in the Legislature, it's just as
sweet to have a victory in the courts,'' Amann said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the state's Freedom of Information Commission last week
said New Haven failed to disclose documents concerning the project.
</P>
<P>
   A measure to repeal the state funding for the mall failed in the
House last year on a 89-59 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the $500 million dollar mall say it will create
about 3,000 construction jobs and generate more tax dollars for the
state and greater New Haven economies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Galleria will give people a chance to work,'' said Rep.
John Martinez, D-New Haven. '' It's an opportunity we must not play
around with. We can't offer people hope and then try to take it
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mall opponents say it will hurt business in downtown New Haven
and surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also argue that the mall, which is to be built near
the intersection of Interstates 95 and 91, will create traffic and
pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will end downtown New Haven as a vibrant economic
center,'' Amann said. ''We should not be using tax dollars to
benefit one community at the expense of another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
