<HEADLINE> Pat Buchanan campaigns in Connecticut for Reform Party bid  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) -- Pat Buchanan, the front-runner for the
Reform Party's presidential nomination, says he hopes to follow
Arizona Sen. John McCain's lead in attracting voters to a maverick
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, best known as the conservative co-host of CNN's
''Crossfire'' show, left the Republican Party last year to seek the
Reform Party's nomination. The party founded by Ross Perot has been
plagued by infighting in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference in Trumbull Wednesday, Buchanan
said he thinks he can win the party's nomination and go on to mount
a credible campaign to create a competitive three-way race for the
presidency with the Democrats and the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our objective, quite frankly, is to win the presidency of the
United States,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes the Reform Party's problems were largely
resolved this week when a federal judge upheld the chairmanship of
Pat Choate, Ross Perot's 1996 presidential running mate. The ruling
ended a tug-of-war that had weakened the party's standing in the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who visited Connecticut as part of a four-day campaign
swing through New England, said he would emphasize the
''re-industrialization'' of America by opposing what he called
unfair trade agreements with China and Mexico that have sent
American jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he thought he would have wide appeal in
Connecticut and other states where McCain won primaries by running
as a non-establishment candidate. But he acknowledged that his
reputation as a conservative would probably not translate well
among some voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're a liberal Republican and you're doing very well,
you're probably not going to vote for Pat Buchanan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan left the GOP last year after party leaders gave their
early endorsement to Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was scheduled to attend a $100-per-person fund-raisier
in Stratford Wednesday night at Knapp's Landing restaurant.
</P>
</TEXT>
