<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska by Snowmobile an Adventure  </HEADLINE>
By KARREN MILLS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- As an experienced snowmobiler, 79-year-old
Edgar Hetteen didn't give it much thought when he hopped off his
machine and broke through the crusted Alaska snow.
</P>
<P>
   But he kept sinking.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had stepped off and stepped into this bottomless quagmire. I
was in up to my armpits and I had not reached bottom yet,'' Hetteen
recalled Wednesday. A fellow traveler hauled him out, and he
resumed his 900-mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   Hetteen and nine companions spent eight days this month
retracing the route he took 40 years ago in an effort to save his
young company, which was making the first modern snowmobile. The
trip helped transform winter travel in northern climates.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people Hetteen met on the first trip were still
living in the Alaskan wilderness when he returned.
</P>
<P>
   ''Forty years ago, we saw dozens and dozens of dog teams hauling
supplies and people,'' he said. ''This time there was only one dog
team in evidence and I believe that was for recreational purposes
only.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I saw was the people taking their children to school on
the snowmobile, bigger children driving their own machines,
machines going down the river hauling supplies,'' Hetteen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was less work, more production per hour. That was a
highly gratifying thing for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, when Hetteen and three companions made their first trip
from Bethel to Fairbanks, their early snowmobiles were the first
mechanical surface transportation ever to cross anywhere in the
state of Alaska. Hetteen made that trip to prove the snow machines
worked and save Polaris, the company he co-founded.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hetteen left Polaris years ago, he convinced the
company -- now the world's largest manufacturer of snowmobiles -- to
retrace the trip that proved the snowmobile was more than just a
goofy machine.
</P>
<P>
   This time, David Johnson, 77, Hetteen's brother-in-law and the
inventor of the early snowmobile, also made the trip. Polaris used
the adventure to officially launch its new marketing campaign, and
chief executive Tom Tiller made the trek.
</P>
<P>
   Tiller said he was overwhelmed by the hospitality of the Alaskan
people, who met the group as they arrived in each of the small
villages, fed them and gave them a place to spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   ''They treated us like celebrities,'' he said. ''We went into
the schools and talked to the kids about safety in snowmobiling and
afterward they would get our autographs for an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the children had never seen a snowmobile helmet, Hetteen
said. Polaris is sending helmets to each school the group visited.
</P>
<P>
   People also were curious about how the two elderly men would
fare during the long trip. Very well, thank you, said Hetteen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't feel any different at the completion of this trip
physically than I did at the end of the trip 40 years ago,'' he
said. ''I had a supply of Tums, Mylanta and Pepsid AC with me. I
forgot to use any of them on the whole trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Hetteen traveled the final two miles into Fairbanks aboard one
of the original Sno-Traveler machines, providing dramatic evidence
of the changes in snowmobiles over 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good thing it was short because the machine was not in
very good mechanical condition,'' he said. ''The crowd paid very
little attention to the old machine and that's great. New, shiny
technology, that's the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Polaris site on trek:
http://www.polarisindustries.com/Alaska/home.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharpton, Haitian-Americans press Justice for NYPD monitor  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Angry at the shooting of another unarmed black
man by New York City police, the Rev. Al Sharpton and leaders of
the Haitian-American community called on members of Congress to put
pressure on the Justice Department to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ''How many people have to die before the federal government
comes in and protects the lives of the citizens of the city of New
York?'' Sharpton asked at a meeting at the Capitol on Wednesday
with more than a dozen members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The group is calling for the Justice Department to speed up its
probe of the New York Police Department, launched more than two
years ago after the brutal attack by police on Abner Louima in the
bathroom of a Brooklyn station house. In the interim, it wants an
emergency federal monitor to oversee the NYPD.
</P>
<P>
   The call for federal action comes after the March 16 shooting of
Patrick Dorismond, the fourth fatal shooting of an unarmed black
man by officers in the city in 13 months. Dorismond was shot after
a scuffle with cops who approached the 26-year-old off-duty
security guard outside a Manhattan bar asking if he knew where to
buy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The city has practically declared war on our community,'' said
Vladimir Rodney, an attorney with the Brooklyn-based
Haitian-American Alliance. Louima is also Haitian-American.
</P>
<P>
   The Dorismond shooting came amid heightened tensions between
police and minorities in the wake of the acquittal of four officers
who killed unarmed West African immigrant Amadou Diallo in a hail
of 41 bullets.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 law allows the Justice Department to sue over an alleged
pattern of civil rights violations by a police department. The
Justice Department's Civil Rights Division and the U.S. Attorney's
Office in Brooklyn are currently in negotiations with the Giuliani
administration over the findings of their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Louima's lawyer, Sanford Rubenstein, said the time lapsed
has made clear ''that these negotiations have not been
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We need the Justice Department task force to move to the next
step,'' Rubenstein said. If negotiations fail, the Justice
Department can file a lawsuit against a municipality, forcing it to
change police patterns and practices.
</P>
<P>
   Such a lawsuit was recently filed against Columbus, Ohio, after
the city and the police refused to cooperate. The Justice
Department accused police in Columbus of roughing up citizens and
falsely arresting people who witnessed police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   In the two other cities where the Justice Department has
intervened -- Steubenville, Ohio and Pittsburgh -- consent agreements
have been reached. The cities promised to correct problems in the
training, supervision and discipline of officers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gregory Meeks, chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus'
task force on police brutality, said Wednesday he would write to
the Justice Department demanding it send in a monitor to oversee
the NYPD and release its findings on the NYPD. The findings of the
Justice probe have been kept confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Meeks, D-Queens, said he also wanted a meeting with Attorney
General Janet Reno. After the Diallo verdict, Sharpton, Meeks and
others met with Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, Reno's top
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is considering whether to file federal
civil rights charges against the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokeswoman Kara Peterman said she could not
comment on the probe into the NYPD but said any requests or views
from members of Congress would be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office did not immediately return a phone
call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
