<HEADLINE> N.J. Hoteliers Kicking Sand  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE MAY, N.J. (AP) -- At the Heritage Inn, a beach tag is one of
the amenities. It comes with the room, just like the color TV, the
refrigerator and daily maid service.
</P>
<P>
   The tag costs owner Barbara Bednar $13, but she provides one to
every hotel guest. When a guest checks out, the tag is passed to
another guest so that they, too, can use the beaches at the
southern tip of New Jersey without buying a tag.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true at the Marquis de Lafayette Hotel, the
Avondale-by-the-Sea and dozens of other hotels, motels and
bed-and-breakfast inns here.
</P>
<P>
   ''We always gave them to our guests,'' says George Loper,
president of the Cape May Hotel and Motel Association. ''It was the
one thing they got free. It gave them a friendlier feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the city wants to charge businesses or their out-of-town
guests more money to use the beaches. And, like any break with
tradition in this picturesque Victorian-themed seaside resort, the
proposal is ruffling some feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are not going to be happy when they hear this,'' said
Herb Weiner, who runs the 46-united Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to fill a $100,000 to $200,000 budget gap for
guarding, cleaning and maintaining beaches, city officials
announced in January that they would begin enforcing a little-known
provision of the 1977 ordinance governing beach tags -- to wit: that
the tags are non-transferable.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Mayor Jerry Gaffney says, was to make beachgoers pay
their fair share for upkeep of the beaches, which costs the city
more than $1 million a year and has run at a deficit for the last
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the beachgoers are out-of-town visitors, and
many of them get beach tags for free when they rent a room, Gaffney
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is it fair that you and I buy a tag and use it 10 or 20 times
a year but a hotel buys one and turns it over 100 times?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without some new revenue source, the deficit in the beach fund
would be made up with money from the general fund, he said. If that
happened, full-time residents would, in effect, be paying twice to
bail out beaches that out-of-town visitors are using, Gaffney said.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged hotel and motel owners said enforcing the ban on
transferred tags would force them to stop giving them to guests.
Some hotels include the promise of free beach tags in their
pamphlets and don't want to have to renege.
</P>
<P>
   ''I spent $4,000 a year on beach tags. If they make them
non-transferable or raise the price too much, it would be
cost-prohibitive for me,'' said Tracy Holder, general manager of
the Marquis de Lafayette Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The ruckus sent city officials back to the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they want to establish a special class of tag for
businesses and rewrite the ordinance to make all tags transferable.
The ''commercial tag,'' for any buyer who rents rooms out, would
cost between $18 and $25 and would be transferable.
</P>
<P>
   Cape May residents would still be able to share their tags with
relatives, visitors or other guests.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't care if you have 27 cousins and 16 uncles,'' said the
mayor. ''But if you rent three or four rooms out, that's a
different story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
