<HEADLINE> Atrial Fibrillation Drug Lauded  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- The drug Cordarone is twice as effective as two
other widely prescribed medicines at treating atrial fibrillation,
a common heart flutter, researchers reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2 million Americans are estimated to have atrial
fibrillation, a condition in which the two small upper chambers of
the heart quiver instead of beating effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Former Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley was
treated for the condition during his campaign. Its major hazard is
an increased risk of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In a study in today's New England Journal of Medicine, Canadian
doctors found Cordarone holds a ''striking'' advantage over two
other rhythm-protecting medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Denis Roy and others from the Montreal Heart Institute
tested low doses of Cordarone, which is also known as amiodarone,
against the drugs sotalol and propafenone in 403 patients. After 16
months of follow-up, atrial fibrillation had recurred in one-third
getting Cordarone, compared with two-thirds getting the other
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that our results challenge the notion that
amiodarone should be used only in patients whose conditions are
resistant to other drugs,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The study was financed by the Medical Research Council of
Canada. Cordarone is made by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories. Sotalol,
also called Betapace, is made by Berlex Laboratories, while
propafenone, or Rhythmol, is made by Knoll Pharmaceutical Co.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: New England Journal of Medicine site:
http://www.nejm.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
