<HEADLINE> Rep. Gephardt Changes Ballot Name  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT CHARTON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Mind the name-calling in this race.
</P>
<P>
   It's Gebhardt vs. Gephardt in a Missouri congressional primary
that has House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt accusing Republicans
of dirty tricks.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-term St. Louis congressman, whose name is Richard A.
Gephardt, drew a Democratic primary challenge on the last day of
filing from Richard A. Gebhardt, a 65-year-old political newcomer
from St. Peters near Gephardt's home base of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Gephardt, who hopes to become speaker of the House
if the Democrats regain control, to submit paperwork changing his
ballot name to ''Richard A. (Dick) Gephardt.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the name by which I have been known since childhood.
Furthermore, I wish to avoid any confusion caused by others who
wish to mislead and confuse voters,'' Gephardt wrote on his
name-change paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Gebhardt on Monday entered the race for the
Democratic nomination in the Second District. But he switched the
next day to the Third District, giving Gephardt his only opposition
in the Aug. 8 primary. Residency in a congressional district is not
a requirement to run.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday why he changed races, Gebhardt said he would
rather file against Gephardt ''than the people over in the
Second.''
</P>
<P>
   Gebhardt wouldn't answer other questions, saying he hadn't slept
much in weeks and was grieving about two recent deaths in his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''Goodbye, have a nice day,'' he told a reporter. ''I'm not
trying to be cute, I'm just trying to get my wits back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and other Missouri Democrats said Gebhardt appeared to
be better known to Republicans than Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   GOP activists said Gebhardt often attended Republican meetings
in St. Charles County, and the publisher of a GOP publication said
Gebhardt requested his mailing address be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have faith in the democratic process and think that the
voters will see through the Republicans' dirty tricks,'' Gephardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Republican Party chairwoman Ann Wagner denied the state
GOP engineered Gebhardt's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never spoken with or met or heard of Richard A.
Gebhardt,'' Wagner said. ''We do not file shill candidates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
