<HEADLINE> Blueberries May Get Council  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The watermelon has one. Peanuts do too. Even
the mushroom, a fungus no matter how you slice it, has a national
research and promotion board dedicated to its economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Now the blueberry may gain a national advocate of its own.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,200 blueberry producers and importers were eligible to
vote this month in a referendum on whether to create a new,
industry-funded U.S.A. Blueberry Council. Ballots were due Friday
to the Agriculture Department, which will announce the results
within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan accounts for 41 percent of the U.S. blueberry crop,
according to the North American Blueberry Council. New Jersey is
second with 22 percent, followed by Oregon with 13 percent, Georgia
with 7 percent and North Carolina and Washington with 5 percent
each.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. cultivated blueberry production was an estimated 83,300
tons in 1997, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan Blueberry Growers Association and the New Jersey
Blueberry Industry Advisory Council have endorsed creating a
national council.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel there's a whole world out there that may not know the
blueberry story, the health benefits of blueberries,'' said Art
Galletta, a co-owner of Atlantic Blueberry Company in Hammonton,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He cited recent research that indicates eating blueberries may
improve short-term memory, restore coordination and fight a variety
of health problems including heart disease and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Many blueberry producers already pay voluntary dues to the North
American Blueberry Council. The national council, if approved,
would charge mandatory assessments to all domestic producers as
well as foreign producers who ship blueberries to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The new council would collect some $1.1 million a year. Its
mission, according to the agriculture department, would be to
''develop and finance an effective and coordinated program of
promotion, research and information to maintain and expand the
markets for cultivated blueberries.''
</P>
<P>
   North America is the world's leading producer of blueberries,
which is one of only three fruits native to the continent, the
others being the Concord grape and the cranberry.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) -- Researchers want to know how pesticides
affect the health of Iowa farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this spring, farmers from 12 Iowa counties will be
recruited for medical tests -- such as providing urine samples -- to
help University of Iowa researchers measure their exposure to
pesticides. The farmers' spouses and children may be asked to
provide samples as well.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, who will be paid for their participation, also will be
asked to show researchers how they handle and apply pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the generous cooperation of some local farm families, we
may be able to learn more about how pesticide exposure occurs and
what we can do to prevent it,'' said Steve Reynolds, associate
professor of occupational and environmental health.
</P>
<P>
   The study was created to expand on the Agricultural Health Study
now being conducted in North Carolina and Iowa. More than 50,000 of
the 90,000 or so participants live in Iowa.
</P>
</TEXT>
