<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumer says OPEC action may not be enough to lower gas prices  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If crude oil prices don't fall in the next few
weeks, says Sen. Charles Schumer, he'll call for the United States
to dip into its strategic oil reserves to help accomplish that
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer warned on Wednesday that oil-producing nations' release
of more crude oil may not be enough to bring down gas prices this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is no time for celebration. I don't think we've done the
job yet,'' Schumer, D-N.Y., said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he would wait a few weeks to see how the market
reacts to Tuesday's announcement by The Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries that it would increase production by 6.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Spot prices for oil dropped a dollar to $26.17 a barrel
Wednesday on the New York Mercantile Exchange, declining from a
high of $34 a few weeks ago in anticipation of the OPEC production
increases. U.S. officials expected crude prices to continue
dropping, perhaps by as much as $2.50 a barrel by August, and said
they expected gasoline prices to follow the price decline.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said crude prices should ideally dip to between $20 and
$25 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   He has for months urged the Clinton administration to dip into
the oil reserves, citing concerns over the high costs of heating
oil in New York. Forty-three percent of New York households use oil
for heat -- more than any other state. Prices skyrocketed over the
winter as OPEC cut down on production and cold weather blanketed
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer and Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, have introduced
legislation to make it easier to access oil in the reserves. The
Clinton administration has been reluctant to use the reserves,
saying they are intended for emergencies, not price controls.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC agreed Tuesday to increase production by 1.7 million
barrels a day and other producers were expected to expand
production as well to fill a 2-million-barrel-a-day shortfall that
has tripled crude prices in the past 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, normally a close ally of the president, has been highly
critical of what he sees as the administration's slow action on the
oil-price issue. He said he first contacted the White House and
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson in September.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they could have been doing more earlier,'' Schumer
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the potential for high gas prices this summer, Republicans
have proposed a rollback of the federal 18.4-cent gasoline tax by
4.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he needed more information before he could endorse
such a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have anything against giving some temporary relief
when the prices are high, but I have some questions that haven't
been answered yet,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 0121 </TRAILER>
