<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soc. Security Mistakes Common  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Memo to taxpayers: Double-check the Social
Security numbers on those income tax forms. And don't forget the
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants and the Internal Revenue Service say mistaken or
missing Social Security numbers are the most common errors people
make, even more likely for taxpayers who are rushing to meet this
year's April 17 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Warren, a tax accounting instructor at Millsaps College
in Jackson, Miss., and Richard Davis, an accounting professor at
Susquehanna University in Selinsgrove, Pa., are both former IRS
officials who have compiled lists of the top mistakes and myths
encountered by taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Their No. 1 myth: People believe that tax law is an exact
science with yes-or-no answers to every question.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tax law is subject to interpretation based on factual
situations,'' Warren said. ''Always establish the facts first and
then ask the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   To the IRS, Social Security numbers are the coin of the realm --
they establish a taxpayer's identity and those of any dependents.
Taxpayers often transpose numbers or forget to let the Social
Security Administration know when a woman marries and changes her
name, which can lead to a computer mismatch that raises a red flag
at the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   People also frequently fail to put a child's Social Security
number on the forms, which is needed to claim a dependent
exemption, a child care credit or the earned income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, out of roughly 125 million returns, the IRS got
nearly 1.7 million with a Social Security mistake. ''That's the top
math error we see,'' agency spokesman Don Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS will notify taxpayers about the mistake and allow it to
be corrected over the phone, but it can slow down a refund.
</P>
<P>
   Other frequent tax errors:
</P>
<P>
   --Making math miscalculations, particularly among lower-income
people who claim the complicated earned income tax credit. For
taxpayers who are not using a computer or a tax professional, Davis
and Warren say careful double-checking of the math is essential.
</P>
<P>
   --Forgetting to sign and date the tax return. If a joint return
is being filed, both spouses must sign even if one had no income to
report.
</P>
<P>
   --Failing to attach all the proper paperwork, such as a W-2 form.
</P>
<P>
   --Reporting income in the wrong place. For example, many people
report earnings from money market funds as interest when the IRS
can consider them a dividend. ''The IRS computer will think that
you underreported your income in the amount of the missing
dividends -- and you will be receiving unwanted mail,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   --Unnecessarily declaring a state tax refund from last year as
income. It is not.
</P>
<P>
   People also believe a number of myths about tax law and what
happens when they file their tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, people frequently delay filing a tax return past
the April deadline because they believe they must have all the
money in hand before the paperwork can go to the IRS. In fact, a
taxpayer should always file the return as soon as possible to avoid
penalties, although interest will be charged on the amount due.
</P>
<P>
   ''Willful failure to file a return is a federal crime,'' Davis
warned.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS also has a number of options now for people who cannot
pay, such as payment over the telephone by credit card and easily
approved installment agreements. Sometimes taking out a loan is
better than paying IRS interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Some other tax myths:
</P>
<P>
   --''People who owe zero taxes don't need to file.'' Not
necessarily, because workers who had taxes withheld from their
paychecks may be due a refund.
</P>
<P>
   --''The IRS can go back many years to audit my returns.'' The
statute of limitations is three years, unless fraud is involved.
</P>
<P>
   --''I must do whatever the IRS tells me, even if I disagree.''
Taxpayers can request a meeting with IRS managers to contest an
agent's conclusion, take their case to the Taxpayer Advocate or the
agency's appeals process. The U.S. Tax Court is another avenue for
taxpayers to bring disputes with the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   --''I got a refund, so I know the IRS won't audit me.'' A refund
is not a sign that the IRS agrees with a tax return, only that the
math is correct. An audit can still occur within three years.
</P>
<P>
   --''Child support payments are tax deductible.'' Not so. Alimony
payments are, however, and the recipient has to declare them as
income.
</P>
<P>
   --''Single people living together can file a joint tax return.''
Couples must be married to file jointly. In fact, if each partner
has roughly the same income filing jointly could trigger the
''marriage penalty'' that forces them to pay higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   IRS: http://www.irs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
