<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Blames Assad on Peace Terms  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton says Israel has offered to
relinquish a ''significant'' portion of the contested Golan Heights
while Syrian President Hafez Assad is simply stonewalling on terms
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough that Assad say, ''I don't like your position''
and demand all the land Syria lost in the 1967 Middle East war,
Clinton said Wednesday at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once you know what the other side wants and you don't think
you can do it, then you ought to come up with some alternative way
of trying to respond to the underlying concerns that are behind the
position,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who made no headway in a three-hour meeting Sunday with
Assad in Geneva, was sympathetic to Assad's territorial demands.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, if the Syrian president disagreed with Israel's
''quite significant'' territorial proposal, ''then there should be
some other proposal, I think, coming from the Syrians about how
their concerns could be handled.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Israeli Embassy here, spokesman Mark Regev said Israel
''wants to make a deal with Syria and has presented positions to
the Americans that are designed to make the process work.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's truly a pity,'' Regev said, ''that the Syrian leadership
up 'till now has not demonstrated a similarly practical approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's public criticism of Assad's strategy was unusually
pointed, although he praised the Syrian leader as well as Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak as being committed to reaching a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had suggested ways for Assad to respond to
Israel's offer, but his overtures were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we're going to have a negotiation, it takes two people
coming up with ideas, or three sides in this case,'' Clinton said,
noting the U.S. role as mediator.
</P>
<P>
   He then went on to praise Barak as wanting to resolve the
impasse in peacemaking and said, ''I think President Assad would
like to resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between Israel and Syria hosted by the Clinton
administration in Shepherdstown, W.Va., broke down in mid-January.
Through back-channel diplomacy and then in the Geneva meeting,
Clinton and his advisers tried to reopen the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The failure in Geneva wound up an overseas trip in which the
president suffered several setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In South Asia, both India and Pakistan refused to reverse their
nuclear weapons programs, and Pakistan's military leaders refused
even to promise restoration of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The setbacks were then compounded when Clinton was unable to
narrow differences between Syria and Israel and get the talks
reopened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0142 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov Engler Looks To Boost Influence  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michigan Gov. John Engler has a new political
action committee and has given thousands of dollars to candidates
for federal office, an indication that the Republican is trying to
boost his national profile and influence.
</P>
<P>
   Without fanfare, the Governor Engler Leadership Fund was
established last July. It collected $77,450 from 61 donors in its
first six months, with 46 contributions coming from people living
outside Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The PAC allows Engler to give up to $5,000 to a candidate --
rather than the $1,000 per election he is limited to as an
individual -- and pay for his travel for appearances for various
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Engler has donated only $4,000 from his PAC -- $1,000
each to Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush; former
Virginia Gov. George Allen, who is running for the Senate; Sen.
Spencer Abraham, R-Mich.; and Michigan state Sen. Mike Rogers, who
is seeking a House seat.
</P>
<P>
   Engler spokesman John Truscott said the governor is looking for
other GOP candidates to help.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to very carefully scrutinize where we give the
money,'' Truscott said. ''It will be in targeted races. It will be
in close races.''
</P>
<P>
   Engler, whose third and final term as governor expires in 2002,
was an early Bush supporter and is one of the Texas governor's
''Pioneers'' -- individuals who have raised $100,000 for him.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since the time Bush entered the race, Engler has been
mentioned as a potential running mate or Cabinet member, and the
PAC's existence raises speculation that Engler wants to boost his
visibility to make himself more appealing to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he raises a lot of money and helps a lot of people and does
a lot of things behind the scenes, that door is always open,'' said
Ed Sarpolus of EPIC/MRA, a Lansing, Mich., polling firm. ''The
question is whether Governor Engler will get a plum position in the
Bush administration or a lemon.''
</P>
<P>
   Truscott repeated the frequent denial that Engler is looking to
join Bush's ticket or serve elsewhere in a Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how ardently he can say that,'' Truscott said.
''He wants to put Governor Bush in the White House because he knows
he would be a great president, not because he wants to be a Cabinet
member.''
</P>
<P>
   Many governors have created leadership funds for state
candidates, but federal PACs are rare, according to Larry Makinson,
executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan group that studies money and campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Other governors who have formed PACs that support federal
candidates include New York Gov. George Pataki, former Illinois
Gov. Jim Thompson and former New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, all
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   David Rohde, a Michigan State University political science
professor, said leadership PACs began as fund-raising tools for
federal candidates, but are becoming more common for other
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is just another way for people who want to be
players at the national level to try to have an influence on
elections and build ties to people who may want to help them later
on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Engler ''may or may not want to be a candidate for president or
vice president, but he sure wants to be a player on the national
level.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
