<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Badgers' Bryant Enjoying Success  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Jon Bryant is thoroughly enjoying every
unlikely event in his unlikely basketball career.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin Badgers' success in the NCAA tournament has been
improbable, perhaps even more so because of the man leading them to
victory against college basketball's established powers and
collective wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, a Division II transfer who was in the midst of an
inconsistent and low-scoring senior season, has suddenly become a
star.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's my dream,'' Bryant said. ''It's incredible that we're
getting ready to play in the Final Four. You think about stuff like
this, but deep down you probably think it will never happen. I'm
just glad I'm helping the team more than I was earlier in the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant helped beat Fresno State with a career-best seven
3-pointers, including four on four straight possessions, then hit
three more and had 12 points in Wisconsin's upset of top-seeded
Arizona in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   He followed those performances with two more good offensive
games, which were complemented by an increasing role in the team's
defense. Bryant scored 16 points in the upset of fourth-seeded LSU
and hit five 3-pointers on the way to 18 points in the Badgers'
West Regional final victory over Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's pretty unlikely, but that's the way our team works,''
Bryant said. ''On any day, any one of us can be the star and take
the big shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Expected to be one of the team's offensive leaders before the
season began, Bryant averaged just 7.3 points during the regular
season and shot just 36 percent, prompting coach Dick Bennett to
move him in and out of the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   His 3-point shot, Bryant's specialty, betrayed him regularly. He
was 4-of-9 in a 15-point loss at Penn State, then 1-of-6 in a loss
at Ohio State two weeks later. By the time the Big Ten tournament
rolled around, he was getting limited playing time, getting just
five minutes in Wisconsin's quarterfinal victory over Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't what was expected from Bryant, who starred at St.
Cloud (Minn.) State before transferring to Madison because he
thought he would fit well in Bennett's system. It took two years to
convince Bennett of that fact; he turned down Bryant's transfer
request as a freshman in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was probably good for me,'' Bryant said. ''It gave me a
chance to keep working on my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Plymouth, Minn., Bryant became a fan of Bennett's
overachieving teams at Wisconsin-Green Bay, where Bennett coached
from 1985-95. When the Phoenix engineered an astonishing upset of
Jason Kidd-led California in the 1994 NCAA tournament, Bryant
cheered them on.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as one of Wisconsin's two seniors, Bryant is a part of just
such a substance-over-style affair. He doesn't hesitate to admit he
didn't think the Badgers could get this far.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, had Bryant known how well he would be playing, he
might have had a different opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I could play at Wisconsin and help the team out, but
I never thought we'd get to the Final Four, to be honest with
you,'' Bryant said. ''I guess I can't really describe my
feelings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0220 </TRAILER>
