<DOCNO> APW20000330.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Billy Ball Captures Florida  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- The casual observers see what they want
to see.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those people say Florida and coach Billy Donovan are all
about running, pressing and hoisting up 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   On closer inspection, it's clear that's only half the story.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Donovan believes Florida can succeed only if it sets the
tempo and uses its depth to wear down opponents. But the number of
long-range bombs has gone down, while production in the middle has
risen since 1996, when Donovan took over a team that mentor Rick
Pitino declared ''bankrupt of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   And Donovan disagrees with the theory that Billy Ball is simply
a matter of the young coach rolling the ball out there and letting
his young, talented players freelance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really wish people would take the time to try to understand
our system,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   But the misperception could be part of the method.
</P>
<P>
   Because, just when a team thinks it's in a 40-minute endurance
contest of racehorse basketball, the Gators can change.
</P>
<P>
   Duke found out last week. After running with the Blue Devils for
35 minutes, Donovan called off the press. He backed the Gators into
a zone, something they executed quite well, and dared Duke to shoot
3-pointers. The result: Florida finished with an 18-4 run and won
87-78. Duke shot 3-for-19 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happened in the regional final against Oklahoma
State. When Florida got tired and needed to slow it down and start
pounding inside, it could do so and do so effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ''The perception is that we just hoist up 3-point shots and let
them go from all over the place,'' Donovan says. ''But we're down
in attempts. And that's because of the strength of our guys up
front.''
</P>
<P>
   The centers, sophomore Udonis Haslem and freshman Donnell
Harvey, help the Gators tick from the outside in a way they didn't
when Donovan first arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Fail to respect the big men and they have shown they can score.
Double-team them, and they can kick it outside to guards Teddy
Dupay or Brett Nelson, both of whom shoot better than 41 percent
from behind the arc.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of offensive plays that we execute very
well,'' said Harvey, who averages 10 points and seven rebounds.
''We all get touches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators have gone from an average of 23 3-point attempts a
game the last three years to 19 this season. Instead of one true
center last year, the Gators have two.
</P>
<P>
   Haslem averages 11.4 points, and production in the middle has
climbed by about 10 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're more than just a run-and-gun offense,'' Harvey said.
''That's just what people see the most.''
</P>
<P>
   The system, Donovan says, is more difficult to coach than the
slow, plodding styles because there are so many more risks
involved.
</P>
<P>
   If the fast break is run incorrectly, there goes an easy scoring
chance, something not acceptable in this style of play. If the
press breaks down, the other team gets an easy basket when baskets
are hard to come by, especially at this point in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's much more room for error,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   But now, there's something to fall back on. It's called an
inside game, or a zone defense, and it often takes both opponents
and fans by surprise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0220 </TRAILER>
