<DOCNO> APW20000330.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Wants To Sweeten Tax Relief  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans are proposing to sweeten their
remedy for the tax code's penalty on married couples by giving some
extra help to people at the higher and lower ends of the income
scale.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee was scheduled today to begin
considering the marriage penalty legislation, which would consume
about $250 billion in projected budget surpluses over 10 years if
changes in the original bill are made.
</P>
<P>
   One proposed change, sought by GOP conservatives, would
gradually adjust the 28 percent tax rate so it applies to more of a
married couple's income, making the bracket twice that of single
filers. The original bill did the same thing only to the bottom 15
percent tax bracket, similar to the House-passed version.
</P>
<P>
   In current law, two people who are married pay income taxes at
higher rates in both the 15 percent and 28 percent brackets than
they would if they were single. About 25 million couples nationwide
are hit by the tax code's marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The other proposed change would raise the income cutoff by
$2,500 for lower-income couples who claim the earned income tax
credit, up from $2,000 in the original bill. This change was
suggested by Sen. Jim Jeffords of Vermont, a leading GOP moderate.
</P>
<P>
   The two changes, described by Senate aides on condition of
anonymity, would add $10 billion to the bill's cost over 10 years.
The House bill, which has drawn a veto threat from President
Clinton over its cost, carries a price tag of $182 billion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman and chief sponsor of the bill, Sen.
William Roth, R-Del., was expected to incorporate both of the GOP's
changes in an amendment, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Finance Committee were working on an
alternative by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York that would
eventually allow couples the choice of filing their income taxes as
singles or as a married couple. The change would be phased in
slowly to avoid a sudden drain on the budget surplus. It still
would cost an estimated $150 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats were pushing for an amendment that would further
increase the income cutoff for couples who claim the earned income
tax credit and allow the lower-earning spouse to claim a tax credit
of up to $500 as a way of offsetting the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Committee: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)finance
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0220 </TRAILER>
