<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Students Rally Behind Michigan St.  </HEADLINE>
By DEE-ANN DURBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- The party was still going on at
Michigan State, with hundreds of fans rallying behind the
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom Izzo already was planning for the next celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ''Get all your homework done, because next Tuesday afternoon I
plan on being here celebrating,'' Izzo told the students crowded
into Jenison Field House for a send-off rally Wednesday, shortly
before the team departed for the NCAA Final Four in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans, making their second straight Final Four
appearance, need to beat Wisconsin on Saturday to make it to their
first national championship game since Magic Johnson led the
Spartans to the title 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans' confidence is understandable: Michigan State
already has beaten Wisconsin three times this season and is playing
in its second consecutive Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   During the 45-minute rally, the pep band played the school fight
song, cheerleaders performed and the crowd waved green and white
pompons. Team members threw miniature green-and-white basketballs
into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to tell you that we've tried to represent the
school as best we could,'' Izzo said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've been behind us this whole time,'' said guard Mateen
Cleaves, one of the seniors who spoke to the crowd. ''I just want
to ask you to stay behind us two more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Acker, a sophomore studio art major, spent the afternoon
making a large charcoal drawing of Cleaves. Acker could barely
contain his excitement as he thrust the drawing into the air.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm screaming like a little schoolgirl,'' he said. ''My
prediction is Florida and us, and we're taking 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida plays North Carolina in Saturday's other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Nicholson, a senior trumpet player with the team's pep
band, said he's certain the Spartans will win this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're all seniors, and this is their year,'' said Nicholson,
a history major from Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   After the rally the team boarded a bus and headed to the airport
for the flight to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration, while scaled down, continued when the Spartans
reached Indianapolis. As they walked into the lobby of the team
hotel, a high school band from Brownburg, Ind., was playing the
Michigan State fight song.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the players seemed to have had enough. Most got their
keys and headed quietly to their rooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
