<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Talks Oil at News Conference  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calling the inflated price of gasoline ''a
sobering experience for the American people,'' President Clinton
says he hopes Congress will now take seriously his plans for
developing alternative fuels and energy-saving technology.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference Wednesday, Clinton urged oil companies to
quickly convert OPEC's increased oil production into lower prices
at the gas pump, and said he doubts Congress would repeal the
4.3-cent-a-gallon gasoline tax he helped push to passage in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He pressed lawmakers to renew his authority over the oil
stockpile in the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, which expires Friday.
And while he called for action on his energy proposals, he
deflected criticisms that he hasn't been aggressive enough in
trying to prod Americans to consider alternative fuels either.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, maybe not, but I've done a lot more than the Congress
has,'' Clinton said. ''I hope this has been a sobering experience
for the American people and for all of us, and that we can now do
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke during a wide-ranging news conference in the White
House East Room, his second this year. He discussed serious matters
-- New York police shootings, trade with China -- and irreverent
ones: the possibility of paternity leave for British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, and whether the five Oscars won by the dark satire
''American Beauty'' means Hollywood is ignoring his call to abandon
violent images.
</P>
<P>
   ''I certainly don't believe that movie glorified violence,''
Clinton said. He even made light of National Rifle Association
President Charlton Heston's TV ads criticizing his stance on gun
control: ''I still think Charlton Heston's a great actor and I
enjoy watching his movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was ''as appalled as the next person'' when he
learned his 1996 campaign had accepted illegal contributions from
foreigners. ''We didn't need it to win, it was wrong, and we did
everything we could to try to correct it and set it right,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He railed against a campaign finance system that requires
lawmakers to go out and raise cash, rather than devote that time to
passing laws or spending time with their families. ''It wears them
out, and I worry about them. I really believe that Congress would
function better if they didn't have to spend this much time
(fund-raising).''
</P>
<P>
   On other matters, Clinton said:
</P>
<P>
   --His proposal before Congress to allow China entry into the
World Trade Organization is ''a hundred-to-nothing deal for
America'' that, if bypassed, would ensure that the rewards of open
trade go to Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   --Both Syria and Israel should develop ideas and resume talking
peace, especially since Syrian President Hafez Assad ''now knows in
great detail what the Israeli proposals were.''
</P>
<P>
   --Regardless of their ''personal chemistry,'' he hopes to have
the same type of warm relationship with new Russian President
Vladimir Putin that he had with Boris Yeltsin. ''The United States
and Russia have vast national interests that require them to work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   --Declined to discuss the police shooting deaths of three unarmed
black men in New York City -- which his wife, Hillary, has made an
issue against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in their Senate campaign. With
better training policies and ''consistent'' effort, he said, crime
can fall and community relations improve.
</P>
<P>
   ''The two things are not inconsistent,'' Clinton said. ''I think
I should say no more, particularly in view of the latest incident,
which was tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   --Said the Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old
Cuban boy enmeshed in an international custody case, should accept
the decision of federal courts should they order the boy returned
to his father in Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
