<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Visits Helms Turf  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Before the U.N. Security Council paid an
unprecedented visit to one of the world body's most ardent critics
in Congress, U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke decided to do a
little ground work.
</P>
<P>
   Would there be ''an ambush by anyone'' during the meeting today
with the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, chaired by Sen. Jesse
Helms?
</P>
<P>
   ''None that I know of,'' the committee's top Democrat, Sen.
Joseph Biden of Delaware, said he tried to assure Holbrooke by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a cordial visit seemed most likely, Biden suggested,
even though many frictions remain.
</P>
<P>
   In January, at Holbrooke's invitation, Helms became the first
U.S. lawmaker to address the Security Council. While he went
through a familiar litany of complaints about the organization,
Helms appeared to win over many delegates with his civility.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 council members later accepted Helms' invitation to come
to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's very much looking forward to their visit and he's glad
they're all coming,'' said Marc Thiessen, spokesman for the North
Carolina Republican. ''We began a very good dialogue up in New
York. He wanted to continue the dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council was beginning the visit with a brief
meeting at the State Department with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Also planned were a ''walking tour'' of the Capitol, a talk by
the Senate historian, an underground trolley ride to one of the
Senate office buildings, a luncheon, and a ''roundtable
discussion'' with Helms' committee.
</P>
<P>
   Council members were to meet with President Clinton at the White
House and attend a dinner with Albright as host.
</P>
<P>
   While ambassadors initially were skeptical about Helms'
invitation, they later seemed to warm up to it -- and see the visit
it as a good way to help mend frayed U.S.-U.N. relations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that this is so vital and important for the United
Nations that we cannot just brush this aside,'' said the current
Security Council president, Bangladesh Ambassador Anwarul
Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
   The council, he said, had to take ''the bull by the horns. If
there is a problem, we have to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Council members may use the occasion to try to press for more
installments on U.S. back dues. The United Nations puts the figure
at $1.7 billion but the United States calculates it at closer to $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year voted to pay $926 million of the arrears over
three years. The United States paid a $100 million installment late
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But to get the balance, the United Nations must meet about a
dozen conditions drafted by Helms and Biden. Those terms generally
have not been well received in New York.
</P>
<P>
   They include a reduction the U.S. share of the U.N. peacekeeping
budget from the current 31 percent to 25 percent and of the regular
budget from 25 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Helms has said the United Nations must also trim its spending
and not draw the United States into ''entangling alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian Ambassador Sergey Lavrov said Wednesday he bought his
plane ticket to Washington only after Albright also extended an
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   He and several other ambassadors stressed that the one-day visit
was not an official outing but rather a trip by individual
ambassadors, each invited personally by both Helms and Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ''It so happened that each of us decided that as individuals we
can spend a day in Washington and get away from this New York
boring routine,'' Lavrov said.
</P>
<P>
   Biden said Helms' visit to the United Nations in January and the
return visit by council members was part of a ''sea change'' in
attitudes in Congress toward the world body.
</P>
<P>
   ''The staunchest critics of the United Nations are now talking
about wanting to cooperate with the U.N.,'' Biden said. ''And not
just Helms.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The 'black helicopter' guys and the 'one-world government'
guys, all those folks, you're not hearing from them any more,''
Biden said. ''That used to be standard fare in every right-wing
speech.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
