<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Seeks New Life After Surgery  </HEADLINE>
By CRISTINE GONZALEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLACKAMAS, Ore. (AP) -- The higher the weighing scale read, the
lower Donna Treat felt. By last December, she was 575 pounds and at
rock bottom.
</P>
<P>
   A rare form of lymphedema, a disease that causes fluid to
accumulate in the body, had added 2-foot-long sacs to her hips.
Each weighed 100 pounds and were so heavy she could no longer walk.
Treat already had quit her job as a data-entry processor and sold
her car because she couldn't fit into it.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Treat made her first public appearance since a
hospital procedure took 165 pounds off her body. She now weighs 410
pounds and -- for the first time in years -- can see her knees.
</P>
<P>
   While she hopes the change will eventually restore a sense of
normalcy to her life, she realizes she may face a long journey.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy, but it was just one step in the process,'' said the
51-year-old woman, whose operation was on March 16. Before she was
taken to the hospital, Treat had not left her home for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   About 250,000 people in the United States have lymphedema,
according to the World Health Organization. Primary lymphedema can
be present at birth, or develop at puberty or in adulthood.
Secondary lymphedema can develop as a result of radiation,
infection or trauma. Women who have been treated for breast cancer
are particularly susceptible.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors do not know how Treat contracted the disease, but say
only about 1 percent of lymphedema cases are as severe as hers. The
cause of the disease is unknown, but doctors say it is not related
to eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   A team of 30 specialists gathered at Kaiser Permanente Sunnyside
Medical Center to devise a treatment program for Treat, who had
been confined to her bed. They began by draining excess fluid using
body compression and diuretics.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a sling created by a nurse at the medical
center, doctors compressed Treat's hips and posterior until the
liquid gravitated to the center of her body. There it was
reabsorbed by the lymphatic system and excreted as urine. (On one
day, Treat excreted 11 liters of urine. The average person passes
two liters a day.)
</P>
<P>
   Once Treat's weight dropped to 450 pounds, a 10-person team
performed the weight reduction surgery. Vascular and plastic
surgeons spent four hours removing the excess weight, making
incisions about 2 feet long from the back of her knees to her
buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   All told, they took out 40 pounds of lymph tissue, abnormal
skin, and small amounts of fat and blood.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seventy-five percent of what we did for her was before the
surgery,'' said Dr. Michael Schiedler, a vascular surgeon at the
center. ''The hardest part is next because she won't see a dramatic
improvement -- there's going to be a lot of waxing and waning.''
</P>
<P>
   Treat will spend the next few months in physical therapy to
rebuild muscles she hasn't used in months. Before she can walk,
she'll have to become strong enough to stand for longer periods of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Treat, a divorced mother, said she's up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of hours, she held court Wednesday in her hospital
room for reporters and photographers. On the wall was a banner
reading ''... but a shadow of her former self.''
</P>
<P>
   She showed off her latest accomplishment: Standing for a few
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a highly motivated person,'' she said with a smile. ''You
know, if you don't do it it's not going to get done, so the
question is, 'How bad do you want it?'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.lymphnet.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0225 </TRAILER>
