<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yagudin Ready at Skating Worlds  </HEADLINE>
By SALVATORE ZANCA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France (AP) -- After a bizarre start to the pairs
competition, it was time to get back to the original point of the
world championships -- skating, jumping and spinning.
</P>
<P>
   And there was no one better in the world to do that than Alexei
Yagudin.
</P>
<P>
   Yagudin seeks his third consecutive world title tonight in the
men's event at the World Skating Championships. After his virtuoso
performance in the short program on Tuesday, he was a clear
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Yagudin and his Russian rival and ex-training partner, Yevgeny
Plushchenko, are in a virtual head-to-head competition for the gold
medal.
</P>
<P>
   American Michael Weiss was in third with a small chance to win,
but it is essentially a winner-take-all contest between Yagudin and
Plushchenko.
</P>
<P>
   Russians Maria Petrova and Alexei Tikhonov won the pairs title
Wednesday with the most time-tested of methods: skating cleaner
than the competition.
</P>
<P>
   They skated to Vivaldi's ''Four Seasons'' nearly perfectly,
surpassing China's Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo, who led after the
short program. However, they had four costly errors in the free,
including two-footing a throw triple-salchow and his double of a
triple toe jump.
</P>
<P>
   French pair Sarah Abitbol and Stephane Bernadis overcame the
shock of a razor attack against Bernadis to win the bronze and
France's first world pairs medal since 1932.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadis, who received an injection of pain reliever a half-hour
before the competition, showed no obvious difficulty from the
8-inch cut down his left forearm, inflicted just a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   That was just one of a number of unsettling events at the pairs
event.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was more pressure than usual,'' Tikhonov said. ''When you
skate, you usually are just in your own world. It was very
different this time because I worried about our team friends and
what happened with Stephane.''
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the sudden withdrawal Sunday of two pairs,
including defending champions Yelena Berezhnaya and Anton
Sikharulidze, after samples tested positive for banned substances.
In both cases, the skaters said stimulants were contained in
medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bernadis reported that a male assailant wielding a razor
slashed his forearm at the skaters' hotel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the final evening of pairs on Wednesday, Ukrainian skater
Dmitri Palamarchuk banged his head on the ice when his right blade
appeared to catch during a press lift.
</P>
<P>
   His partner, Julia Obertas, was uninjured. Palamarchuk managed
to get off the ice on his own, but then lost consciousness at the
skaters' entrance for about five minutes. An X-ray and scan at a
hospital showed no damage, but he was being kept overnight for
observation, International Skating Union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians Kristy Sargeant and Kris Wirtz were next on the ice,
but were so upset by Palamarchuk's injury they had to stop. It
reminded them of when Wirtz fell four year ago in a similar manner
and was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   They were told to continue, and went on unenthusiastically to
finish 10th.
</P>
<P>
   The qualifying round of the women's competition seemed almost
boring, even with chief title contenders Michelle Kwan and Irina
Slutskaya skating back-to-back in the first group.
</P>
<P>
   Both performed six triple jumps, and neither fell. But after
Kwan's rather flat program to ''Red Violin,'' and scaled-down
triple-double and double salchow, Slutskaya didn't even bother to
put in either her triple lutz-triple loop, or triple salchow-triple
loop combinations,
</P>
<P>
   Kwan arrived in Nice under pressure to perform a difficult
triple-triple combination, but didn't. ''I was a little upset with
myself. I did it so well in practice, and came here and popped it,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Maria Butyrskaya easily led the weaker second
qualifying group with six triples, but she put her hand down on a
double axel.
</P>
<P>
   The women continue Friday with the short program before
finishing the championships Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
