<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Air Force Plane Crashes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- A Sri Lankan air force AN-26 plane
crashed Thursday with at least 36 military personnel onboard, an
air force spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the passengers was not immediately known. The plane
was flying from Palaly, in the war-torn north, to Colombo, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The accident took place at Thalawa, 90 miles north of Colombo,
said spokesman Wing Commander A. Wijesundera.
</P>
<P>
   Army spokesman Brig. Palitha Fernando said the pilot complained
of engine trouble shortly before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Tamil Tigers have in the past shot down several aircraft during
their battle with the military, but the cause of Thursday's
accident was not known.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas have been fighting since 1983 to carve out a
homeland in the northeast for the minority Tamils. More than 61,000
people have been killed in the war.
</P>
