<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily News To Mark 75th Birthday  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- True to its in-your-face style, the
Philadelphia Daily News will celebrate its 75th birthday Friday
with a commemorative edition that runs 450 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is titled ''75 Reasons We Love Philadelphia,'' with
No. 1, of course, being the Daily News. No surprise there.
Self-promotion is a People Paper trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we made it anything else, people would think that aliens
had taken over the paper,'' says editor Zachary Stalberg, whose
humor and penchant for colorful language has set the tone for the
feisty tabloid since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Knight Ridder-owned newspaper put out its first edition
March 25, 1925. Almost from the start, it found itself in dire
financial straits. In the early years, delivery drivers performed
their own repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the paper has employed legions of colorful
characters. There was the editor who was caught sleeping inside his
large rolltop desk, whiskey bottle in hand. And the 1930s-era
sports editor who saved a reporter from being shot by the husband
of a woman with whom the reporter had been dallying.
</P>
<P>
   Like many newspapers around the country, the Daily News has seen
a steep slide in circulation -- 31 percent since 1988 -- but has
stabilized around 160,000, Stalberg said. It is facing a new threat
from Metro, a daily tabloid distributed free on the region's public
transportation system.
</P>
<P>
   The paper still covers Philadelphia like no one else -- railing
against abandoned cars in dilapidated north Philadelphia, keeping
close tabs on City Hall, needling the city's education
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a paper that deeply loves the city of Philadelphia,''
says Lynn Washington, a former Daily News reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Hopelessly outgunned by The Philadelphia Inquirer, the Daily
News has nonetheless won two Pulitzers, one for editorial writing
and another for editorial cartooning. Its sports section is
beloved.
</P>
<P>
   The two newspapers are still at it. One columnist routinely
calls the Inquirer the ''Morning Yawn.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing I'd rather do than beat the hell out of the
Inquirer on a story,'' says police reporter Scott Flander, who has
been with the paper 17 years. ''And they can say the same thing
about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although office hijinks have toned down quite a bit, the Daily
News maintains its irreverent attitude. The headlines have included
''Spit Happens'' (pro basketball star Charles Barkley spits on an
8-year-old), ''Side Order of Lead'' (gangland slaying at a south
Philadelphia diner), and ''Cunanan's Best Shot'' (serial killer
Andrew Cunanan commits suicide).
</P>
<P>
   The paper's most famous headline is also the subject of one of
its more enduring stories.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1980, the Phillies had just won the World Series and a
debate was raging in the newsroom over the choice of headlines --
''We Win'' or ''They Did It.''
</P>
<P>
   Editor Gil Spencer finally deferred to a janitor named Ralph
who, after considering the options, pointed to ''We Win.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a good choice: A famous photo shows Phillies pitcher and
World Series hero Tug McGraw holding the paper aloft during the
team's victory parade.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, though, that Ralph wasn't exactly an informed
arbiter. A reporter later told Spencer that the janitor didn't know
how to read.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me, that kind of captures the Daily News,'' Stalberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0241 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYPD truancy patrol under fire  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Norman Siegel, executive director of the New
York Civil Liberties Union, confessed he played hooky when he was a
youngster.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel laughed about the memory Wednesday, but warned that for
the city's students, being a little late for school can land you in
police custody.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel and several police officers are questioning why NYPD
truancy vans and officers are stationed outside high schools and
are taking into custody tardy students clearly on their way to
class.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Eric Adams, co-founder of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who
Care, said such tactics are dangerous at a time when the police
department's relationship with the city's minority communities is
already frayed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're concerned at any time when the police department has
unnecessary contact with innocent civilians in a very aggressive
fashion,'' Adams said. ''It's always potent. It can lead to someone
losing their lives, like Patrick Dorismond.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond, 26, was the latest unarmed black man to be fatally
shot by police after he got into a scuffle with a plainclothes
officer who had asked him where he could buy drugs. His death on
March 16 angered many New Yorkers who contend the NYPD is out of
control. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has been roundly criticized for his
handling of the shooting, especially for releasing Dorismond's
sealed juvenile record.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, four students -- all black girls
-- described run-ins with truancy police, which Adams said occurred
more often in poor neighborhoods than privileged ones. Two of the
students stopped are daughters of NYPD officers.
</P>
<P>
   Adams stressed that the students did nothing wrong, and were in
front of their schools when they were stopped. A videotape, taken
by an unidentified private citizen and given to Adams, shows a
marked police van parked next to Springfield Gardens High School in
Queens on March 3. Students walking alone into the school are not
approached by police, but a large group of kids are, and are herded
into the van.
</P>
<P>
   Adams alleged that the officers have an arrest quota, so they
wait until a group of students come together, and target them.
Police spokeswoman Marilyn Mode said there are no such quotas, and
added that the truancy program is set up for parents' benefit, to
keep students in school.
</P>
<P>
   Truancy is not a criminal offense -- it's a violation of the
state's compulsory education law, which states that children up to
the age of 16 must attend school unless there is prior consent
between their guardian and school officials. Truant students are
taken by police to a Board of Education facility where they are
held until school officials can notify their guardians. They are
given ''youth referrals,'' which are expunged from their records
when they turn 18.
</P>
<P>
   But two of the students -- Janell Boyd, 17, and Tenyae Brazeal,
14, who attend Springfield Gardens -- were criminally charged. Boyd,
a junior, was charged with disorderly conduct, and Brazeal, a
freshman, for assaulting a school safety officer. Both girls denied
the charges, stemming from a Feb. 17th incident.
</P>
<P>
   That morning, both girls were running late. School started at
8:25 a.m., but it was 9:07 a.m., and the girls were hurrying to
class.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother knew I was running late,'' Janell said. Her mother,
Detective Evidelia Boyd, said that was true.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were stopped in front of the school, but Tenyae
managed to get inside the building and was going to call Boyd when
she ''accidentally'' bumped into a school safety officer. Tenyae
was then arrested and charged with assault, she said. Janell was
arrested for disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Both girls were taken to the 113th Precinct in Queens, and their
parents called.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was definitely wrong for the police officers to stop
children on school grounds,'' she said, adding that the experience
frightened her daughter. ''She was crying, she was shaking, she was
visibly upset.''
</P>
<P>
   When Boyd asked the arresting officer why her daughter had been
charged with a crime, she was told: ''She gave me a hard time.''
</P>
<P>
   Janell eventually received a desk appearance ticket and was
released to her mother's custody.
</P>
<P>
   ''My daughter did not commit a crime,'' said Boyd, who works in
the 88th Detective Squad.
</P>
<P>
   Two other students -- LaToya Ellerby and Kyisha Frazier, both 17
and seniors -- were stopped outside Pacific High School in Brooklyn
twice, last year and in January. The girls were detained for
questioning but not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Kyisha's mother, Officer Lisa Frazier of the 88th Precinct, said
she was very upset her daughter had been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ''She had done nothing wrong,'' Frazier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 0242 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truth Is Hard To Find in Kashmir  </HEADLINE>
By LAURINDA KEYS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATI SINGHPURA, India (AP) -- Women's anguished wails pour from
every other brick house in this Kashmir village surrounded by apple
orchards, rice fields and sparkling Himalayan snow peaks.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a week since the killers came in the night, ordered
the men from their shops and homes and shot them to death outside
the temple and in front of a hay barn. Hardly a family was not
touched by the March 20 massacre of 35 Sikhs.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen wore Indian army uniforms. They spoke Urdu, the
language of mostly Muslim Kashmir and neighboring Pakistan. The
government has identified the killers as 17 men, mostly foreigners,
from two Pakistan-based militant groups, Hezb-ul Mujahedeen and
Lashkar e-Toiba, both fighting to separate Kashmir from India.
</P>
<P>
   Home Minister L.K. Advani said the militants carried out the
massacre to publicize India's 52-year dispute with Pakistan over
Kashmir during President Clinton's visit to South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan and the militant groups denied that, and claimed India
massacred its own citizens to discredit the Kashmir separatist
movement -- a charge India dismissed as ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is swarming with armed groups, each with its own agenda,
creating uncertainty about responsibility for many atrocities.
International watchdogs like Amnesty have accused all of them --
including the Indian army -- of human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor is often a substitute for fact and there are several
versions of every event. Residents take sides based on their
religion, race and whether they have been hurt by the army, the
militants, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Sikh leaders and Kashmiri Muslims have called for an independent
inquiry into the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian army said it killed five of the Chati Singhpura
raiders in a gunbattle Saturday in Panchaltan, eight miles east of
the prosperous village.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is certain that they were the killers,'' said Gurbachan
Jagat, director general of Kashmir's police.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies were burned beyond recognition and handed over to
Muslims in Panchaltan for burial without any forensic tests.
</P>
<P>
   Police also said Indian security forces gunned down six
guerrillas Wednesday who were suspected of involvement in the
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   The 50,000 Sikhs in the Kashmir Valley had never before been
targeted during the 11-year insurgency that has killed more than
25,000 people. The Indian army says it is fighting about 10
Kashmiri and Pakistan-based militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   A visiting Clinton told India and Pakistan they need to start
talking about the disputed area that has caused two of their three
wars. But he emphasized that he had not come to mediate between the
two nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he understands the complexity of the problem. That is
the reason why he doesn't want to be getting too much involved,''
said Omer Farooq, chairman of the All Party Hurriyet Conference,
which demands Kashmir's independence from India.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still feel that Mr. Clinton has got a role to play in the
region,'' said Farooq, the chief Muslim priest in the Kashmir
Valley. Farooq suggested Clinton follow up with private,
confidence-building measures to ''give some push from the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagat said information about the militants who came to Chati
Singhpura was provided by a man the government said was a resident
of the village and had joined Hezb-ul Mujahedeen. He was arrested
after a witness said he was seen with the attackers, Jagat said.
</P>
<P>
   In the village, only two men saw the gunmen and lived. One is in
the hospital and the other has gone away. The village women said
all they know is that the gunmen were dressed like Indian soldiers
and behaved like Indian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was milking the cow when they came,'' said Jaeet Kaur, 60,
whose husband, two sons and two teen-age grandsons were killed.
When the gunmen ordered her to go inside, she obeyed because she
thought they were soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   And when did she come to know they were not?
</P>
<P>
   ''How do we know?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''After some time I heard the shots and ran out. I was searching
for our people, shouting here and there for someone to come to the
rescue. But there was no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Sikh men, former soldiers or government servants, became
angry and insulted at questions about whether the killers might
have been affiliated with the army, as many Muslim Kashmiris
believe.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one knows what is the truth,'' said Sana Ullah Bhatt,
editor of the independent Daily Sun, the most widely read newspaper
in the valley with a circulation of 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Bhan, inspector-general of the Kashmir police, said 145
militants have been killed this year. Police and security forces
are bracing for the spring, when the snow melts in the mountains,
and more guerrillas can cross.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there will be an attempt to answer the questions
about all the killings when peace comes, Bhatt hung his head.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have not seen peace since 1947. There will never be peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Pitch Medicare Proposal  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) -- Taking time out of a full day of
Democratic fund raising in New York, President Clinton plans a
pitch for his proposal to reform the Medicare system and add
coverage for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Shoring up Medicare is a major element of the president's
domestic legislative agenda for his final year in office, and
something his aides say has a good chance of passing even in an
election year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance today at a Manhattan senior citizen's
center is meant to help increase public pressure on the
Republican-led Congress, where there is already bipartisan support
for some of the president's health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also plans three fund-raising appearances in Manhattan,
a short commute by presidential helicopter from the Westchester
County home he and Hillary Rodham Clinton bought last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew to New York on Wednesday night, after a
fund-raising dinner in South Carolina that marked his first trip to
that state since a racially charged Republican presidential
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he knew his audience at historically black
Allen University expected him to address the controversy over
display of the Confederate flag atop the Statehouse in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton soft-pedaled the question, and stopped short of
saying outright that the flag should come down.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as the waving symbol of one American's pride is the
shameful symbol of another American's pain, we still have bridges
to cross,'' Clinton said during a fund-raising tribute to Rep. Jim
Clyburn, D-S.C., who is chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   The remark was an echo of Clinton's remarks earlier this month
in Alabama, where Clinton went to commemorate the 35th anniversary
of the Selma voting rights march.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
calls the flag a racist emblem and is leading a tourism boycott of
South Carolina until the flag is removed.
</P>
<P>
   Both Texas Gov. George W. Bush and his then-challenger, Arizona
Sen. John McCain, refused to take a position on the flag, calling
it a local issue. Democrats accused them of pandering to the far
right of their party.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and his then-challenger, former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, both said the flag should come down.
</P>
<P>
   The flag's defenders say it is a potent symbol of Southern
heritage and honors those who died during the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know everyone expects me to say something about that,''
Clinton said of the flag, but he seemed resolved to keep the
rhetoric low at a time when a compromise over the flag may be at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the NAACP offered some support for a plan to remove
the flag from the Statehouse but display other Civil War-era flags
on the building grounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0256 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Approval of Aid for Colombia Near  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House is standing by its plan to provide
$1.7 billion to help Colombia's hard-pressed government battle drug
traffickers and the leftist rebels who protect them.
</P>
<P>
   But as lawmakers move toward approving a wide-ranging, $13
billion measure containing those funds, they seem ready to make
half the bill's $2.1 billion for U.S. peacekeepers in Kosovo
contingent upon increased contributions there by European
countries.
</P>
<P>
   A vote to do that -- set for today -- would set up a possible
clash with President Clinton. His aides wrote legislators that the
provision ''would put at risk the considerable progress we have
made in this troubled region.''
</P>
<P>
   Language proposed by Reps. John Kasich, R-Ohio, Barney Frank,
D-Mass., and others would free the restricted Kosovo funds if
Clinton certifies that European countries have provided more
economic, humanitarian and policing assistance to the breakaway
Balkan enclave.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the 78-day air war against Yugoslavia began, there
are 37,000 NATO-led peacekeepers in Kosovo, including 5,300
Americans. Amid recent flare-ups of ethnic violence in the Yugoslav
province, some lawmakers want increased European involvement, in
part to compensate for the large U.S. share of the bombing costs.
</P>
<P>
   As the House worked on the spending bill, which would provide
extra funds for this year, the Senate Budget Committee neared
approval of a $1.83 trillion budget for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That Republican-written measure resembles a budget the House
approved last week for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. It would
cut taxes by at least $150 billion through 2005 and hold spending
for many domestic programs next year to $290 billion, or 2.6
percent more than this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to vote on the budget next week, and
congressional leaders hope for final approval of a compromise
version of the measure by mid-April. The fiscal plan does not need
Clinton's signature and sets overall tax and spending targets,
leaving details for later legislation.
</P>
<P>
   House supporters of the Colombia aid package see it as a major
step toward curbing drug supplies in the United States. U.S.
officials say 90 percent of the cocaine and 65 percent of the
heroin used in the United States comes from Colombian-grown coca.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the House voted 239-186 to reject an effort by
Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., that would have delayed, and perhaps
eventually killed, $522 million of the Colombia aid. The roll call
came after House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who rarely joins
floor debate, took to the well of the chamber to ask colleagues for
the full amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said the aid ''is about our children, and whether we
want our children to grow up in a society free from the scourge of
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said the package would risk involving the United
States in what has been a long-running, bloody civil war that could
continue for years. They also said U.S. resources should be
directed more toward preventing drug use at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fundamental problem is the addiction that causes people to
crave ... drugs,'' said Rep. Jim Ramstad, R-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Ramstad later tried killing the entire $1.7 billion Colombia aid
package, losing 262-158.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had requested $1.3 billion for Colombia, on top of $300
million already in the pipeline, but supported the House proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The money is for training and equipping Colombian troops and
police -- including 63 helicopters -- along with intelligence
operations, incentives for farmers to grow other crops, and
assisting neighbors Peru, Ecuador and Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the House added $4 billion to the overall bill for
the Pentagon, including funds for upgrading helicopters and AWACS
radar warning planes, equipment repair, and military housing and
health care.
</P>
<P>
   The funds, backed by House leaders to satisfy pro-defense
lawmakers who wanted a bigger defense budget for 2001, were
approved 289-130.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's ultimate fate is uncertain. Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., has said he wants to shrink it and put the
remnants into spending measures for fiscal 2001 that Congress will
write later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But House leaders have pressed on, hoping to persuade Lott to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes $1.6 billion for rising Pentagon fuel
costs; $858 million for its fiscally ailing health care plan; $2.2
billion for victims of Hurricane Floyd, which battered North
Carolina last autumn, and other natural disasters; and $600 million
to help poor families pay utility bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0259 </TRAILER>
