<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut to take lead role in antitrust investigation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut's attorney general says he
will take a lead role in a national investigation of the gun
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will center on allegations that the nation's
largest gun maker, Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp. of Springfield, Mass., has
been the target of retaliation from the rest of the industry after
entering into a gun-control agreement with the Clinton
administration, Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under that agreement, the company pledged to take a series of
steps in return for protection from lawsuits brought by 29 cities
and counties across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The measures included steps long sought by gun-control
advocates: mandatory trigger-locks on all weapons, investment in
''smart gun'' technology to prevent non-owners and children from
firing a weapon, and marketing restrictions such as waiting periods
and limits on the number of gun purchases made at a single time.
</P>
<P>
   The March 17 agreement was met with protests by gun-owners
groups and Smith &AMP; Wesson's competitors. One group, the Gun Owners
of America, urged its 200,000 members to boycott Smith &AMP; Wesson
products and to ask their local dealers not to stock the company's
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is at this point at least the appearance of an effort
that involved concerted activity targeting Smith &AMP; Wesson by
manufacturers, distributors, dealers and possibly others,''
Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said his office will be joined in the probe by
officials from New York and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford Courant, citing sources outside the attorney
general's office it did not identify, reported today that officials
from the White House and other federal agencies that regulate
handguns considered joining the effort at a high-level meeting in
Washington on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am aware of the meeting Tuesday in Washington and of the
speculation about an investigation,'' said Ken Jorgensen, director
of public and media relations for Smith &AMP; Wesson. ''Obviously I can
confirm that other companies in our business are quite unhappy with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorgensen said that, in the wake of the March 17 agreement, some
dealers have told Smith &AMP; Wesson that they will no longer carry
their gun models. Others have said that ''they hope all the other
dealers in their neighborhood stop carrying Smith &AMP; Wesson models,
because we love your company and then we'll have the market all to
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports of attempts to pressure gun magazines into refusing
Smith &AMP; Wesson advertisements have also reached the company,
Jorgensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal cautioned that launching an investigation does not
necessarily guarantee that a lawsuit will be brought.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be specific about the activities his
investigators will be looking into. But he said that investigators
and attorneys from all three states are already interviewing
witnesses and gathering information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
