<DOCNO> APW20000330.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 06:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Using New Was To Deal With DDT  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL CHAVEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Federal officials say they will toughen
measures to prevent consumption of fish tainted by a huge deposit
of DDT on the ocean floor.
</P>
<P>
   The pesticide has contaminated Santa Monica Bay's Palos Verdes
Shelf for a half-century and earned a Superfund designation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the largest DDT contamination site in the country,''
the Environmental Protection Agency's Keith Takata said Wednesday.
''The first step to protect the public health is to make sure
people aren't eating white croaker contaminated with dangerous
levels of DDT.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the EPA in July will launch a three-month pilot
project to cap 180 acres of ocean floor along the Los Angeles coast
with sand and silt to prevent the spread of the pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   The $5 million experiment will take place in waters about 200
feet deep, said Fred Schauffler, the EPA's project manager.
</P>
<P>
   The contaminated area has an estimated 100 tons of DDT spread
across 17 square miles of ocean floor. There are also about 10 tons
of PCBs.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical manufacturer Montrose Corp. allegedly dumped residue,
including DDT, into the sewage system from 1947 until 1971. The
area was declared a Superfund environmental cleanup site in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   DDT, which was banned in the U.S. in 1973, has been linked to
cancer and reproductive problems in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Because contamination levels of DDT are the highest in
bottom-feeding fish, such as the white croaker, the EPA will call
for more aggressive enforcement of the catch limit and the
commercial fishing ban in the area, Schauffler said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also will launch an educational campaign and monitor
contamination levels of white croaker sold in markets, Schauffler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Montrose and other companies responsible for the pollution have
challenged the EPA's capping plan as being too risky.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ... disagree with the Montrose folks who claim there's no
significant human health risk and the problem is going away on its
own by virtue of biodegradation of DDT,'' Schauffler said. ''Here
we are 30 years after the last significant discharge and we still
have a very major problem on our hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 0624 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials say inmate injured by rubber bullets was not fighting  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The wounding of three Connecticut inmates
by guards shooting rubber bullets inside a Virginia prison has
sparked debate at the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the inmates were injured Monday when a guard at
Wallens Ridge State Prison in Big Stone Gap, Va. tried to break up
a fight between two of them.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was another inmate who was inadvertently hit,'' said
Christina Polce, a spokeswoman from the Connecticut Department of
Correction. ''He was not involved in the (fight), but was nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Farr, said firing rubber bullets is an effective way
to keep order.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very humane way to control your population,'' said
Farr, R-West Hartford. ''It protects the inmates, and it also
protects the corrections officers from having to risk injury by
physically breaking up a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Lawlor, the cochair of the Legislature's Judiciary
Committee disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This guy didn't do anything wrong, and he got shot,'' said
Lawlor, D-East Haven. ''That doesn't say good things about the
security and safety down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia and Connecticut officials refused to identify the
inmates, but Lawlor said 34-year-old Daniel Westberg of West Haven
was the prisoner who was not fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The brawling prisoners were William Valedon, 32, of New Haven
and Andres Davila, 21, of West Hartford, Lawlor said.
</P>
<P>
   Valedon is serving 13 years on a criminal attempt charge; Davila
is serving five years for first-degree robbery; Westberg is serving
eight years for first-degree robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut and Virginia officials are investigating the
shootings, and would not say whether Westberg was struck directly
or injured by rubber bullets which may have ricocheted off the
floor or a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Valedon, Davila and Westberg are three of the 480 Connecticut
prisoners who have been transferred to Wallens Ridge. Gov. John G.
Rowland and corrections officials say the transfers are needed to
ease overcrowding in Connecticut prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's contract with Virginia allows 500 inmates to be
housed at Wallens Ridge for $11 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have accused guards at the Virginia prison of
racial intolerance, and the FBI is investigating allegations of
abuse made by New Mexico inmates who were shipped to the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any time there is a use of force in our prisons or in
Virginia, we're concerned,'' Polce said. ''We want to investigate
this incident and assure that proper policy and procedure was
followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut DOC guards do not carry guns or other weapons in the
enclosed cell blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Traylor, a spokesman for the Virginia Department of
Corrections, said the Wallens Ridge guards acted appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   He said the shootings happened Monday night after the brawling
inmates ignored verbal commands from prison guards to stop. The
guards also fired blank warning shots before shooting the rubber
bullets, Traylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates were treated for injuries at the prison infirmary,
Traylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of the injuries were serious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traylor said the fighting inmates were hit in the lower
extremities with so-called stinger rounds -- hard, rubber balls
about 1/3 of an inch in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Westberg's mother, Carol Westberg, said her son was hit twice in
the back but did not receive immediate medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's something very wrong with the system down there,''
Carol Westberg said. ''My son is not safe. None of the inmates are
safe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 0936 </TRAILER>
