<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 62.98; Nasdaq Down 53.17  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today, with
blue-chip stocks once again attracting money away from technology
shares.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 62.98 at 11,081.70.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which lists most of the world's
leading technology companies, was down 53.17 at 4,591.50 after
tumbling more than 100 points at the start of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 4.82 at 1,503.70.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have been in a protracted slide since March
10, when the Nasdaq closed at a record high of 5,048.62. Investors
are selling off shares of the companies that have performed
especially well in the year to date, hoping to capture profits.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Healtheon/WebMD fell 2 13/16 to 27~, and Cisco Systems
fell 5/16 to 75}.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, United Technologies rose 1{ to 59[ and WalMart rose 1
13/16 to 60 9/16, pacing the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The market was rattled by a report that the U.S. economy soared
to an annual growth rate of 7.3 percent in the final three months
of 1999, the strongest performance in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the gross domestic product -- the country's total
output of goods and services -- was sharper than analysts had
expected, and raised worries that the Federal Reserve will continue
raising interest rates in order to force a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates five times since last June, but so far
has seen little concrete evidence that the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 136.56 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.90 to 539.10.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas indexes declined sharply. Japan's Nikkei stock average
fell 1.3 percent. In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was
down 2.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 2.7 percent, and
France's CAC-40 was down 3.0 percent.
</P>
