<HEADLINE> Newspaper: Ally agrees to inform on Merlino  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A former ally of reputed gangland leader
Joseph ''Skinny Joey'' Merlino has agreed to provide information to
federal authorities linking Merlino and others to a 1993 shooting
that started a mob war, a newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Gaetano ''Tommy Horsehead'' Scafidi would be the first member of
Merlino's inner circle to cooperate and could help authorities
build a case against top Merlino associates who have thus far
avoided indictment, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the U.S. Attorney's office nor the FBI would comment on
the continuing investigation into the Merlino organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the newspaper quoted sources familiar with the case who
asked not to be identified as saying Scafidi's decision to
cooperate was devastating for Merlino, with one describing it as
''the beginning of the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Scafidi, 35, serving an 82-month sentence after pleading guilty
to racketeering charges in 1995, was scheduled to appear before a
federal grand jury after finalizing a cooperating agreement with
authorities earlier this month, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Scafidi was expected to provide an account of the 1993 attempted
murder of Joseph ''Joey Chang'' Ciancaglini, which started a war
between the Merlino faction of the mob and an organization headed
by then-mob boss John Stanfa. Ciancaglini was a Stanfa underboss.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI document made public in 1996 said Scafidi told another
mob informant the hit was ordered by Merlino and Merlino's top
associate, Michael Ciancaglini, brother of Joseph Ciancaglini.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Merlino and George Borgesi, a Merlino associate
Scafidi was expected to implicate, sharply questioned Scafidi's
credibility, saying he was testifying for his own benefit and his
testimony could not be corroborated.
</P>
</TEXT>
