<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden Mayor Milton Milan indicted, surrenders to federalauthoritries  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Camden Mayor Milton Milan has been indicted
on unspecified federal charges and surrendered to federal
authorities this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, 37, a first-term Democrat elected in 1997, has been under
scrutiny by federal authorities in a wide-ranging investigation of
alleged corruption in Camden city government. A grand jury
subpoenaed Milan's payroll records and requested information about
political fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the grand jury spent a full day behind closed
doors with federal prosecutors, leading to speculation that an
indictment was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Milan emerged from his City Hall office around 10:30 a.m. and
told reporters outside that he had been indicted and was going to
the U.S. Attorney's office two blocks away to turn himself in.
Milan was accompanied by his lawyer, Carlos A. Martir Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Martir confirmed that his client had been indicted, but said he
did not know the specific charges. He said Milan had a 10:30
appointment to meet with federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney scheduled a 1:30 news conference to discuss
the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Milan asserted that he was ''absolutely not guilty'' of any
charges and said the entire matter was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a political procedure. What could not be done
politically has been turned into a criminal procedure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milan then walked to the federal courthouse surrounded by a
throng of reporters. Traffic stopped and people poured out of
office buildings along the route to watch the procession.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the pace of the federal inquiry had quickened
as city lawmakers were subpoenaed to appear before the grand jury
and questioned about a wide range of issues including city
contracts, organized crime and contractors who performed repairs on
Milan's East Camden home.
</P>
<P>
   Milan's name also was mentioned prominently in the recent
federal trial of two men convicted as leaders of a Camden drug
ring. Several witnesses claimed that Milan sold drugs in Camden in
the 1980s and bought several shipments of cocaine before becoming
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Milan's East Camden home and City Hall office were
raided by FBI agents who carted away boxes of documents.
</P>
<P>
   While the investigation dragged on for at least two years, Milan
maintained a high public profile, vehemently denying any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first Hispanic mayor of this desperately poor city of
87,000 located on the Delaware River across from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine Corps veteran and former contractor, he was elected to
city council in 1995 and became council president a year later. He
parlayed his popularity into a run for mayor to make Camden
political history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
