<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Drops 64.36; Dow Up 9.46  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today, with technology
shares dragging the Nasdaq composite lower for a fourth straight
session and weighing on other market indexes.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 9.46 at 11,028.18.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which lists most of the world's
leading technology companies, was down 64.36 at 4,580.31 after
tumbling more than 100 points at the start of trading.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 2.44 at 1,510.96.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have been in a slide since March 10, when the
Nasdaq closed at a record high of 5,048.62. Investors are selling
off shares of the companies that have performed especially well in
the year to date, hoping to capture profits.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Healtheon/WebMD fell 2 5/16 to 28], and Cisco Systems
fell 1| to 74 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, United Technologies rose 1 5/16 to 58 15/16 and
WalMart rose 1 3/16 to 59 15/16, pacing the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology specialists are starting to use the 'v' word --
value,'' said Zane Brown, vice president at Lord, Abbett &AMP; Co.
''People are questioning valuations and are less willing to buy
technology stocks at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   The market was rattled by reports that Tiger Management, an
investment company that focuses on hedge funds, will soon close.
Tiger, run by renowned money manager Julian H. Robertson Jr., was
once among the world's largest hedge fund families with $21 billion
in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's assets have shrunk to about $6 billion, but investors
still fear its shutdown will create a less liquid market, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were further unnerved by a report that the U.S.
economy soared to an annual growth rate of 7.3 percent in the final
three months of 1999, the strongest performance in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the gross domestic product -- the country's total
output of goods and services -- was sharper than analysts had
expected, and raised worries that the Federal Reserve will continue
raising interest rates in order to force a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates five times since last June, but so far
has seen little concrete evidence that the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the European Central Bank left key interest rates
unchanged as ebbing inflation, stable exchange rates and moderate
wage contracts calmed policymakers. Most European stock indexes
were lower, however, extending a selloff that began before the
interest rate announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 345.22 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.15 to 544.15.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
