<P>
Mob attack shuts Baptist seminary in Nigeria
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Baptist seminary in Kaduna, Nigeria,
was nearly destroyed and three students and eight others were
killed during late February rioting by a Muslim mob, Baptist Press
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Most buildings on campus were burned down and seminary President
Uche Enyioha said it would cost up to $5.3 million to replace them.
Many books were destroyed in the library, which had just reached
the 10,000 items required for accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 seminary students and nearby residents tried
unsuccessfully to defend the campus against a mob that numbered in
the thousands, missionaries told Baptist Press.
</P>
<P>
   The seminary board has decided to resume classes for graduating
seniors after Easter in a Baptist chapel to the south. The board
hopes the other students can be called back by January, but is
unsure whether to rebuild at the present campus or relocate.
</P>
<P>
   Both mosques and churches were burned, and hundreds killed,
during the four-day conflict between Muslims and Christians.
Trouble began when Christians called public marches to protest a
proposal to impose Islamic religious law on all citizens of Kaduna
province, in northern Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
