<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine apologizes for jokes about Italian-Americans  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Jon S. Corzine, the former Wall Street
executive seeking the Democratic nomination for Senate in New
Jersey, has apologized for two remarks that played on stereotypes
of Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The two remarks were publicized Wednesday by Manny Alfano,
chairman of the Italian-American One Voice Committee, who demanded
an apology from Corzine for ''ethnic slurs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I never intended to cause embarrassment. I never intended to
offend,'' Corzine said Thursday. ''I shouldn't have said what I am
reported to have said, and if I did, I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said he did apologize to the people offended by the
remarks. He stopped short of admitting that he made them.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who said he is of Italian descent, offered the apology
at a news conference at which he accepted the endorsement of Unite
Garment Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Minority Leader Joseph Doria, who attended the news
conference, said the remarks being attributed to Corzine are a
distraction created by Gov. Jim Florio's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, Doria said he had no direct evidence linking the
comments, which were reported by The New York Times on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The first remark occurred several months ago at a restaurant in
Newark, where Corzine was seeking the support of six prominent
Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano said that upon being introduced to a lawyer named David
Stein, Corzine remarked, ''Who is Dave Stein? He's not Italian, is
he? Oh, I guess he's your Jewish lawyer who is here to get the rest
of you out of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Alfano, the second remark occurred two weeks ago
when Corzine met an Italian-American businessman and quipped, ''Oh,
you make cement shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Goldstein, one of Corzine's two campaign managers, said
the candidate ''never, ever'' uttered the alleged reference to the
''Jewish lawyer.'' Stein, the lawyer in question, said he did meet
with Corzine four to six months ago but does not recall the comment
in question.
</P>
<P>
   As for the balance of the statements attributed to the
candidate, Goldstein said, ''Jon Corzine never intended to offend
anyone by his remarks. He believes he should not have said
something like this and he apologizes for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman Sachs, is locked in a
hard-hitting primary battle with Florio for the Democratic
nomination to succeed retiring Sen. Frank R. Lautenberg, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   One in four New Jersey Democrats has Italian roots, including
Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano, who lives in Bloomfield, said Thursday that he is not a
supporter ''yet'' of either Florio or Corzine. He said he went
public with Corzine's statements to defend Italian-Americans, not
to score political points.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sorry, but this constant barrage of mob movies, the
Sopranos (television show) ... people think they can say anything
to Italians and we're not going to be offended,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
