<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Visits D.C.  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council took seats in the
historic Old Senate Chamber today for a greeting and a civics
lesson from Sen. Jesse Helms. The ardent critic of the world body
reminded the visiting delegates of the Senate's ''unique role'' in
U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it's been suggested to you that the president alone''
speaks on behalf of the United States on foreign policy matters,
Helms, R-N.C., said. ''Not in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegates accepted Helms' invitation after he became the
first U.S. lawmaker to address the Security Council last January.
All 15 members came from New York, billing it as an unofficial
visit, and arriving individually.
</P>
<P>
   ''Welcome to the heart of democracy,'' Helms, chairman of the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee and a fierce past critic of the
world body, said as he welcomed delegates to his turf.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he had done in his New York speech, Helms mixed
cordiality with a few digs at the world body.
</P>
<P>
   He said he knew it was ''difficult for some visitors'' to
understand the ''unique role the Senate plays,'' including the
power to ratify treaties, confirm ambassadors and -- with the House
-- pay for foreign operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is my hope that this may be helpful to you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Helms spoke to the delegates in the Old Senate Chamber, used for
Senate sessions from 1810 to 1859 but now chiefly for ceremonial
events.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the delegates joined senators for lunch. In a toast, Sen.
Joseph Biden of Delaware, the panel's senior Democrat, said he hope
the daylong visit in addition to promoting better understanding
would show Security Council members ''how disorganized we are -- and
how many different voices we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The current Security Council president, Bangladesh Ambassador
Anwarul Chowdhury, toasted the Senate in return and said both
organizations ''seek the understanding and realization that the
United Nations is the most-needed organization in today's world.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at the State Department, the delegates stood before the
flags of their countries and were greeted by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is truly a unique occasion and one that I think is very,
very important and I thank them all for not only going the extra
mile, but the extra 200 miles to get here,'' said Albright, herself
a former U.N. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Council members arrived for the unprecedented visit on their
own, stressing the individual invitations. Russia's U.N. Ambassador
Sergey Lavrov declined to ride in a bus from the airport with a
group of other ambassadors. Instead he went in a Russian Embassy
car.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would be outspoken, Lavrov said: ''You know that
being in a private capacity means we would be acting on impulses,
not instructions, so we'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials were not sure how the day would play out as
the diplomats met with members of the Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke, doing a little ground work in
advance, called Biden to ask if there would be ''an ambush by
anyone'' during today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''None that I know of,'' Biden said he tried to assure
Holbrooke. In fact, a cordial visit seemed most likely, Biden
suggested, even though many frictions remain.
</P>
<P>
   The day's itinerary called for a tour of the Capitol, a talk by
the Senate historian, an underground trolley ride to one of the
Senate office buildings, a luncheon, and a ''roundtable
discussion'' with Helms' committee.
</P>
<P>
   Council members were to visit the White House and attend a
dinner with Albright as host.
</P>
<P>
   While ambassadors initially were skeptical about Helms'
invitation, they later seemed to warm up to it -- and see the visit
it as a good way to help mend frayed U.S.-U.N. relations.
</P>
<P>
   Council members may use the occasion to try to press for more
installments on U.S. back dues. The United Nations puts the figure
at $1.7 billion but the United States calculates it at closer to $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year voted to pay $926 million of the arrears over
three years. The United States paid a $100 million installment late
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But to get the balance, the United Nations must meet about a
dozen conditions drafted by Helms and Biden. Those terms generally
have not been well received in New York.
</P>
<P>
   They include a reduction the U.S. share of the U.N. peacekeeping
budget from the current 31 percent to 25 percent and of the regular
budget from 25 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
