<HEADLINE> Boston Bar Charges Dismissed  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE LeBLANC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Licensing officials dismissed charges Thursday
against a bar owner accused of mocking Black History Month with a
display of stuffed monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairman Daniel Pokaski said there was a lack of evidence
that the display at Tom English's Cottage was racist. The charge of
displaying objectionable material could have led to the suspension
or revocation of the bar's license.
</P>
<P>
   The case was provoked by a Boston Herald article that quoted an
unnamed bartender as saying the monkeys were a tribute to Black
History Month.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got to bring it to closure,'' Pokaski said. ''What are
we dealing with? We're dealing with a remark made by a bartender.
We're not talking about life or death.''
</P>
<P>
   Bar owner Tom English did not attend the hearing. His lawyers
declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   English and two bartenders testified Tuesday that the display
was not intended to demean any racial or ethnic group. He said the
monkeys were part of a tropical scene he displays every January and
February to provide some comfort in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Herald reporter David Wedge said only one bartender was on duty
when he conducted his interviews. Bartender Vincent Salamone
testified he was working when Wedge was in the bar, but denied
making the comments.
</P>
<P>
   Wedge declined to testify and said he stood by his story.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the bar were dismayed by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no disputing the existence of that display,'' said
City Councilor Charles Yancey, who is black. ''It's mockery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
