<HEADLINE> Gun Industry Antitrust Probe Begins  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- An antitrust investigation has begun into
allegations that gun manufacturers are targeting Smith &AMP; Wesson in
retaliation for its agreement to put safety locks on handguns,
Connecticut's attorney general said.
</P>
<P>
   The probe is being conducted under state laws in Connecticut,
New York and Maryland, said Attorney General Richard Blumenthal. He
said more states were expected to become involved and subpoenas
were imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Jorgensen, a Smith &AMP; Wesson spokesman, said some gun dealers
opposed to the settlement will no longer carry the company's
models. He also said the Springfield, Mass.-based company has
received reports of attempts to pressure gun publications into
refusing Smith &AMP; Wesson advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a gun wholesaler said after the March 17 agreement
it would no longer distribute Smith &AMP; Wesson products.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is, at this point at least, the appearance of an effort
that involved concerted activity targeting Smith &AMP; Wesson by
manufacturers, distributors, dealers and possibly others,''
Blumenthal said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delfay, president of the National Shooting Sports
Foundation, denied the allegations of a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could not be more confident that these are just independent
actions by businessmen,'' Delfay told The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   In the agreement with the Clinton administration, Smith &AMP; Wesson
said it would include safety locks with all handguns and pistols
within two years and that new firearms would not be able to use
magazines that hold more than 10 rounds. It also agreed to devote 2
percent of firearms revenues every year to developing technology
that limits a gun's use to its lawful owner.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, several cities, states and the federal government
agreed to drop threatened lawsuits over gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   After the agreement, wholesaler RSR Group Inc., a distributor of
Smith &AMP; Wesson products for more than 20 years said, ''we have come
to the difficult conclusion that we cannot continue to do business
with Smith &AMP; Wesson under the problematic terms of their current
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said investigators and attorneys from all three
states were interviewing witnesses but he declined to be specific.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent criticism of Smith &AMP; Wesson by National Rifle
Association President Charlton Heston, the organization said the
company was still welcome at its annual meeting in Charlotte, N.C.,
in May.
</P>
<P>
   After the agreement, Heston said the British owners of Smith &AMP;
Wesson do not place the same value on the Second Amendment's right
to bear arms as do Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anybody is welcome, and I think it is good for the
organization, in this case for this foreign-owned company, to hear
from their American consumers,'' NRA spokesman Bill Powers told The
Charlotte Observer on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson said it planned to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''People within the gun movement have disagreed with each other
before in a civil manner,'' Jorgensen said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Rifle Association site http://www.nra.org
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson site: http://www.smith-wesson.com
</P>
<P>
   National Shooting Sports Foundation site: http://www.nssf.org
</P>
<P>
   RSR Group Inc. site:
http://www.rsrwholesale.com/rsrgun/htmls/allgunhm.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
