<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Icahn Seeks 100M Shares of Nabisco  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financier Carl Icahn said today he is prepared
to begin a cash tender offer of $13 a share for 100 million shares
of Nabisco Group Holdings Corp., and said he would consider selling
the entire company if he gains control of it.
</P>
<P>
   The plans that Icahn outlined in a letter today represent his
most ambitious effort yet to gain control of the company that was
created when RJR Nabisco Holdings spun off its cigarette holdings
in the face of mounting litigation against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Parsippany, N.J.-based Nabisco Group Holdings' sole asset is
an 80.5 percent stake in Nabisco Holdings Corp., the food company
that makes Ritz crackers, Oreo cookies and Planters nuts.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Nabisco Group said Icahn's proposal will be
reviewed by the board and it urged shareholders to take no action
in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nabisco Group surged 29 percent on the news, rising
$2.68} to $12 in early afternoon trading on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn already owns about 31 million shares of Nabisco Group and
said another 100 million shares would give him control of about 40
percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is prepared to start the tender offer on April 4
provided that Nabisco drop its poison pill provision adopted
earlier this month to make a takeover by an unwanted suitor
prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Nabisco board adopted the poison pill, which allows
shareholders to buy more stock at a big discount if an unwanted
takeover effort begins, after Icahn announced he intended to run a
slate of candidates for election to the board.
</P>
<P>
   In today's announcement, he said owning 40 percent of its stock
would facilitate election of his nominees for the board, and said
the new board's ''first order of business'' would be to consider
the sale of Nabisco Group at a favorable price.
</P>
<P>
   He also set two other conditions for starting the tender offer --
that Nabisco approve his purchase of shares despite a Delaware law
that would otherwise limit him to owning no more than 15 percent of
its shares and setting a new date for the annual meeting so that he
could vote the shares he purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The annual meeting is currently scheduled for May 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
