<HEADLINE> Jagger Opens School Arts Center  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Mick Jagger rolled back to his old grammar school
Thursday to open a $3.6 million community arts center named after
him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones frontman graduated in 1961 from Dartford
Grammar School in Kent. Back then, he was better known for his role
in organizing a student strike to demand higher quality student
dinners.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the school assembly, Jagger praised the modern
approach taken by the current headmaster. When he was enrolled, he
said, students with an interest in music and the arts were treated
like they had ''an embarrassing illness'' that had to be kept to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jagger, 56, also posed for photos with members of the school
band, who performed their rendition of the Rolling Stones classic
''Brown Sugar.''
