<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Brennan's Widow Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mary Fowler Brennan, wife of the late Supreme
Court Justice William J. Brennan, has died at age 83.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brennan died Tuesday at Arlington Hospital in suburban
Virginia. A court spokeswoman said she died of complications while
being treated for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brennan, a 40-year Supreme Court employee, worked for
nearly 26 years as Brennan's secretary. After the death of the
justice's first wife, he and his longtime secretary were married in
1983 -- her last day as a court employee.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Wermiel, an American University law professor and
Brennan scholar, said Mrs. Brennan once told him she had been
reluctant to leave her previous Supreme Court job to work for the
justice. But she was urged by Justice Felix Frankfurter, for whom
she had worked briefly, to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan died in 1997 at age 91. He had retired in 1990 after a
34-year tenure on the nation's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brennan's survivors include two sisters.
</P>
</TEXT>
