<HEADLINE> Wis. Charges Van Crash Company  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JANESVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- A company that employed seven young
magazine sellers killed in a van accident has been charged with
homicide, and its owner-manager is accused of supplying drugs to
the victims.
</P>
<P>
   The seven were killed March 25, 1999, when a minivan carrying 14
people ages 15 to 22 crashed near Janesville. The driver of the van
pleaded guilty to vehicular homicide and is serving seven years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The company -- YES, based in DeWitt, Iowa -- is charged with
homicide by negligent use of a vehicle, physical abuse of a child,
reckless injury and recklessly endangering safety, Attorney General
James Doyle said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   YES owner-manager Choan A. Lane is charged with delivery of a
controlled substance to a minor and contributing to the delinquency
of a minor.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint says members of the sales crew used marijuana
daily and were encouraged to bring back drugs at the end of a sales
day, calling sales incentive programs ''points for joints'' and
''cash for hash.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from YES or Lane; telephone
numbers are no longer listed for them in DeWitt.
</P>
</TEXT>
