</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOPer Criticizes E-Mail Witnesses  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A White House lawyer today suggested that a
court affidavit describing the White House system for archiving
e-mail was literally true, even though it didn't disclose that many
messages were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Angering some House Republicans at a hearing, White House
counsel Beth Nolan and Justice Department lawyer Robert Raben said
they did not know who assisted the White House computer specialist
who filed the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is inconceivable you come up here and not have any of the
answers,'' Rep. Dan Burton, the committee chairman, told Raben, who
promised to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Burton sent a criminal referral to the Justice Department
suggesting that the computer specialist, Daniel Barry, committed
perjury in the affidavit for a lawsuit. The affidavit stated that
''e-mail within the EOP (Executive Office of the President) system
... has been archived in the ... Automated Records Management
System.''
</P>
<P>
   The computer problems -- which White House officials learned of
in June 1998 -- didn't become public until February in a lawsuit
over the Clinton White House's gathering of FBI background files of
Republican appointees from past administrations. As a result of the
computer problems, perhaps hundreds of thousands of e-mails were
never reviewed to determine if they should be turned over to
Congress and prosecutors in various investigations.
</P>
<P>
   It may take 170 days to reconstruct e-mail back-up tapes and
conduct a thorough search, Nolan testified at a hearing of the
House Government Reform Committee. There are 625 back-up tapes for
Vice President Al Gore's office alone, said Nolan. The time
estimate of 170 days was a sharp reduction from an earlier estimate
of one to two years.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan suggested that the affidavit is literally true.
</P>
<P>
   ''E-mail was archived, but some e-mail was not captured,'' she
argued.
</P>
<P>
   ''But that is not what the affidavit says,'' Burton retorted,
referring to the omission in the affidavit of any problems with the
e-mail system.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan said the affidavit was written in connection with events
that happened early in the Clinton administration and had nothing
to do with the e-mail problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., suggested Nolan was coming up with a legal
theory to explain away a false affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never said I was providing a legal theory,'' Nolan snapped,
but simply offering ''context.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said ''I am concerned'' that the lawyers who assisted
Barry in the preparation of his affidavit, and who counseled him at
the time the affidavit was signed, were aware that the information
was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   Burton cited lawyers in the White House counsel's office as
possibly being ''involved in this deception.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
