<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 91.83; Nasdaq Down 118.85  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, with technology shares
dragging the Nasdaq composite index lower for a fourth straight
session and old-fashioned industrial stocks buoying the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 91.83 at 11,110.55. The Nasdaq was down 118.85 at
4,525.82.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was down 0.05 at 1,508.57.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have been in a slide since March 10, when the
Nasdaq closed at a record high of 5,048.62. At its current level,
the Nasdaq is within market watchers' definition of a correction --
a reversal of an upward trend.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are selling off shares of the companies that have
performed especially well in the year to date, hoping to capture
profits. Today, wireless data company Qualcomm fell 7~ to 149|, and
network gear maker Cisco Systems fell 2 11/16 to 73].
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron, a maker of network switches and software, plunged 16~
to 30~ after saying it anticipates a first-quarter loss of $25
million to $45 million as it restructures itself into four
operating companies. Goldman Sachs cut its rating on Cabletron
stock to ''market perform'' from ''market outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, aerospace company United Technologies rose 3] to 61;
3M rose 3 3/16 to 90 13/16; and Coca-Cola rose 2{ to 49], pacing
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology specialists are starting to use the 'v' word --
value,'' said Zane Brown, vice president at Lord, Abbett &AMP; Co.
''People are questioning valuations and are less willing to buy
technology stocks at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   The market was rattled by the official announcement that Tiger
Management, a family of hedge funds, will soon shut down. Tiger,
run by renowned money manager Julian H. Robertson Jr., was once
among the world's largest hedge fund families with $21 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's assets have shrunk to about $6 billion, but investors
still fear its shutdown will create a less liquid market, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were further unnerved by a report that the U.S.
economy soared to an annual growth rate of 7.3 percent in the final
three months of 1999, the strongest performance in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the gross domestic product -- the country's total
output of goods and services -- was sharper than analysts had
expected, and raised worries that the Federal Reserve will continue
raising interest rates in order to force a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates five times since last June, but so far
has seen little concrete evidence that the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the European Central Bank left key interest rates
unchanged as ebbing inflation, stable exchange rates and moderate
wage contracts calmed policymakers. Most European stock indexes
were lower, however, extending a selloff that began before the
interest rate announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 778.66 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners led by
a 7-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.04 to 536.96.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
