<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Europe's key markets took their lead from a
technology sell-off in the United States, falling an average of 2
percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the technology-heavy Nasdaq Stock Market dropped
nearly 4 percent, creating a domino effect in other parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also attributed the poor performances to a decision by
the European Central Bank on Thursday to leave its key short-term
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks Ericsson, Nokia and Siemens were particularly
hard hit.
</P>
<P>
   In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100 Share Index closed down
153.6 points, or 2.3 percent, at 6,445.2.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 219.87 points to 7,644.89. The
Paris CAC-40 Index was down 191.66 points to 6,313.82. Milan's
MIBtel Index was down 880 points to 31,722.
</P>
<P>
   By the close of the European session, the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx
Index -- which tracks companies in countries that joined the single
currency -- was down 14.98 points, or 3.3 percent, at 440.25. The
Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was down 164.3 points, or 3.0
percent, to 5,252.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell
points 11.4 points, or 2.8 percent, to 391.66, while the Dow Jones
Stoxx 50 Index fell 135.7 points, or 2.6 percent, to 5,025.6.
</P>
</TEXT>
