<DOCNO> APW20000330.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Charged in N.Y. Investment Scam  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- Five members of a Long Island ''boiler
room'' operation bilked investors out of $3.2 million, using the
proceeds for Hawaiian vacations and Atlantic City gambling trips,
state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''These defendants were all about greed, pure and simple,''
Spitzer said in a statement. ''They preyed upon unsophisticated
investors to finance a lavish lifestyle. Now that the money has run
out, we are going to vigorously prosecute them.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner, chief salesman and three brokers of Renaissance
Capital Management, Inc., were arrested this week and accused in a
38-count indictment with grand larceny, securities fraud and other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges that from October 1997 to June 1999,
Renaissance owner Allen Andrescu and his brokers promised investors
they could double or triple their money within 90 days if they
invested in a company called NNPD textiles, which they said was
about to go public. The setup was a typical of a ''boiler room''
operation, in which brokers make high-pressure, unsolicited phone
calls to people to sell stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The stock was in fact worthless, Spitzer said, and the company
never went public. About 90 investors lost between $10,000 and
$250,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best thing you can do when someone calls you with promises
of doubling or tripling your money with a hot stock tip is to hang
up the phone,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrescu faces eight counts of second-degree grand larceny, six
counts of third-degree grand larceny, 14 counts of violating New
York securities laws, and other charges. If convicted, he could
face up to 15 years in prison on each count of second-degree grand
larceny.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance's top salesman, Vikram Randhawa, faces six counts
each of second- and third-degree grand larceny, as well as
violations of securities laws and other charges. He also faces up
to 15 years if convicted of the grand larceny charges.
</P>
<P>
   Three others, Pammi Lamba, Zuher Khalfan and Hamir Ramolia, are
charged with one count of scheming to defraud and violating
securities laws. They face up to four years on each count, if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   All the defendants pleaded innocent at their arraignments in
state Supreme Court in Nassau County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1446 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki Helps NY Conservative Party  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- At the same time Gov. George Pataki is
backing Rudolph Giuliani's Republican Senate bid against Hillary
Rodham Clinton, he is helping raise money for the Conservative
Party -- even though it might support a vote-splitting alternative
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In a fund-raising letter obtained Thursday by The Associated
Press, the Republican governor asks for donations to the
Conservatives ''so they can fight Hillary Clinton's $25 million
campaign machine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long also is courting
potential alternatives to the New York City mayor. Most political
experts believe a separate Conservative Party candidate could drain
votes away from Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
also collect votes on third-party ballot lines. No Republican
running for statewide office has won in New York since 1974 without
the support of the small Conservative Party, including Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Long's displeasure with Giuliani stems from the mayor's
acceptance of backing from the state's Liberal Party. Giuliani also
has refused to support a ban on what critics call ''partial-birth''
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said Thursday that the governor
has been sending fund-raising letters to help the Conservative
Party ever since he became governor.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility that helping the Conservative Party
could help elect Clinton, McKeon said: ''We remain hopeful that the
mayor will be able to work out his issues with the Conservative
Party and that he'll be able to run on the Conservative line.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the Giuliani campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the governor and the mayor have been chilly
since 1994 when Giuliani crossed party lines to back Democrat Mario
Cuomo against Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki endorsed Giuliani's Senate bid last year only after
appeals from national and state party leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
