<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 274: Dow Up 28  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks plunged today, dragging the
Nasdaq composite index lower for a fourth straight session.
Old-fashioned industrial stocks rose, keeping the Dow in positive
territory. With less than an hour of trading left, the Nasadaq
composite index was down 274.79 at 4,355.69.
</P>
<P>
   hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Nasdaq was
down 191.22 at 4,453.45, on track for its one of its worst
performances ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 28.31 at 11,047.03, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 0.05 at 1,490.54.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have been in a slide since March 10, when the
Nasdaq closed at a record high of 5,048.62. At its current level,
the Nasdaq is within market watchers' definition of a correction --
a reversal of an upward trend.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are selling off shares of the companies that have
performed especially well this year, hoping to capture profits.
Today, wireless data company Qualcomm fell 11\ to 146\, and network
gear maker Cisco Systems fell 3 5/16 to 72}.
</P>
<P>
   Cabletron, a maker of network switches and software, plunged 19]
to 28] after saying it anticipates a first-quarter loss of $25
million to $45 million as it restructures itself into four
operating companies. Goldman Sachs cut its rating on Cabletron
stock to ''market perform'' from ''market outperform.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, aerospace company United Technologies rose 3\ to 60~;
3M rose 3 to 90|; and Coca-Cola rose 2 15/16 to 49 13/16, keeping
the Dow in positive territory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology specialists are starting to use the 'v' word --
value,'' said Zane Brown, vice president at Lord, Abbett &AMP; Co.
''People are questioning valuations and are less willing to buy
technology stocks at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco rose 2 5/16 to 11| after financier Carl Icahn said he is
prepared to begin a cash tender offer of $13 a share for 100
million shares. The plans represent his most ambitious effort yet
to gain control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The broad market was rattled by the official announcement that
Tiger Management, a family of hedge funds, will soon shut down.
Tiger, run by renowned money manager Julian H. Robertson Jr., was
once among the world's largest hedge fund families with $21 billion
in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson made his name and his fortune by investing in
undervalued industrial or transportation companies. His resistence
to technology stocks contributed to his funds' downfall -- Tiger
recently had about $6 billion in assets -- and subjected him to
criticism from some investors.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with technology stocks sliding, Robertson's parting shot
to the sector contributed to selling pressure, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The current technology, Internet and telecom craze, fueled by
the performance desires of investors, money managers and even
financial buyers, is unwittingly creating a Ponzi pyramid destined
for collapse,'' Robertson said in a letter to Tiger's limited
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were further unnerved by a report that the U.S.
economy soared to an annual growth rate of 7.3 percent in the final
three months of 1999, the strongest performance in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the gross domestic product -- the country's total
output of goods and services -- was sharper than analysts had
expected, and raised worries that the Federal Reserve will continue
raising interest rates in order to force a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates five times since last June, but so far
has seen little concrete evidence that the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the European Central Bank left key interest rates
unchanged as ebbing inflation, stable exchange rates and moderate
wage contracts calmed policymakers. Most European stock indexes
were lower, however, extending a selloff that began before the
interest rate announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 926.71 million
shares, well ahead of Wednesday's pace. On the Nasdaq, decliners
led by a 7-to-3 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 11.30 to
531.70.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
