<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Move Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices moved higher in
trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as the market
reacted to weather conditions in the crop-growing regions.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures surged as forecasts called for little or no rain
over the weekend for parts of the Midwest. National Weather Service
forecasts had called for normal to above-normal rain in the region
that would end a week of dryness.
</P>
<P>
   The corn market also was boosted by improved export sales,
according to analysts. The U.S. Agriculture Department reported
exports of corn totaled about 780,000 metric tons, a 40 percent
increase over the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Lighter rainfall forecast for the weekend also helped boost
soybean futures prices. Improved sales of soymeal and soyoil also
gave a lift to soybean prices.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures prices were higher on projections by the
International Grains Council of record world wheat consumption this
year. That is expected to spur export sales. Gains were tempered by
poor export figures.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery was 4\ cent higher at $2.55 a bushel; May
corn was 6\ cents higher at $2.33\ a bushel; May oats were 2{ cents
higher at $1.21 a bushel; May soybeans were 8{ cents higher at
$5.37{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle and pork futures prices were higher in trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   April live cattle were .18 cent higher at 71.85 cents a pound;
April feeder cattle were .05 cent higher at 83.80 cents a pound;
April lean hogs were .88 cent higher at 64.15 cents a pound; May
pork bellies were 1.40 cents higher at 97.20 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
