<DOCNO> APW20000330.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Mark Annual Protest Day  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinians from the West Bank and Gaza joined
with Israeli Arabs on Thursday to demonstrate on Land Day, the
annual protest of Israel's confiscation of Arab land. At least 20
people were injured in clashes with Israeli police and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The most violent confrontation came in the Israeli Arab town of
Sakhnin, where police said about 400 demonstrators broke through a
fence surrounding an Israeli army base. Police fired rubber-coated
steel pellets at the demonstrators, wounding 15.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Sakhnin medical center, Dr. Ali Naji, said
12 were lightly wounded, two suffered head wounds and another had a
broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   Five Palestinians were wounded in demonstrations in the West
Bank and Gaza. In the traditionally Arab eastern section of
Jerusalem, about 400 Palestinians marched peacefully, protesting
Jewish settlement expansion in the West Bank and demolition of Arab
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Land Day commemorates the 1976 killings of six Israeli Arabs
during a protest against Israeli land expropriations.
</P>
<P>
   Observance of Land Day was confined at first to Arabs who live
inside Israel, but in recent years, Palestinians in the West Bank
and Gaza have joined in.
</P>
<P>
   A survey released to coincide with Land Day showed that Israeli
Arabs, who make up about one-sixth of the country's population, now
identify themselves more often as Palestinians and less as
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, by the Givat Haviva Center for Peace Research,
showed that 46 percent of Arabs with Israeli citizenship consider
themselves Palestinians who live in Israel, 21 percent see
themselves as Palestinians only, and only 11 percent define
themselves as Israeli Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Answering the same question just four years ago, 38 percent
identified themselves as Israeli Arabs. The survey was based on a
random sample of about 500 people, with a 4 percent margin of
error.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction between Arabs in Israel and Palestinians in the
West Bank and Gaza is mostly geographical. Many Palestinians became
refugees during the war that followed the creation of Israel in
1948, fleeing to the West Bank and Gaza, while relatives stayed
behind and became Israeli citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees came under Israeli control when Israel captured the
West Bank from Jordan and Gaza from Egypt in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Arab leaders complain that their people are treated like
second-class citizens. Their towns and villages top the country's
unemployment lists, municipalities are chronically short of funds,
and city officials charge that they have no land reserves for
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The Land Day clashes came as Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
returned home from Washington for consultations after a round of
peace treaty talks in Washington. The talks are to resume next
week. The two sides have set a May target date for agreeing on a
framework for the treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1616 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Funding of Tobacco Case Argued  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ZUCKERBROD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some Republican lawmakers are fuming that the
Justice Department solicited money from other federal agencies to
pursue a lawsuit against tobacco companies after Congress denied
funding.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm ticked off at them for circumventing the clear legislative
intent,'' said Rep. Hal Rogers, R-Ky., chairman of the Commerce,
Justice, State and Judiciary Appropriations subcommittee that
oversees Justice Department funding.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and others are looking at ways to block the agency from
using any of the money it has been promised by other departments.
And they may try to repeal the law that Attorney General Janet Reno
used to solicit the money.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year denied the Justice Department's request for
$20 million to pay for litigation to try to recover billions of
dollars spent by Medicare and other federal health programs to
treat people with tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department filed the lawsuit anyway in September,
then asked other agencies to help pay for it but never alerted
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno recently told Rogers' subcommittee
she received commitments for a total of $8 million from the
departments of Defense, Veterans Affairs and Health and Human
Services.
</P>
<P>
   Reno contends those agencies incurred costs from treating
smokers, and she cited a 1995 law that allows her department to
take money from other agencies to pay for litigation involving
''unusually high costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department previously has used the law to collect
more than $100 million from the Navy to defend it in a lawsuit
worth more than $2 billion brought by defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and other lawmakers say they are trying to determine if
the law is being applied properly in the tobacco case and whether
the Justice Department and the other agencies were supposed to
notify Congress about the funding plan.
</P>
<P>
   Reno testified she did not believe receiving the money from
other agencies required congressional notification.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members of the House Appropriations Committee only learned
of the arrangement last month when reviewing President Clinton's
2001 budget. They say they noticed the three agencies were seeking
$12 million for the tobacco lawsuit, which prompted them to ask
questions. It was then they then learned the agencies had already
agreed to give the Justice Department $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers says some lawmakers are so upset they might try to repeal
the 1995 law. Among them are Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, who chairs
the Appropriations Committee, and Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
another committee member.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will not be tolerated. It will be fixed,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., also an Appropriations Committee
member, wrote a letter to Stevens urging him not to act rashly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Repealing this provision will tie the Justice Department's
hands and make it difficult for the department to recover billions
of taxpayer dollars lost due to preventable tobacco-related
illnesses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials also are urging lawmakers not to
get rid of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a serious problem for the department and the
government,'' said a Justice Department official who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has said she needs between $10 million and $15 million this
year to pursue the lawsuit, and that the department has spent about
$1.5 million of its own money so far.
</P>
<P>
   Named in the suit are Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Co., American Tobacco Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp.,
Lorillard Tobacco Co., British American Tobacco Ltd., Liggett and
Myers Inc., the Council for Tobacco Research-USA and the Tobacco
Institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1616 </TRAILER>
