<DOCNO> APW20000330.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden Mayor Milton Milan indicted, vows to fight charges  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- The city's mayor was indicted Thursday and
surrendered to federal authorities to face charges that he engaged
in what the U.S. attorney called a ''detailed and systematic reign
of corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19-count indictment charges Milton Milan with accepting cash
bribes, vacation trips, automobiles and home improvement work from
individuals and firms seeking to do business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   It also alleges that former Philadelphia-South Jersey mob boss
Ralph Natale and mob associates ''made direct payments of money and
other benefits'' to Milan. Natale has been cooperating with federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ''Milan put the office of mayor up for sale. Whatever you needed
from him, you could buy from him,'' said U.S. Attorney Robert J.
Cleary.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, 37, a first-term Democrat elected in 1997, had been under
scrutiny by federal authorities in a wide-ranging investigation of
alleged corruption in Camden city government. The indictment
charges him with criminal activity dating as far back as March
1996, when Milan was still a member of the city council.
</P>
<P>
   A defiant Milan pleaded innocent Thursday to all charges and
vowed to clear his name and remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to stay down. I'm going to get back up and
fight. I'm going to continue to be mayor of this city,'' Milan said
Thursday afternoon as he emerged from the federal courthouse after
being freed on $150,000 bail. He said he was going right back to
work because ''I still have time on the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, he asserted that the entire matter was
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a political procedure. What could not be done
politically has been turned into a criminal procedure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City Council member Ali Sloan-El, a persistent critic of Milan,
termed the indictment ''an embarrassment to this city'' and said
the mayor should have stepped down. He stopped short of calling for
his resignation, however.
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon news conference, the U.S. attorney said Milan
''was corrupted from the minute he set foot in City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The mayor designed this pay-to-play system for his own selfish
benefit, and the people of this city be damned,'' Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the investigation is continuing, but would not name
others allegedly involved. He also would not say if additional
arrests were expected.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Milan include mail and wire fraud, extortion
and money laundering. If convicted on all counts, he could be
sentenced to up to 130 years in prison. Each count also carries a
penalty of up to $250,000 in fines, with the exception of the money
laundering conspiracy count, which carries a penalty of up to
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's events followed increasing speculation in recent
weeks that an indictment was imminent. On Wednesday, the grand jury
that has been hearing testimony and examining evidence spent a full
day behind closed doors with federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the media were camped outside Milan's East Camden
home at dawn Thursday. He greeted reporters casually, calling it
''just a regular day,'' hopped on his red Honda motorcycle and
headed for his City Hall office.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:30, he emerged from the building, saying that he had been
indicted and was going to the U.S. attorney's office two blocks
away to turn himself in.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic stopped and people poured out of office buildings to
watch the spectacle as Milan walked up the street, accompanied by
his lawyer, Carlos F. Martir Jr., and a throng of reporters and
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of the federal inquiry had quickened in recent weeks as
city lawmakers were subpoenaed to appear before the grand jury and
questioned about a wide range of issues including city contracts,
organized crime and contractors who performed repairs on Milan's
home.
</P>
<P>
   Milan's name also was mentioned prominently in the recent
federal trial of two men convicted as leaders of a Camden drug
ring. Several witnesses testified that Milan sold drugs in Camden
in the 1980s and bought several shipments of cocaine before
becoming mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The charges made public Thursday do not involve narcotics, and
Greg Reinert, a spokesman for the Camden County Prosecutor's
Office, said he knew of no pending drug-related case or
investigation involving Milan. The statute of limitations on
narcotics activity is five years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Milan is the first Hispanic mayor of this desperately poor city
of 87,000 located on the Delaware River across from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine Corps veteran and former contractor, he was elected to
city council in 1995 and became council president a year later. He
parlayed his popularity into a run for mayor to make Camden
political history.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. attorney's press release on the indictment:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.njusa.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
