<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel: Remove Crown Symbol in Class  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- All symbols of the British
monarchy should be removed from courtrooms in Northern Ireland, a
panel reviewing Northern Ireland's justice system recommended
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, set up as part of the Good Friday Agreement, also
called for scrapping the declaration ''God save the queen'' when
judges enter the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are among some 300 recommendations made by the
Criminal Justice Review Group, set up to examine Northern Ireland's
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Panel member Joanna Shapland said the recommendation to remove
all crown symbols was made so that court employees and those called
as witnesses would feel ''comfortable in that environment wherever
they come from, whichever group or section of Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   But the nine-member panel also tried to find a middle ground in
dealing with symbols, one of the most contentious issues in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The group recommended no change in displaying the royal coat of
arms outside courthouses and said the Union Jack flag should
continue to be flown in line with practice on other government
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson called the report a
''major contribution to the debate on criminal justice issues.'' He
ordered a six-month consultation period to discuss the
recommendations with political parties, the Irish government and
employees in the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The judicial review did not involve matters related to policing.
Mandelson has already promised to unveil legislation to transform
the predominantly Protestant Royal Ulster Constabulary into a new
Police Service of Northern Ireland that would enjoy greater support
from Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp., Ian Paisley
Jr., justice spokesman for the hard-line Protestant Democratic
Unionist Party, complained that removing the crown symbols from
courtrooms would further erode British identity in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But Kevin McNamara, a lawmaker and former Labor Party spokesman
on Northern Ireland, welcomed the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Northern Ireland, the trappings of tradition contained a
none too subtle reminder that the Unionist community became
accustomed to claiming ownership of the justice system and the
right to dispense justice,'' McNamara said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
