<HEADLINE> GM To Unveil 20 New Truck Models  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will roll out 20
new full-size truck models in the next 2{ years as part of a new
focus on the high-profit market segment.
</P>
<P>
   GM officials said Thursday that the company was also bulking up
its full-size truck capacity to 1.7 million vehicles in 2001, up
300,000 vehicles from current levels.
</P>
<P>
   The new models include Chevrolet and GMC full-size pickups and
GMC and Cadillac full-size sport utility vehicles. GM's redesigned
Chevrolet Suburban and GMC Yukon SUVs have done well in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   Full-size trucks carry some of the largest profit margins of any
vehicle an automaker builds. The success of U.S. automakers' trucks
and SUVs have propelled them to record profits in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest automaker also said it would introduce
four-wheel steering on a 2002 model full-size truck. The system
adds a steering rack to the rear axle, and in test models reduced
the turning radius by 20 percent. GM said the system would improve
stability and make pulling a trailer easier.
</P>
</TEXT>
