<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> San Francisco Chronicle Sale OK'd  </HEADLINE>
By BART JANSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department today approved the sale
of the San Francisco Chronicle to The Hearst Corp., the owner of
its century-long rival, after Hearst agreed to sell its flagship
San Francisco Examiner to owners of a local free-distribution
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives Hearst control of the city's dominant newspaper
and ends a joint operating agreement in which the two papers have
split profits evenly for the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Both newspaper deals were to close Friday. After a transition of
four months, the papers will operate independently.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the first time in 35 years, San Francisco will have two
independent daily papers,'' said Joel Klein, assistant attorney
general in charge of the Justice Department's antitrust division.
''Consumers, such as advertisers and readers, will obtain the
benefits of full competition between two daily morning papers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had been investigating the Chronicle sale
because of concerns the Examiner might not survive without the
joint operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came on the same day that losing bidder Clint
Reilly, a former San Francisco mayoral candidate, was to ask a
federal judge in San Francisco to block the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends the Examiner cannot compete with the Chronicle
under the terms of the sale to ExIn LLC, a company formed by Ted
Fang and his family, publishers of the thrice-weekly San Francisco
Independent and Asian Week.
</P>
<P>
   The government's approval did not surprise Reilly's lawyer,
Joseph M. Alioto. ''The antitrust division of the Justice
Department has not enforced the antitrust laws,'' he said, citing
mergers in oil, telecommunications and other industries.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst spokesman Paul Luthringer declined comment. Calls to the
Chronicle's publisher and the Independent were not immediately
returned today.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle board voted in June to sell Chronicle Publishing
Co. and two months later Hearst's $660 million bid was accepted.
Critics said the deal would create a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 25, after months of pressure from the Justice Department
and politicians to improve the terms of the deal, Hearst added
trucks, printing presses and other assets, along with the
Examiner's name and subscriber list.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, after culling through 81 bids, Hearst announced
the sale of the 120-year-old Examiner to Fang, who plans to switch
the afternoon Examiner to morning publication in August and compete
head-to-head with the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, Hearst will subsidize Fang by paying
all costs in the first four months, $16 million in the next eight
months and up to $25 million a year for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement under which the Examiner and Chronicle share
business operations but have separate editorial staffs was not part
of the deal. That agreement was to expire in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's daily circulation is about 456,000 and the
Examiner's is 107,000. They published a joint Sunday edition with a
circulation of almost 579,000. The Independent's circulation is
375,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1631 </TRAILER>
