<HEADLINE> N.J. Mayor Milan Surrenders  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- The mayor was arrested Thursday on federal
charges of taking mob payoffs of cash, vacations and automobiles in
what the U.S. attorney called a ''detailed and systematic reign of
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton Milan, 37, pleaded innocent and was released on $150,000
bail, saying he is ''absolutely not guilty'' and that the case was
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ''What could not be done politically has been turned into a
criminal procedure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Upon his release, Milan said he was going right back to work at
City Hall because ''I still have time on the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Milan was charged in a federal indictment with bribery,
conspiracy, extortion, money laundering and fraud. It alleges Milan
received cash, vacation trips, dinners, automobiles and home
improvements from former Philadelphia mob boss Ralph Natale and his
associates.
</P>
<P>
   Natale has been cooperating with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said Natale paid the money in hopes of winning
city contracts for mob-connected businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Milan put the office of mayor up for sale. Whatever you needed
from him, you could buy from him,'' U.S. Attorney Robert J. Cleary
said Thursday, adding it was a ''detailed and systematic reign of
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment alleges criminal activity dating as far back as
1996, when Milan was a member of the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   Milan is the first Hispanic mayor of this desperately poor city
of 87,000 located on the Delaware River across from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, a first-term Democrat elected in 1997, had been under
scrutiny by federal authorities in a wide-ranging investigation of
alleged corruption in Camden city government.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses at the recent federal trial of two men convicted of
running a multimillion-dollar cocaine ring in Camden said Milan
sold the drug in the 1980s and tipped off dealers about raids after
becoming mayor in 1997. The mayor has not been charged with any
drug offenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
