<HEADLINE> Woman, Four Teens Die in House Fire  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SEEWER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Ohio (AP) -- A fire swept through a two-story house,
killing a 33-year-old woman, her two teen-agers and two of her
fiance's.
</P>
<P>
   The finace, Rodney Bunley, leaped to safety from an upstairs
window. He was treated for a cut to the arm.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters said one of the teen-agers discovered the blaze
Wednesday night and alerted Bunley, who awakened the others and
told them to go to the window as smoke poured into the bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Bunley jumped first, then waited for his family to follow.
</P>
<P>
   When he looked up, his fiancee, Marian Wright, was standing in
the window, assistant Fire Chief Bob Brinkman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He saw her disappear in the smoke,'' Brinkman said. ''He
thought they were coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters believe Wright went back to get the teen-agers,
whose bodies were found in three upstairs bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The dead teen-agers were identified as Marshonda Wright, 13,
Marquis Wright, 16, Rodnina Bunley, 17, and Ravis Bunley, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Chief John Brookman said investigators believe the fire
started on the house's first floor, probably on the front porch,
but were unsure of the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors reported hearing an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We heard this loud crash and then somebody started
screaming,'' said Erin O'Brien, who lives next door. ''There was no
way they could get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima is about 70 miles southwest of Toledo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
