<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 186; Dow Ends Off 38.16  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index narrowly averted its
worst day in history today, ending a volatile session sharply lower
as investors bailed out of stocks that have run up sharply in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq fell 186.49 to close at 4,458.18, a loss of 4.0
percent. With less than 30 minutes remaining in the session, the
Nasdaq was down 289 points before recovering ground as investors
guessed the index had reached rock-bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's plunge carried over to the broader market, dragging
the Dow Jones industrial average into negative territory after it
had risen sharply earlier in the session. The Dow ended down 38.16
at 10,980.56.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 20.56 to 1,487.96.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,563 up, 1,470 down and 450
unchanged. On the Nasdaq, decliners led advancers by a 3-to-1
margin.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.17 billion shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.04
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 14.83 to
528.17.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have been in a slide since March 10, when the
Nasdaq closed at a record high of 5,048.62. Today, several factors
derailed the sector, pushing the Nasdaq well into market watchers'
definition of a correction -- a reversal of an upward trend.
</P>
<P>
   At the core, investors were continuing a selloff of stocks that
have performed especially well this year, hoping to capture
profits. Today, wireless data company Qualcomm and network gear
maker Cisco Systems fell steeply.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, with the end of the first quarter looming on
Friday, mutual fund managers dumped technology stocks so quarterly
reports won't show faltering high-tech names.
</P>
<P>
   The selling pressure knocked the Nasdaq below 4,450 -- a
so-called technical benchmark that prompted a wave of
computer-driven selling. Only as the Nasdaq headed toward 4,400 did
investors step back into the market, bringing the index back from
its nadir.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors' increasing jitters over the highly
volatile technology sector caused the drop.
</P>
<P>
   ''Aside from the technical speak on the Nasdaq, the
psychological nerve of the market is slowly beginning to unravel a
bit,'' said Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George
K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The technology selloff also followed the announcement that Tiger
Management, a family of hedge funds, will soon shut down. Tiger,
run by renowned money manager Julian H. Robertson Jr., was once
among the world's largest hedge fund families with $21 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson made his name and his fortune by investing in
undervalued industrial or transportation companies. His resistence
to technology stocks contributed to his funds' downfall -- Tiger
recently had about $6 billion in assets -- and subjected him to
criticism from some investors.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's parting shot to the sector contributed to today's
selling pressure, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The current technology, Internet and telecom craze, fueled by
the performance desires of investors, money managers and even
financial buyers, is unwittingly creating a Ponzi pyramid destined
for collapse,'' Robertson said in a letter to Tiger's limited
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in technology marred a strong advance by many old-line
industrial companies. United Technologies, 3M and Coca-Cola rose
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology specialists are starting to use the 'v' word --
value,'' said Zane Brown, vice president at Lord, Abbett &AMP; Co.
''People are questioning valuations and are less willing to buy
technology stocks at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco rose after financier Carl Icahn said he is prepared to
begin a cash tender offer of $13 a share for 100 million shares.
The plans represent his most ambitious effort yet to gain control
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were further unnerved by a report that the U.S.
economy soared to an annual growth rate of 7.3 percent in the final
three months of 1999, the strongest performance in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the gross domestic product -- the country's total
output of goods and services -- was sharper than analysts had
expected, and raised worries that the Federal Reserve will continue
raising interest rates in order to force a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates five times since last June, but so far
has seen little concrete evidence that the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the European Central Bank left key interest rates
unchanged as ebbing inflation, stable exchange rates and moderate
wage contracts calmed policymakers. Most European stock indexes
were lower, however, extending a selloff that began before the
interest rate announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
