<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani significantly outpaces Clinton in fund-raising  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani continues to
significantly outpace Hillary Rodham Clinton in money-raising for
their U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani raised about $7 million during the first three months
of this year, compared to a little over $4 million raised by
Clinton, according to preliminary figures released Thursday by
their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the mayor raised nearly $12 million, compared to the
first lady's $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   With seven months left to go before the election, Giuliani has
already raised more money than Chuck Schumer raised in total for
his successful Senate campaign in '98, putting the Clinton-Giuliani
race easily on track to be the most expensive New York campaign
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ''When a candidate does this well raising money, it's reflective
of the fact that the candidate has tremendous support,'' said
Giuliani's campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the candidate with the most money does not always
win. Recent high-profile races in which Republicans have outspent
Democrats but then lost include Al D'Amato's campaign against
Schumer, Oliver North's campaign against U.S. Sen. Charles Robb of
Virginia, and Michael Huffington's campaign against U.S. Sen.
Dianne Feinstein of California.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman Howard Wolfson said he was happy with her
fund-raising results and unsurprised that Giuliani raised more.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had an outstanding period,'' Wolfson said, adding:
''They raised more than us in the last period. Given the strength
of their secret fund-raising campaign, I suppose that will be true
this period as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign has complained about the Giuliani campaigns
refusal to release the texts of their direct-mail fund-raising
solicitations. Teitelbaum on Thursday said there was no need for
the Giuliani campaign to release the letters because the Clinton
campaign had already made them public.
</P>
<P>
   Neither campaign had estimates of their cash on hand, which
would reflect how much has been spent out of the money they have
raised.
</P>
<P>
   Formal filings of contributions and expenditures for the Jan. 1
through March 31 period must be filed with the Federal Election
Commission by April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum said the money came from every county in New York,
and every state in the country, with roughly half from in-state
contributors. He said the average contribution was $70.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson did not have a breakdown for the money Clinton raised,
but in the last filings, both candidates had raised about half
their money from out of state donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 1719 </TRAILER>
