</P>
<P>
   Tiger To Liquidate Funds Worth $6B
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Julian H. Robertson Jr., a scion in financial
markets, told investors today he is liquidating the $6 billion
Tiger Management investment funds, calling the current market
frenzy for technology stocks a ''Ponzi pyramid destined for
collapse.'' Robertson, who had used a strategy of picking
undervalued industrial stocks, took 18 years to build Tiger into
the largest hedge fund family in the world with assets of $23
billion. Tiger's demise took just 18 months. Robertson's reversal
of fortune highlights the radical shift in the markets to
technology and Internet stocks and away from traditional
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn Seeks 100M Shares of Nabisco
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financier Carl Icahn said today he is prepared
to begin a cash tender offer of $13 a share for 100 million shares
of Nabisco Group Holdings Corp. He said he would consider selling
the entire company if he gains control of it. The plans that Icahn
outlined in a letter today represent his most ambitious effort yet
to gain control of the company that was created when RJR Nabisco
Holdings spun off its cigarette holdings in the face of mounting
litigation against tobacco companies. The Parsippany, N.J.-based
Nabisco Group Holdings' sole asset is an 80.5 percent stake in
Nabisco Holdings Corp., the food company that makes Ritz crackers,
Oreo cookies and Planters nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Economy Finishes 1999 Strong
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The red-hot U.S. economy, powered by heavy
spending by consumers and the federal government, was roaring ahead
at an annual rate of 7.3 percent in the final three months of 1999,
the fastest growth rate in nearly 16 years, the government reported
today. The October-December rate of increase in the gross domestic
product, the nation's total output of goods and services,
represented the strongest quarterly performance for this long
economic expansion, which began in March 1991.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Chronicle Sale OK'd
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department today approved the sale
of the San Francisco Chronicle to The Hearst Corp., the owner of
its century-long rival, after Hearst agreed to sell its flagship
San Francisco Examiner to owners of a local free-distribution
newspaper. The deal gives Hearst control of the city's dominant
newspaper and ends a joint operating agreement in which the two
papers have split profits evenly for the past 35 years. Both
newspaper deals were to close tomorrow. After a transition of four
months, the papers will operate independently.
</P>
<P>
   GM To Unveil 20 New Truck Models
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will roll out 20
new full-size truck models in the next 2{ years as part of a new
focus on the high-profit market segment. GM officials said today
that the company was also bulking up its full-size truck capacity
to 1.7 million vehicles in 2001, up 300,000 vehicles from current
levels. The new models include Chevrolet and GMC full-size pickups
and GMC and Cadillac full-size sport utility vehicles. GM's
redesigned Chevrolet Suburban and GMC Yukon SUVs have done well in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Study: Contaminated Chickens Missed
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A study of chicken slaughtering plants finds
that one in every 100 birds passes by government inspectors with
fecal contamination on it or signs of poultry diseases that
threaten human health. Agriculture Department officials who
released the study today said the contamination rate is relatively
low but they expect to cut it further under an experimental new
inspection system. Chicken carcasses are subject to additional
cleansing after they pass the inspectors, so all fecal material
should be eliminated before the meat reaches consumers, industry
officials say. The study was conducted over the past year at 16
poultry plants that have agreed to take part in the new inspection
system.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot Names New COO
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Home Depot named Mark Baker its chief operating
officer and an executive vice president today. Baker will have
responsibility for operations of Home Depot's 883 U.S. stores. Nine
Home Depot divisions will report to Baker, whose duties also will
include marketing and communications, proprietary brands and Apex
Supply, a plumbing company Home Depot owns. Baker, who began his
career with Home Depot as vice president of merchandising in the
Midwest, was most recently president of the chain's mid-south and
southern divisions.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan To Join Japan Net Bank
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- U.S. investment bank J.P. Morgan and Co. said today
it will join an online bank venture led by Sony Corp. that
eventually will allow customers to make transactions through Sony's
PlayStation2 video game console. J.P. Morgan will spend $14.2
million for a 4 percent stake in the Sony-led group, which also
includes Japan's Sakura Bank Ltd., which will invest $56.9 million
for a 16 percent stake. Sony will contribute $284.4 million, or 80
percent of the bank's $355.5 million start-up capital.
</P>
<P>
   5 Charged in N.Y. Investment Scam
</P>
<P>
   FARMINGDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- Five members of a Long Island ''boiler
room'' operation bilked investors out of $3.2 million, using the
proceeds for Hawaiian vacations and Atlantic City gambling trips,
state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said today. The owner, chief
salesman and three brokers of Renaissance Capital Management, Inc.,
were arrested this week and accused in a 38-count indictment with
grand larceny, securities fraud and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Europe's key markets took their lead from a
technology sell-off in the United States, falling an average of 2
percent today. Analysts also attributed the poor performances to a
decision by the European Central Bank on Thursday to leave its key
short-term interest rates unchanged. Technology stocks Ericsson,
Nokia and Siemens were particularly hard hit. In domestic markets,
London's FTSE-100 Share Index closed down 153.6 points at 6,445.2;
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 219.87 points to 7,644.89, and
Milan's MIBtel Index was down 880 points to 31,722. The Dow Jones
Euro Stoxx Index was down 14.98 points,at 440.25. The Dow Jones
Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell points 11.4 points
to 391.66.
</P>
