<HEADLINE> 30-year Mortgage Rates Hold Steady  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rates on 30-year mortgages held steady this
week but are still up more than 1 percentage point from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The average interest rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages was
unchanged from last week at 8.23 percent, according to a survey
released Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage company. This time a
year ago, 30-year mortgages stood at 6.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-February, the rates on 30-year mortgages hit a 3{-year
high of 8.38 percent. That was the highest since a 8.42 percent
rate for the week ending July 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing, were
also unchanged this week at 7.84 percent, matching last week's
level.
</P>
<P>
   On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an
average initial rate of 6.76 percent this week, down slightly from
6.78 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three
types of mortgages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
