<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Space Station 'Lifeboat' Tested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) -- A prototype ''lifeboat''
for the international space station made its highest and longest
test flight on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The unmanned X-38 -- a wedge-shaped craft with no wings and no
engine -- was dropped from under the wing of a B-52 bomber at 39,000
feet and parachuted safely to the desert floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vehicle flew just about as we expected,'' said Bob Baron,
X-38 project manager at NASA's Dryden Flight Research Center. ''We
purposely put in some pitches and rolls. All that looked very, very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA is working to develop a similar vehicle that the astronauts
aboard the space station could use to return to Earth in an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   For the first years of the space station, astronauts will have
to rely on a three-man Soyuz capsule for emergency escapes. NASA
hopes to put a seven-person lifeboat on the space station in 2005
or 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's test was the fifth free flight of the $85 million
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
