<HEADLINE> House Committee Passes Hmong Bill  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER, 
V0850-----
r w *1153AP-Hmong-Citizensh     03-30 0346
*1153 AP-Hmong-Citizenship,0345   
House Committee Passes Hmong Bill   
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Judiciary Committee Thursday
unanimously passed legislation that would make it easier for
America's former Laotian allies during the Vietnam War to become
U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, Chairman Henry Hyde said, is needed ''in recognition
of their compelling circumstances and extraordinary sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 Hmong and Lao veterans packed the hearing, dressed
in green military fatigues. They applauded when Hyde announced that
the committee had passed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, sponsored by Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., waives
the English-language requirement for Hmong and Laotians who were
recruited by the CIA in Laos for covert military actions.
Supporters say the Hmong, an ethnic group in Laos, have found it
difficult to learn English because their language did not have a
written form until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, R-Ill., called the Hmong a ''tribal, semi-nomadic''
society and displayed an illustrated ''story cloth'' that Hmong use
to communicate their history and culture from one generation to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were recruited often as boy soldiers, giving the best
years of their lives to the United States secret army in Laos,''
Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were fierce allies of American forces and rescued many
American pilots,'' said Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, the top
Democrat on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has passed the legislation in previous years, only
to see it stalled elsewhere in Congress. But Philip Smith,
Washington director of Lao Veterans of America, said the chances
are much better this time because 103 members of Congress,
including Hyde, have signed on as co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our expectation is that it will pass the full House soon,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Hmong and Lao veterans marched to another House
building to see their governor, Jesse Ventura, who was testifying
on another issue Thursday but supports the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
