<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinics for Poor Cutting Back  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Warning of possible closures, a panel of
experts urged the government Thursday to spend $2.5 billion to keep
afloat public hospitals and clinics stretched thin by large numbers
of uninsured patients and the loss of paying patients to HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ''These trends are beginning to place unparalleled strain on the
health care safety net in many parts of the country,'' the report
by the Institute of Medicine cautioned in recommending the infusion
of federal aid over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many providers may be unable to survive the current
environment,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Local health care providers applauded the recommendations by the
IOM panel of private health experts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very simple -- you can't provide care to everyone without
having sufficient revenue,'' said Robert Sillen, executive director
of the Santa Clara Valley Health and Hospital System in California.
</P>
<P>
   The term ''safety net'' refers to organizations that are legally
obligated to provide care to people who cannot afford it. They
include some 700 community health centers and 1,300 public
hospitals. Though estimates vary, more than 8 million Americans get
basic health care from these providers.
</P>
<P>
   The IOM panel also noted that federal oversight of safety net
providers is fragmented and recommended establishing a single, new
agency to monitor them.
</P>
<P>
   Currently some nine agencies are responsible for programs
affecting safety net providers, but there's no coordination, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Many safety net patuents are covered by Medicaid, a
federal-state health program for the poor that reimburses safety
net providers and is the single biggest source of revenue for them.
</P>
<P>
   But over the last decade, many states have converted Medicaid to
managed care to cut costs, inviting health maintenance
organizations and other private providers to compete for Medicaid
patients.
</P>
<P>
   While paying patients benefited from having more choices in
medical care, public hospitals and other safety net providers lost
6 percent of their Medicaid patients, the IOM report said.
</P>
<P>
   Some hospitals and clinics have joined managed care groups to
compete, but reimbursement rates for Medicaid patients under those
plans are sometimes less than what it costs to provide care, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, welfare reform laws passed in 1996 and the balanced
budget act the following year reduced federal subsidies for public
health centers.
</P>
<P>
   With this backdrop of financial pressures, the number of
uninsured who rely on safety net providers grew by 20 percent
between 1988 and 1998 and now numbers an estimated 44 million, or
nearly one in five Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The problems have already frayed the safety net -- in Washington
D.C., where 15 publicly funded clinics once operated, only 5
remain, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   It also cited a study of 400 local health departments that
showed 23 percent of urban centers and 17 percent of nonurban
centers had stopped providing basic health care services.
</P>
<P>
   Most safety net providers have been able to survive, relying on
a patchwork of federal, state and local grants and private money,
the report said. But experts warned many will fail or be forced to
cut back care.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Gage, president of the National Association of Public
Hospitals and Health Systems that represents 100 hospitals, said
some institutions are cutting back hours, closing clinics,
eliminating support services and charging copayments for doctor
visits that were frees.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one want to go down this slippery slope, but when you're
losing money on every case, it's hard to keep going,'' Gage said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Institute of Medicine Web site: http://www.iom.edu/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1749 </TRAILER>
