<DOCNO> APW20000330.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss To Protest Austrian Visit  </HEADLINE>
By ONNA CORAY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- Jewish organizations said Thursday they
will join Swiss anti-racist and left-wing groups in protests
against a state visit by Austrian Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel,
whose government includes a far-right party.
</P>
<P>
   Former Swiss foreign minister Rene Felber said he was ''pained
and embarrassed'' by the government's invitation to Schuessel, at a
time when Switzerland has been struggling to sort out its own
wartime actions. Schuessel arrives on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have only just emerged from a series of painful events
relating to our past,'' Felber told Le Matin newspaper, in
reference to allegations that neutral Switzerland colluded with the
Nazis during the World War II era.
</P>
<P>
   ''And yet again, we are using false excuses to conceal the fact
that we don't dare to distance ourselves from a government
supported by a party whose head -- regardless of what he says --
represents Nazi or Neo-Nazi tendencies,'' said Felber, a social
democrat.
</P>
<P>
   European Union member nations have sought to isolate Austria
since Schuessel's government came to power in February, including
Joerg Haider's Freedom Party. Haider has made -- and since
apologized for -- statements in sympathy with aspects of the Nazi
regime.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian chancellor traditionally makes his first state
visit to neighboring Switzerland, which is not an EU member. The
Swiss government plans to accord Schuessel full diplomatic honors.
</P>
<P>
   Sigi Feigl, honorary president of the Jewish community in
Zurich, said he had rejected an invitation to attend a reception
with Schuessel in a Zurich hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ''By becoming the first host to the Austrian chancellor who has
compromised with the far-right, Switzerland dissociates itself from
the Europeans and accords him deplorable and condemnable support,''
said a statement from the European Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The congress complained that a half-page advertisement featuring
the statement had been rejected by one of Switzerland's main
newspapers, the Neue Zuercher Zeitung.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's acting editor, Hansrudolf Kamer, said the paper
refused to accept the text, calling it factually incorrect and
insulting to Schuessel. He said it was wrong to maintain that
Switzerland was an accomplice to right-wing extremism purely by
receiving the Austrian chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   The highly respected Neue Zuercher Zeitung -- traditionally
sympathetic toward the business and banking establishment -- has
criticized the EU stance toward Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Environment ministers from France, Belgium and Italy called for
Austria's continued isolation at a meeting in Brussels on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
