<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Israel to Slow Plans  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is urging Israel to
slow its drive for international help in a July withdrawal from
Lebanon, a U.S. official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy was planning a trip to the
United Nations in an attempt to arrange international intervention
to ensure a smooth retreat.
</P>
<P>
   But at the behest of the Clinton administration, Israel has
agreed to at least a temporary delay, said the official, who spoke
on condition of anonymity. Levy also will delay his trip,
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak reaffirmed his intention to
pull out of a security zone in southern Lebanon after President
Clinton and Syrian President Hafez Assad failed on Sunday to reopen
Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. request for a delay is intended to allow more time for
Assad to change his strategy and to offer new proposals to Israel,
as Clinton called for at a news conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the pro-goverment Egyptian newspaper Al-Gomuria quoted
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak as saying en route home that he
had told Clinton at the White House on Tuesday that Assad ''is
unable to offer any compromises.''
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak also was quoted as saying Barak had told him he wanted
some land claimed by Syria and ''my answer to him was that is
impossible. I have repeated this in front of Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria objects to a unilateral Israeli withdrawal. It seeks,
instead, to have an Israeli pullback included in an overall
agreement with Israel in which Syria also would recover the Golan
Heights, a strategic highground it lost in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerrillas in southern Lebanon have slain Israeli
soldiers. One of Barak's main reasons in seeking an agreement with
Syria is to avoid more losses by giving up the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
   If Israel withdraws without an agreement, it may have less of a
need for a treaty with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman, James B. Foley, said the United
States would like to see all foreign forces -- presumably Syrian
troops as well as Israeli soldiers -- quit Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But Foley said the administration preferred that an Israeli
pullback be part of an overall settlement.
</P>
<P>
   While the Israeli-Syrian negotiations that broke down in
mid-January have not resumed, ''the process is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say whether the United States would make
proposals of its own to Syria in an attempt to bridge differences
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Syria agrees to rein in Hezbollah guerrillas in south
Lebanon, a withdrawal from a border zone Israel occupies to protect
its northern towns could lead to an escalation of the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is in the Israeli interest,'' Levy said Wednesday in
Jerusalem, ''if international elements will take steps to ensure
the quiet and prevent a deterioration of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Wednesday said Israel had offered to relinquish a
''significant'' portion of the contested Golan Heights but Assad
was simply stonewalling on terms for peace.
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough that Assad say, ''I don't like your position''
and demand all the land Syria lost in the 1967 Middle East war,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once you know what the other side wants and you don't think
you can do it, then you ought to come up with some alternative way
of trying to respond to the underlying concerns that are behind the
position,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1753 </TRAILER>
