<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Seeking China Trade Deal  </HEADLINE>
By FREDERIC J. FROMMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calling it the ''biggest economic decision of
the 21st century,'' Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura urged Congress to
pass China trade legislation during a hearing Thursday on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
	   ''If you don't forge ahead to open China's markets, rest assured
the window of opportunity will be lost,'' he told members of the
House Ways and Means Committee. ''The Europeans would like nothing
better than for the U.S. Congress to continue fussing over this
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration hoped that Ventura's star appeal
would help win support for granting permanent normal trade
relations with China. The legislation, which would open the way for
China to join the World Trade Organization, faces an uncertain
future in the House.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents include labor unions, critics of China's human rights
record. Leaders of the Reform Party, which Ventura quit last month,
also oppose normalizing relations with China.
</P>
<P>
	   House Democratic Whip David Bonior of Michigan, who is leading
the opposition, released a letter signed by 18 lawmakers who in the
past have voted in favor of annual renewal of China's trade
privileges. These legislators said they would oppose permanent
normal trade status for China, which would eliminate Congress'
annual review.
</P>
<P>
	   ''We are all at this moment united in our opposition,'' said the
letter, which the group addressed to President Clinton. Also
signing the letter was Rep. Joe Baca, D-Calif., whose predecessor,
the late Rep. George Brown, had voted in favor of the annual
renewal of China's trade privleges.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris Padilla, a spokesman for the Business Coalition for
U.S.-China Trade, the main lobbying group in support of permanent
trade relations, questioned whether opponents would be able to
produce as many votes as they are claiming.
</P>
<P>
	   Both sides have conceded the House vote will be extremely close.
The administration is expected to have an easier time in winning
Senate passage of the legislation to scrap the annual review of
China's trade privileges.
</P>
<P>
	   ''We don't have to approve of their human rights record to help
improve them,'' Ventura said. ''Opening their doors to our
businesses practices, our culture, and our democratic ideas will
open their process.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ventura said that such a deal would help feed the Chinese,
adding, ''Isn't simple food on the table human rights?''
</P>
<P>
	   It would also help U.S. businesses and farmers, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ''I don't want protectionist feelings in Congress to stand in
the way of progress for Minnesota,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
	   Members of the committee threw mostly softballs and platitudes
toward the celebrity-governor.
</P>
<P>
	   ''You just hit a home run,'' declared Committee Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas. ''...You today have made this a tripartisan
effort.''
</P>
<P>
	   ''I thought it was a body-slam,'' Rep. William Thomas, R-Calif.,
told the former professional wrestler.
</P>
<P>
	   But the biggest booster was Minnesota's own Rep. Jim Ramstad, a
Republican, who said that if every member of Congress had been
present for Ventura's testimony, ''I don't have any question that
we would pass PNTR for China.''
</P>
<P>
	   Only one member of the panel asked Ventura a pointed question.
</P>
<P>
	   ''Does it concern you that some corporations will go to China to
get low-paying jobs?'' asked Rep. William Coyne, D-Pa.
</P>
<P>
	   ''If they're our corporations, it's our job to look after them,
right?'' Ventura answered, adding that in Minnesota, the problem
isn't unemployment but too few employees.
</P>
<P>
	   Ventura also pushed for normalized relations with Cuba, noting
he had brought it up in a meeting with Clinton last month.
</P>
<P>
	   ''I told him I'm tired of feeling like a criminal every time I
want a Cuban cigar,'' the governor quipped.
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: World Trade Organization: http://www.wto.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1804 </TRAILER>
