<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Pledge $1.8B for Balkans  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL AMES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Pledging to end delays in
reconstruction efforts in the Balkans, international donors
promised $2.4 billion Thursday to revitalize the region's economy
and bolster its shaky democracies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money will go to 35 ''quick-start'' projects due to
start this year, including the repair and construction of roads,
bridges, power-grids and water supply networks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're coming to the stage where projects become concrete
reality, become construction sites,'' said Bodo Hombach,
coordinator of the international Stability Pact for the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The first project gets underway Friday: a $7 million plan to
improve a Kosovo-Macedonia border crossing by building parking
lots.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we say quick start, we mean it,'' said Daniel Hamilton,
the Stability Pact coordinator for the U.S. State Department. He
said another venture to improve Macedonia's highway network will
begin in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $1.8 billion sought for this year's projects,
the 44 nations and 36 international organizations attending the
Stability Pact conference pledged an additional $600 million to
prepare for projects over the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've done well, we've exceeded expectations,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the international help, Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria,
Croatia, Macedonia and Romania have committed to democracy and
economic changes to attract private investment.
</P>
<P>
   Hombach said the international aid should help attract Western
companies to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''My main task as of tomorrow will be mobilizing private
investment,'' Hombach told a news conference. ''I don't think state
money can really deal with the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the government aid is coming from Europe. The European
Union's head office pledged $530 million, and the 15 EU nations
made individual pledges. The United States pledged $77.65 million.
</P>
<P>
   As well as the economic aid, the money will also fund
democracy-building projects such as training for local government
officials, improving history teaching and support for free media.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia was excluded from the package as donor nations continue
to demand Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic bow to demands for
more democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as Milosevic is in power, there will be no cooperation
with the federal government,'' said Hombach, adding that aid for
projects in Serbia could be freed up ''the moment that Serbia is
democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hombach said authorities in some EU nations planned to
expand aid to Serb cities run by opposition mayors by financing a
temporary ''humanitarian'' bridge across the Danube in the city of
Novi Sad to replace those destroyed by NATO bombing last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1805 </TRAILER>
