<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Challenger: Chavez Is Corrupt  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A fellow ex-coup leader who is
challenging President Hugo Chavez for Venezuela's highest office on
Thursday accused the head of Congress and a key Chavez ally of
being a ''delinquent.''
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Arias, a former army officer who helped Chavez stage
his 1992 coup attempt, personally delivered a series of corruption
charges against congressional head Luis Miquilena to the attorney
general's office in Caracas, the capital. The charges stem from a
government printing contract Miquilena allegedly gave to a company
in which he holds shares.
</P>
<P>
   ''A country cannot keep a congressional president who is a
delinquent,'' Arias told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Miquilena dismissed the allegations, insisting Arias was the
corrupt one because he mishandled funds in the Zulia state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Arias was governor of the oil-rich state of Zulia until earlier
this month. He is one of three former army officers who helped
Chavez carry out the coup attempt but who recently broke with the
president, saying he has betrayed the original goals of their
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   Because Arias is not associated with the traditional political
parties that Chavez's leftist coalition has all but destroyed, he
is seen to have a chance at victory in May 28 presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Arias said he ''deplored'' Chavez's decision to use Miquilena
and Cuban leader Fidel Castro as ''guides for running a country.''
</P>
<P>
   A new constitution pushed through by Chavez last year requires
most public offices, including the presidency, to be
''relegitimated'' through new elections. Chavez took office just
over a year ago promising to carry out a ''social revolution'' and
rule in favor of the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1819 </TRAILER>
