<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House approves millions to aid lobstermen  </HEADLINE>
cbstfpr
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. House Thursday approved $8.6 million
to help lobstermen hit hard by the mysterious deaths of lobster in
the Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The money will pay for additional research into the cause of the
massive die-off and create a revolving loan fund to help lobstermen
refinance their business obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriation was part of a $13 billion package of money for
the Pentagon, Colombia and recovery from Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   While the money is helpful, it's also not nearly enough, said
Rep. Christopher Shays.
</P>
<P>
   ''The House appropriated $40 million for citrus growers to
compensate for lost production due to the unexpected breakout of
citrus canker. Like them, the Long Island Sound lobstermen deserve
our help,'' the Stamford Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not merely a bad year for the lobster crop on the Long
Island Sound. It is the disappearance of an entire species. It is a
disaster no one anticipated and therefore no one prepared for,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is working on a similar version of the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
