<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Unveils Teacher Training Plan  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- On a campaign day that took him from finger
painting to fund raising, George W. Bush borrowed from former rival
John McCain and the Clinton administration in formulating ideas for
supporting teachers and ensuring classroom discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican presidential candidate, also gave a glimpse
Thursday into how he will select a No. 2 for his ticket as he
rolled out another $3 billion in federal education proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning at Milwaukee's Fritsche Middle School with Gov.
Tommy Thompson, Bush was asked about the open speculation that
surrounded Bob Dole's 1996 pick of a running mate. Thompson, who
was passed over by Dole, had complained at the time about the
indignity of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had not yet put a strategy in place, but promised
''a quiet effort to screen potential candidates'' by a selection
committee of people who can ''keep their counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There does not need to be a lot of needless leaks, rumors and
gossip,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   In a discussion with a dozen education policymakers in the
Fritsche library, Bush enumerated his plan for a big expansion of
the ''troops to teachers'' program for turning highly skilled
retired military personnel into math and science teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senator McCain talked a lot about this in the course of the
primaries and I appreciate him bringing this issue to our
collective attention,'' Bush said of the program begun during
President Clinton's first term. Bush proposed increasing funds from
$2.4 million to $30 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a signal that says there are a lot of good people who
should be welcomed into the ranks of teachers,'' said Bush, the
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other proposals, which would bring the total cost of
Bush's education agenda to $13.4 billion over five years were:
</P>
<P>
   --An additional $400 million each year for state programs that
currently get $2 billion annually from Washington to recruit new
teachers or retrain existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   --A tax deduction of up to $400 a year for teachers who buy
school supplies with their own money.
</P>
<P>
   --A ''Teacher Protection Act'' to ''shield teachers from
meritless lawsuits when they enforce reasonable classroom rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democrat battling Bush in this
presidential contest for the upper hand on education, has, by
contrast, proposed to boost the federal investment in education by
$115 billion over 10 years -- more than four times Bush's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real centerpiece of his agenda is an enormous tax cut that
may force him to go back on these promises,'' said Gore campaign
spokesman Doug Hattaway. ''He hasn't said how he's going to pay for
the tax cut without cutting education programs, dipping into Social
Security or dragging us back to deficit spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed the spending gap. ''His motto is, 'Vote for me;
I'll spend more money.'''
</P>
<P>
   Taking questions from reporters, Bush confessed that he has not
yet opened his census form. ''I've been traveling, as you know,''
he said. But he sympathized with those Americans facing the ''long
form'' census, which has 53 questions that some congressional
Republicans have criticized as intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want as accurate a count as possible but I can understand
why people don't want to give over that information to the
government. And if I have the long form I'm not so sure I would
either,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   On Gore's campaign chairman, Tony Coelho, the subject of a
criminal investigation into past financial dealings, Bush said
''Mr. Coelho ought to be innocent until proven guilty, of course.
But the vice president ought to be taking this seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not addressed the substance of the allegations against
Coelho, saying only that Coelho was doing a good job on the
campaign and would remain on staff.
</P>
<P>
   Before a 45-minute flight to Milwaukee, Bush toured a preschool
class at Locust Lane Elementary school in Eau Claire, Wis. The
business-suit-clad candidate mischievously eyed the finger paints.
''No, I better not,'' he said. But within minutes he was back at
the paint station, rolling paint-smeared marbles across white
paper.
</P>
<P>
   He beamed as he showed of his artwork: ''A Rorschach test of
me!''
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, he had toured Milwaukee's Harley-Davidson plant
because, as spokeswoman Karen Hughes said, it is ''a symbol of
Wisconsin pride.'' Bush also headlined a $75-per-plate benefit
dinner for the Waukesha County GOP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1823 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Determined in D.C.  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia's U.N. ambassador decided Thursday to
go it alone --at least on the trip from the airport -- when all 15
members of the Security Council made an unprecedented visit to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than sharing a bus with some of the other members, Sergey
Lavrov took a Russian Embassy car to the State Department, the
first stop in a hectic schedule that also took them to the Capitol
and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Courteous but outspoken, and determined not to be overwhelmed by
Washington's power brokers, the ambassadors stepped gingerly onto
the political stage.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in advance if he would be outspoken during the day's
meetings, Lavrov said he was in Washington in a ''private
capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   He elaborated: ''You know that being in a private capacity means
we would be acting on impulses, not instructions, so we'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Lavrov joined his fellow ambassadors on the
bus from the State Department to the Capitol, to avoid getting
caught in Washington traffic. The bus had a police escort.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On a daylong outing from what Lavrov called the boredom of New
York, the ambassadors got a lesson on U.S. history and were treated
as VIPs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like a tourist,'' Lavrov said after listening to Senate
historian Richard Baker. ''I came as a tourist for that lecture,
and I listened as a tourist and I was not bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though several ambassadors insisted repeatedly that they
were in Washington as individuals -- not as THE Security Council --
Sen. Jesse Helms, the host for the day -- managed to get the 15
ambassadors to pose for a class photo with him after a 2{-hour
roundtable with the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, which he
heads.
</P>
<P>
   The main business of the day was U.N. reform, a pet project of
Helms who has been one of the most vocal critics of the world body,
and U.N. peacekeeping, which in the past nine months has expanded
dramatically to Kosovo, East Timor, Sierra Leone and Congo. But
underlying the visit was the frayed relationship between the United
States and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
invited Helms to speak to the Security Council in January and the
senator reciprocated with an invitation to the Capitol. But Lavrov,
among others, did not accept until Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright also extended invitations on an individual basis for a
briefing and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh's U.N. Ambassador Anwarul Chowdhury, the current
Security Council president, told Helms that his visit in January
''was an ice-breaking one.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the dessert served at a lavish lunch -- called ''The
Capitol Dome with white chocolate mousse'' -- he said ''ours ... was
a chocolate-breaking one.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Canadian envoy Robert Fowler ended his serious remarks about
U.N. reform with a personal plea to Helms and the other senators
for a ''a technical contribution'' to the Security Council -- the
timing device in the committee room with green, yellow and red
lights that warns speakers when their time is running out. He said
it could ''significantly streamline'' operations at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is it worth a billion dollars?,'' quipped Sen. Carl Levin of
Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Armed Services
Committee, who also briefed the council members. The United States
contends it owes the United Nations $1 billion though the U.N.
officials say the debt is $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Many Security Council members are frequent visitors to
Washington, and well-versed in American history, but it was the
first trip to Washington for China's new U.N. ambassador, Wang
Yingfan.
</P>
<P>
   During a tour of the Statuary Hall, where the House of
Representatives once met, the Capitol's top tour guide Ted Daniel
told the ambassadors that if they stood in one spot, they could
hear him speak from across the noisy room. They listened -- and
heard him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Origins of the CIA,'' quipped Britain's U.N. Ambassador Jeremy
Greenstock.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the beginning of eavesdropping,'' added Bangladesh's
Chowdhury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1823 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Market Mutual Funds Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market
mutual funds rose by $6.32 billion in the latest week to $1.005
trillion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category rose
by $5.76 billion to $835.29 billion for the week ended Wednesday,
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. Tax-exempt fund
assets rose by $559.5 million to $169.35 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of institutional money market funds fell by $11.64
billion to $698.73 billion for the same period. Among institutional
funds, taxable money market fund assets fell by $11.35 billion to
$646.99 billion; assets of tax-exempt funds fell by $296.7 million
to $51.74 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Total money market assets stood at $1.703 trillion for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.709 trillion to
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 5.38 percent from 5.32 percent the
previous week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
published in Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. The 30-day
average yield rose to 5.31 percent from 5.28 percent, IBC Financial
Data said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day compounded yield rose to 5.53 percent from 5.46
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield rose to
5.45 percent from 5.42 percent, IBC Financial Data said.
</P>
<P>
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
unchanged at 48 days, IBC Financial Data said.
</P>
<P>
   The online service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage
yield available on money market accounts remained unchanged at 2.04
percent as of Wednesday from a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing
checking accounts rose to 0.83 percent from 0.82 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield was 4.88 percent
on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 4.85 percent the
previous week. Yields were 5.32 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 5.31
percent; 5.59 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 5.56 percent; and
6.00 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 5.95 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1833 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0192 </DOCNO>
