<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Seagate Technology Inc., down 7{ at 66{
Veritas Software Corp., up 2} at 145\ on the Nasdaq
</P>
<P>
   Veritas and an investment group led by Silver Lake Partners
announced a $20 billion deal Wednesday to take Seagate, a maker of
disk drives, private. Veritas is the world's largest maker of
storage management software.
</P>
<P>
Cabletron Systems Inc., down 20| at 29\
</P>
<P>
   The company, a maker of network switches and software,
anticipates a first-quarter loss of $25 million to $45 million as
it restructures itself into four operating companies. Goldman Sachs
cut its rating on Cabletron stock to ''market perform'' from
''market outperform.''
</P>
<P>
Castle &AMP; Cooke Inc., up 4 13/16 at 16~
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and chief executive officer David Murdock wants to
acquire the 73 percent of stock that he, his company Flexi-Van
Leasing Inc., or other affiliates don't already own. The all-cash
proposal of $17 per share is a 41 percent premium to Wednesday's
closing price. Castle &AMP; Cooke is a real-estate developer.
</P>
<P>
Pep Boys, down 11/16 at 5 13/16
</P>
<P>
   Veritas Software will replace Pep Boys in the S&AMP;P 500 index. Pep
Boys will drop to the S&AMP;P SmallCap 600 Index. Shares of the
automotive retailer have dropped 59 percent in the past year,
giving it a market capitalization smaller than many components of
the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond Inc., up 10[ at 43|
</P>
<P>
   The company reported a 42 percent jump in earnings to 34 cents a
share for the quarter ending Feb. 26. Analysts had expected Bed
Bath &AMP; Beyond to earn 30 cents per share. Total sales rose 37
percent, while same-store sales climbed 9.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Profit Recovery Group International Inc., down 7| at 18]
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to report earnings and revenue below
analysts' expectations for the first and second quarters. Profit
Recovery blamed a revenue shortfall in its French tax recovery
auditing division, due to a series of strikes in March.
</P>
<P>
Pulaski Furniture Corp., up 5[ at 21~
</P>
<P>
   The company agreed to a management-led buyout offer worth $65
million, or $22.50 per share. Pulaski, which makes and imports
residential furniture, had been considered a buyout candidate, with
strong sales and profits and a low stock price.
</P>
