<HEADLINE> Lawyer To Elian's Dad Knows Politics  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE PFLEGER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gracing the evening news and handling
high-profile cases is nothing new for Greg Craig, the attorney for
Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   As the special counsel for President Clinton during his
impeachment trial, Craig took the spotlight as one of the
president's chief defenders and spokesman for his legal team.
</P>
<P>
   Since graduating from Yale law school in 1972, Craig has
represented a variety of clients. He helped defend John Hinckley
after his failed attempt to assassinate President Reagan and has
lobbied Washington power brokers on behalf of a wealthy Haitian
family who tried to ward off economic sanctions harmful to their
business.
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago, Craig -- an attorney with a top Washington law
firm, Williams &AMP; Connolly -- traveled to Cuba with two U.S.
religious leaders for a meeting with Cuban officials and Gonzalez.
He agreed to help Gonzalez try to regain custody of his son Elian,
the 6-year-old Cuban refugee who was found floating at sea after a
shipwreck more than four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our trip to Cuba was really exploratory,'' said Rev. Dr. Joan
Brown Campbell, former general secretary of the National Council of
Churches. She went on the Cuba trip and hosted Elian's grandmothers
on their visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Craig ''wanted to be very clear that he could
represent the father and the father would be a free agent.'' And
Craig wanted to be sure Gonzalez would accept his counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Craig asked the State Department Thursday for visas for Gonzalez
and other family members to come to the United States during the
immigration appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez ''is ready at a moment's notice,'' once he gets
assurances that Elian will be put in his custody during the legal
proceedings, Craig told a crowd of reporters outside his office.
''He has been ready, willing and waiting for too many weeks, for
too many months.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig's legal services will be paid through contributions to a
humanitarian fund established by the General Board of Church and
Society of The United Methodist Church, the Washington-based
organization said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   At 55, Craig is not a stranger to politics.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Sen. Edward Kennedy during the 1980s, Craig advised
the Massachusetts senator on foreign policy and defense. Later, he
offered him counsel during the 1991 rape trial of Kennedy's nephew,
William Kennedy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Craig also served as the State Department's director of policy
planning, as well as a stint overseeing the department's Tibet
policy.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments to the press, Craig, a father of five, chastised
Elian's Miami relatives, who have him in custody, for allowing news
cameras into his bedroom and parading him before demonstrators in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one on the face of this planet care more about the
well-being and welfare of Elian Gonzalez than does his father,''
Craig said. ''Can anyone doubt that the time is long overdue for
this boy to be reunited with his father?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
