<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Dives 186.78; Dow Off 38.47  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index narrowly averted its
worst day in history Thursday, ending a volatile session sharply
lower as investors bailed out of the high-tech stocks that have run
up dramatically in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   A confluence of factors battered the sector, but analysts said
investors' growing uneasiness about the high prices for many
technology stocks was the biggest contributor to the selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq fell 186.78 to close at 4,457.89, a loss of 4.0
percent. With less than 30 minutes remaining in the session, the
Nasdaq was down 289 points before recovering ground as investors
guessed that the index had reached rock-bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's plunge carried over to the broader market, dragging
the Dow Jones industrial average into negative territory after the
Dow had risen as much as 124 points earlier in the session. The Dow
ended down 38.47 at 10,980.25.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 20.60 to 1,487.92 and the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 11.43 to 531.57.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have been in a slide since March 10, when the
Nasdaq closed at a record high of 5,048.62. Just this week, the
Nasdaq has fallen 505.14 points. It suffered its fifth-biggest
one-day point drop Thursday; its largest drop ever was 229.46
points on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Triple-digit point swings in the Nasdaq are becoming more
commonplace amid continuing volatility in technology issues. Nine
of the index's 10 biggest one-day declines have come this year, as
have nine of the 10 biggest one-day point gains.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, several factors derailed the high-tech sector,
pushing the Nasdaq well into market watchers' definition of a
correction -- a reversal of an upward trend.
</P>
<P>
   At the core, investors hoping to capture profits continued a
selloff of stocks that have performed especially well this year.
What's more, with the end of the first quarter on Friday, mutual
fund managers dumped technology stocks so quarterly reports won't
show faltering high-tech names.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless data company Qualcomm fell 12 17/64 to 145 15/64 and
network equipment maker Cisco Systems fell 2 7/16 to 73|. Apple
Computer lost 10 3/16 to 125}.
</P>
<P>
   The selling pressure knocked the Nasdaq below 4,450 -- a
so-called technical benchmark that prompted a wave of
computer-driven selling. Only as the Nasdaq headed toward 4,400 did
investors step back into the market, bringing the index back from
its nadir.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors' increasing jitters over the highly
volatile technology sector are preventing many from
bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The psychological nerve of the market is slowly beginning to
unravel a bit,'' said Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist
at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The market's swoon followed the announcement that Tiger
Management, a family of hedge funds, will soon shut down. Tiger,
run by renowned money manager Julian H. Robertson Jr., was once
among the world's largest hedge fund families with $21 billion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson made his name and his fortune by investing in
undervalued industrial or transportation companies. His resistance
to technology stocks contributed to his funds' downfall -- Tiger
recently had about $6 billion in assets -- and subjected him to
criticism from some investors.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's parting shot to the sector contributed to Thursday's
selling pressure, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The current technology, Internet and telecom craze, fueled by
the performance desires of investors, money managers and even
financial buyers, is unwittingly creating a Ponzi pyramid destined
for collapse,'' Robertson said in a letter to Tiger's limited
partners.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness in technology marred a strong advance by many
old-line industrial companies. United Technologies rose 3} to 61],
3M rose 1] to 89 and Coca-Cola gained 1 11/16 to 48 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   ''Technology specialists are starting to use the 'v' word --
value,'' said Zane Brown, vice president at Lord, Abbett &AMP; Co.
''People are questioning valuations and are less willing to buy
technology stocks at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco rose 2 7/16 to 11} after financier Carl Icahn said he is
prepared to begin a cash tender offer of $13 a share for 100
million shares. The plans represent his most ambitious effort yet
to gain control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were further unnerved by a report that the U.S.
economy soared to an annual growth rate of 7.3 percent in the final
three months of 1999, the strongest performance in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the gross domestic product -- the country's total
output of goods and services -- was sharper than analysts had
expected, and raised worries that the Federal Reserve will continue
raising interest rates in order to force a slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, advancing issues outnumbered
decliners by a 6-to-5 margin. On the Nasdaq, decliners led
advancers by a 3-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE composite volume totaled 1.43 billion shares, compared with
1.28 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Germany's DAX index fell 2.8 percent, Britain's FT-SE
100 lost 2.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 3.0 percent. Japan's
Nikkei stock average fell 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
