<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Loses Vs. Major Currencies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar lost ground against most European
currencies and fell against the Japanese yen. The euro bounced up
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The weakened dollar was attributed to the declines in U.S.
stocks, led by a big selloff Thursday on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
The Nasdaq index fell 186 to 4,457, a loss of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 96.13 cents, up
from 95.17 cents late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the dollar fell to 105.46 Japanese yen from 105.81 yen
Tuesday. Yen buyers were encouraged by the industrial output data,
which suggested that parts of Japan's ailing economy may be moving
toward recovery.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.6576 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6751, and 1.4554 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4575. The
dollar fell against the British pound, which fetched $1.5954,
compared with $1.5944 late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0348 German
marks, down from 2.0556; 6.8244 French francs, down from 6.8943;
and 2,014.43 Italian lire, down from 2,035.07.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
