<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Soar on Stock Selloff  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose across-the-board Thursday as
investors sought safety during a stock market selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 11/32
point, or $13.44 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
in the opposite direction, plunged to 5.87 percent from 5.97
percent at Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
   A number of factors contributed to the rally, but bond prices
surged primarily because stock prices fell.
</P>
<P>
   Investors bailed out of technology stocks for a fourth straight
session, sending the Nasdaq composite index on one of its worst
one-day slides in history. The index closed down 186.78 to close at
4,457.89, a loss of about 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's decline spread to the broader market, dragging the
Dow Jones industrial average down 38.47 at 10,980.25.
</P>
<P>
   The market for government-backed Treasury bonds is frequently
seen by investors as a safe haven when the stock market skids.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries also benefited from concern that the U.S. government
might cut its ties with Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, which hurt the
market for mortgage-backed and agency debt this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, prices of short-term and
intermediate Treasury securities also rose. Short-term notes rose
5/32 point to 7/32 point, while intermediate notes rose 13/32 point
to 25/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information
service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.87 percent as the
discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 5.70 percent. Six-month
yields were 6.14 percent, as the discount fell 0.01 percentage
point to 5.87 percent. One-year yields were 6.23 percent as the
discount fell 0.05 percentage point to 5.88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 11/32 to 95 11/32. The average yield to
maturity fell to 5.98 percent from 6.01 percent Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
