<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative Party leader says Bush to headline dinner  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the expected
Republican presidential nominee, has agreed to speak at the annual
dinner of the New York Conservative Party, the head of the
influential third party said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long said Bush's decision to
speak at the New York City event on May 17 was ''a clear signal''
that the governor's presidential campaign isn't writing off the
heavily Democratic state for November, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts have said they do not expect the GOP to
contest New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear to me the governor and his campaign have not made
up their minds to walk away from New York,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, said ''we
have not yet accepted this invitation ... It's something that's
under consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Tucker said Long was correct in assuming that Bush
was not writing off New York and noted the Texas governor had
attened a $1,000-a-person, fund-raising reception for the Bush
campaign in New York City on Wednesday hosted by Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ''He intends to campaign there. It's going to be a very
competitive state,'' Tucker said. ''Traditionally, Democrats do
very well in New York, but at this point we are not conceding any
ground anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Told about Tucker's comments, Long said ''my understanding is
it's a green light'' for Bush to attend the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe they haven't formally accepted it, that's possible,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican presidential candidate has carried New York, where
Democrats outnumber Republicans by a 5-3 margin, since Ronald
Reagan pulled it off in 1980 and 1984. Reagan courted New York's
Conservative Party early on, speaking at its annual dinner in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's possible to do it again,'' Long said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our people aren't going to sit on their hands in this race,''
Long added. ''They don't want (Democrat) Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has not been officially endorsed by the Conservative
Party, Long said he expected the Texas governor would easily win
the party's backing.
</P>
<P>
   Long said Bush's appearance at the $500-a-person dinner would
not only help him in New York, but because of media coverage
spilling into neighboring Connecticut and New Jersey, could help
him in those states as well.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is expected to attend the Conservative Party dinner, as
he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   Not on the invitation list is New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, the Republican running for the U.S. Senate against
Hillary Rodham Clinton. Giuliani, who has had Liberal Party backing
in his mayoral campaigns, has never been invited to the annual
Conservative Party dinner. Long has been looking for a
Giuliani-Clinton alternative to run for the Senate on the
Conservative Party line.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, third party support can be important in close races
because unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates
to add the votes from minor party ballot lines to their totals.
Pataki won the 1994 governor's race over Democratic incumbent Mario
Cuomo on the strength of the vote on the Conservative Party line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 1912 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Targeting Money Laundering  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE FAUL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands (AP) -- The United Nations launched a
drive Thursday to enlist secretive offshore havens in the struggle
against money laundering -- appropriately, at a conference set on a
tiny island that is the world's fifth-largest banking center.
</P>
<P>
   ''The amounts involved in these financial scandals have gone
beyond what the world community is prepared to tolerate,'' said
Pino Arlacchi, a U.N. undersecretary general and executive director
of the Vienna-based U.N. Office for Drug Control and Crime
Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day conference was aimed at getting offshore havens to
adhere to a set of banking regulations laid out by the Paris-based
Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
   But some countries said stricter regulations could drive them
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a fact that in the offshore sector there's a greater
scope for money-laundering because of the confidentiality and
secrecy involved,'' the director of international financial
services for the South American nation of Belize, Gian Gandhi, told
the AP. ''But for fledgling new industries like ours it would be
suicidal to enforce those laws at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   To put the problem in perspective, Arlacchi cited last year's
case of at least $7 billion that Russian criminals moved through
the Bank of New York -- and compared it to Jamaica's gross domestic
product of $9.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fact that it was a New York bank showed that ''the
issues involved must also be relevant to 'onshore' jurisdictions,''
said George McCarthy, financial secretary of the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-seven of the world's 55 offshore centers attended the
conference, representing more than 50 percent of offshore business,
organizers said. The only major player absent was Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The 26 developed nations in the Paris-based OECD are targeting
countries with ''harmful tax practices'' to fight the loss of
billions of dollars to tax-free havens. And the United States is
targeting states that allow criminals to legitimize their illegal
gains.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald J. Ranochak, a former U.S. Federal Reserve official who
is coordinating the U.N. forum, said the United Nations would offer
technical assistance and training to countries ''seen to move
forward'' in the anti-money laundering battle.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the countries require only a few thousand dollars to
register a company that can then be used to shelter tax money or
criminal proceeds. Creating several such fictitious companies and
shuffling money among them makes it even harder for regulators to
detect its origin.
</P>
<P>
   The task is made more difficult, speakers noted, by
globalization and technology that moves money from country to
country with the push of a button.
</P>
<P>
   Arlacchi said the tainted money included not only hundreds of
billions of dollars in drug proceeds but profits from trafficking
in migrants.
</P>
<P>
   ''This traffic has become so profitable that even drug
traffickers are beginning to switch,'' he said, noting an estimated
10 million people are smuggled illegally each year.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said the Cayman Islands, a British Caribbean territory
of 40,000 that holds more than $500 billion in deposits from
foreign financial institutions, has tried to develop responses to
money laundering, but noted that some jurisdictions cannot afford
either the time or the resources.
</P>
<P>
   Countries at the conference included a string of Caribbean
islands, Panama, British territories in the Caribbean and several
Pacific island nations, including the island of Niue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1920 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital Punishment Plan Praised  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Illinois Gov. George Ryan -- a death penalty
supporter who prompted a flurry of activity after suspending
executions in his state -- lent his backing Thursday to federal
legislation seeking stronger protections for capital defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know of anything that's really more important if we're
going to have an America with the kind of justice system that works
and works well,'' the Republican governor said at a Capitol Hill
news conference where a bipartisan group of House members
introduced the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see who could be against it, frankly,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Innocence Protection Act'' is sponsored by Democratic Rep.
William Delahunt, who was a prosecutor for 20 years and opposes the
death penalty, and Republican Rep. Ray LaHood of Illinois, who
favors capital punishment. It mirrors a measure already introduced
in the Senate by Democrat Patrick Leahy of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   It seeks to ensure defendants in capital cases get adequate
legal assistance, including access to DNA testing that could prove
their innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Federal defendants would be guaranteed access to DNA testing,
and states would not get DNA-related federal grants unless they
made the testing available to state inmates. One of the measure's
more controversial provisions would allow inmates to sue in federal
court if a request for DNA testing is denied.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., told reporters earlier
that he had not seen the bill but believes it contains
''common-sense protections'' that should be part of the criminal
justice process. He did not promise to advance the measure, though
he pledged to give the legislation a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly we don't want people on death row at risk of losing
their lives if they're innocent,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   LaHood said Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
promised hearings on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We absolutely have to be 100 percent sure when someone
receives the death penalty,'' LaHood said. ''I've tried, in my
limited time here, to work on a number of issues. This, to me, is
one of the really big ones that addresses a very serious problem in
our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt said his experience as a prosecutor outside Boston
taught him ''daily lessons in human fallibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The justice system is comprised of human beings and nothing we
can do can bring absolutely certainty to such a system,'' Delahunt
said. ''But we do have the tools to at least minimize the
possibility of error.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Ryan imposed a moratorium on executions in Illinois
until as task force could determine why more death sentences have
been overturned there than carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, when the Supreme Court allowed states to reinstate
capital punishment, Illinois has executed 12 people. Since 1987,
the state has released 13 from death row after their convictions
were overturned, second only to Florida, which has exonerated 19
people.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, 87 death row inmates have been freed since 1973,
according to the Washington-based Death Penalty Information Center.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been a federal execution since 1963, but the
number of people put to death by the states is growing, including
26 so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, nearly 3,600 people are on death row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1930 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Industry Sues Tobacco Cos.  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) -- Nearly 150 hospitals joined a health care
industry group in filing a $3.4 billion lawsuit Thursday that seeks
reimbursement for the cost of treating uninsured patients suffering
tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   A number of tobacco companies expressed confidence that the
lawsuit would be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit claims the tobacco industry marketed and sold
cigarettes and smokeless tobacco products, despite knowing the
products are harmful, addictive, and lead to serious illness and
death. It was filed in state court by the hospitals and the
Healthcare Association of New York State, an industry group that
represents hospitals, health systems, nursing homes and other
health care agencies throughout New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks to recover costs of care provided to the
uninsured, as well as Medicaid and Medicare patients whose publicly
financed plans did not fully cover the costs of their care.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although it is part of the charitable mission of New York's
nonprofit hospitals to care for all who come to us, we should not
have to bear the burden of intentional fraud, deceit, and greed of
Big Tobacco,'' Healthcare Association President Daniel Sisto said.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants include: Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp.,
Lorillard Tobacco Co. Inc., Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co., the United States Tobacco Co., Council for Tobacco
Research U.S.A., Inc. and the Tobacco Institute, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Smith, a spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson, said he couldn't
comment because he hadn't seen a copy of the suit, but noted
similar lawsuits filed around the country have been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   R.J. Reynolds spokeswoman Carole Crosslin also declined to
comment about the specific case, but said, ''If this suit is like
the other suits that attempt to recover medical costs, we believe
that it will be dismissed, as all other similar suits have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The case filed Thursday is similar to a Justice Department suit,
which accuses cigarette makers of conspiring for 45 years to
mislead the public about the dangers of smoking and seeks to
recover billions of dollars spent by Medicare and other federal
health programs to treat smoking-induced illnesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1931 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
