<DOCNO> APW20000330.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Calls Clinton Judge Biased  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The judge who ruled this week that President
Clinton committed a crime is being asked by Pentagon spokesman Ken
Bacon to remove himself from a lawsuit filed by Linda Tripp on the
grounds that the judge is biased.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, lawyers for Bacon said U.S. District Judge
Royce Lamberth prejudged one of the central issues of the Tripp
lawsuit, whether her privacy rights were violated when the Pentagon
released damaging information about her.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon and Pentagon employee Clifford Bernath, who joined Bacon's
motion for Lamberth to recuse himself, are being sued by Mrs. Tripp
for violating her privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''Judge Lamberth is prejudiced against'' Bacon ''in the purest
meaning of the word,'' his attorney William Murphy wrote in a
20-page motion joined by Bernath.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth ''has prejudged one of the ultimate issues in this
case, without any valid basis for the prejudgment,'' Murphy added.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon's lawyer cited federal law which states that ''any ...
judge ... shall disqualify himself in any proceeding in which his
impartiality might reasonably be questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   In a March 13 opinion, Lamberth stated in a footnote that ''the
Tripp release presents such a clear violation of the Privacy Act.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp is suing Bacon, Bernath, the Pentagon and the
Executive Office of the President over the Pentagon's release of
information to The New Yorker magazine about Mrs. Tripp. She stated
on a security clearance form she had never been arrested, when in
fact she had.
</P>
<P>
   She was arrested for grand larceny when she was a teen-ager,
pleaded innocent and a judge disposed of the case by reducing the
charge to loitering.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon's lawyers filed their motion with the court before
Lamberth's ruling Wednesday in a separate lawsuit that Clinton
violated the Privacy Act by releasing letters from presidential
accuser Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mrs. Tripp's lawyers, David Colapinto, likened the
recusal motion to the unsuccessful effort of Watergate figures John
Mitchell and John Ehrlichman to have Judge John Sirica recuse
himself from their criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''It didn't work for Ehrlichman and Mitchell and it shouldn't
work for Bacon and Bernath,'' Colapinto said Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 1931 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Headlining Party's Dinner  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- George W. Bush, the likely Republican
presidential nominee, has agreed to speak at the New York
Conservative Party's annual dinner, its chairman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Long also said the Texas governor's decision to speak at
the May 17 event in New York was ''a clear signal'' that his
campaign isn't writing off the heavily Democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats outnumber Republicans by a 5-to-3 margin, and some
political analysts have said they do not expect the GOP to contest
New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear to me the governor and his campaign have not made
up their minds to walk away from New York,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, said they
have not yet accepted the invitation. ''It's something that's under
consideration,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker also said Long was correct to assume that Bush was not
writing off the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Traditionally, Democrats do very well in New York, but at this
point we are not conceding any ground anywhere,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Long said his understanding was that there was a ''green light''
for Bush to attend.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican presidential candidate has carried New York state
since Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984. Reagan courted New York's
Conservative Party early on, speaking at its annual dinner in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's possible to do it again,'' Long said Thursday.
''Our people aren't going to sit on their hands in this race. They
don't want (Democrat) Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has not been officially endorsed by the influential
third party, Long said he expected the Texas governor would easily
win the party's backing.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki, a Bush supporter, also is expected
to attend the $500-per-person dinner, as he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, third party support can be important in close races
because unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates
to add the votes from minor party ballot lines to their totals.
Pataki won the 1994 governor's race over Democratic incumbent Mario
Cuomo on the strength of the vote on the Conservative Party line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
