<HEADLINE> Fugitive captured in turnpike shootout gets life term for bankrobbery  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A fugitive captured with his gang in a
shootout at a New Jersey Turnpike rest stop was sentenced Thursday
to life plus more than 39 years in prison for robbing two Camden
County banks and attempting to rob an armored car.
</P>
<P>
   Unless his appeals succeed, Charles ''Crazy Charlie'' Rodriguez,
33, will die in prison since federal prisoners are not eligible for
parole.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is clear you are a miscreant and a threat to society. Your
life has been dedicated to antisocial behavior and evil,'' U.S.
District Judge Joseph A. Greenaway Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   He sentenced Rodriguez's brother, Joseph Rodriguez, 32, to life
plus more than 36 years in prison for the same offenses. A third
Camden man, Jose Soto, 28, got 37\ years in prison for the planned
heist and weapons offenses.
</P>
<P>
   All ''richly deserve'' the sentences, Greenaway said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the three spoke during the all-day sentencing, but all
plan to appeal their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The three were arrested in September 1998 after being fired on
by some of the more than 90 officers awaiting them at the Walt
Whitman service plaza in Cherry Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Their stolen Buick was rammed by a tow truck driven by an FBI
agent. Three agents testified last year that Soto pointed an
assault rifle, prompting agents to open fire. The suspects did not
fire. All escaped serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Agents found the gang wearing bulletproof vests, automatic
weapons and hundreds of armor-piercing bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The trio had gone there to rob an armored car they believed
carried $1 million, not realizing their coconspirator, Rodriguez
cousin Fernando Flores, was an FBI informant.
</P>
<P>
   Flores told them an armored car would be delivering cash to an
ATM machine.
</P>
<P>
   Flores had been enlisted by the FBI to get the gang off the
streets. Flores, a Merchantville police officer for two years in
the mid-1990s, testified he got $14,500.
</P>
<P>
   After a seven-week trial, a jury in July rejected defense
assertions of entrapment.
</P>
<P>
   Greenaway on Thursday rejected entrapment motions for a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were convicted on all nine counts they faced,
including armed bank robbery, attempted robbery, carjacking,
conspiracy and weapons offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Soto was convicted on four counts regarding weapons offenses and
the planned heist, but acquitted on the five charges regarding the
bank robberies, which included carjacking.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Rodriguez still faces state charges, including attempted
murder, stemming from a February 1997 shooting in Camden that
wounded Camden County Park Police Officer Stephen Leoniy III. The
officer was approaching a suspected stolen car when gunfire
erupted.
</P>
<P>
   That made Rodriguez among the most wanted fugitives in southern
New Jersey. An $11,000 reward was offered for his capture and he
was twice featured on the television show ''America's Most
Wanted.'' He got his nickname from his violent criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Greenaway also ordered the Rodriguez brothers to repay $64,039
to the CoreStates Bank in Woodlynne for a robbery July 19, 1997;
and $15,373 to the Commerce Bank in Moorestown for a robbery May
28, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At trial, their lawyers contended that bank surveillance
pictures offer no proof that the Rodriguez brothers and Soto were
behind the ski masks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors countered that the masks and jackets in the pictures
are those that the Rodriguez brothers were wearing when captured.
</P>
<P>
   ''These robberies were well executed, and maybe but for the fact
that these people liked wearing the same clothes, we might not be
here today discussing bank robberies,'' Greenaway said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
