<HEADLINE> Justice Asked To Help in Voting Case  </HEADLINE>
By CANDACE SMITH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- District of Columbia officials asked Attorney
General Janet Reno to bring some Justice Department support behind
an effort to win voting rights for the residents of the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Reno met with Del. Eleanor Holmes Norton, D-D.C., Mayor Anthony
A. Williams, Council Chairwoman Linda W. Cropp and other officials
behind closed doors Thursday on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said she asked the Justice Department to write a brief in
the voting rights case that would express empathy for the fact that
district residents cannot choose a voting member in Congress as
residents of the other 50 states do.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton Tuesday sent Norton a letter stating his
support for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   On March 21, a three-judge federal court ruled 2 to 1 that
district residents do not have a legal right to vote in Congress.
The justices ruled on two lawsuits filed by different sets of D.C.
activists. The district government joined one of the suits.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department argued that the Constitution states that
only people in states can elect representatives and that the
district is not a state and therefore does not have a
constitutional right to elect voting members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in both suits plan to appeal the cases to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Norton said Reno seemed sympathetic to the district's argument.
</P>
<P>
   Reno would only give a ''yes'' answer when asked by reporters if
she supported statehood for the district.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
