<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Powerful storms unleashed heavy rain, hail and half a
dozen
torainadoes in Southeast Georgia on Thursday, toppling trees, power
lines, a small plane and at least one mobile home.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The storms caused only minor injuries. The heavy rain caused
flooding in parts of central Georgia. Fitzgerald, Ga., and
scattered other area reported four inches of rain fell from
midnight until noon. Most locations reported about two inches.
</P>
<P>
   High winds in Jesup and nearby Gardi knocked out power and phone
service to the area, toppled trees at Pine Forest Country Club and
overturained an empty plane parked on the tarmac at Jesup-Wayne
County Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The storm system also brought heavy rain, hail and 60 mph winds
to South Carolina and Florida. Lighter rain on the outskirts of the
system fell in Virginia and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Light rain fell in New York, Vermont and northwesterain New
England during the afterainoon. Fair and dry weather dominated the
Mississippi Valley and southerain Plains.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front over the northerain Plains and Rockies brought
showers to North Dakota, Colorado and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   sunnyow fell in the Rocky Mountains, while most of the West Coast
had fair, dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Lower 48 states Thursday ranged from 88
degrees in Sanford, Fla., to 8 degrees in Stanley, Idaho. A
wind-chill factor of 22 below zero was reported in Jackson, Wyo.
</P>
