<HEADLINE> McCain Giving Some Delegates to Bush  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY BARKS HOFFMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- John McCain is giving former GOP
presidential primary rival George W. Bush six of the Michigan
delegates he won and has similar deals or is close to agreement in
several New England states the Arizona senator won before
suspending his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reached Thursday in Michigan allows Gov. John Engler to
attend the National Republican Convention as a Bush delegate and is
the latest move toward GOP reconciliation after the divisive
primary contest. At one point, McCain and Engler talked by phone, a
McCain aide said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain agreed to give Bush six delegates to add to the six the
Texas governor won in the Feb. 22 Michigan primary, leaving the
Arizona senator with 46 of the state's 58. McCain has suspended his
campaign, and Bush has won enough delegates to clinch the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain camp said delegate agreements also had been reached
or were close in New England states where the senator won
primaries, including Connecticut, Rhode Island, Vermont and
Massachusetts. A McCain aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
had no details.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain aide said that the senator, in his first campaign
swing next week on behalf of Republicans, will campaign for Sen.
Lincoln Chafee, who's vying to maintain the seat once held by his
late father, John. Rep. Robert Weygand, D-R.I., is running for the
seat.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also will hold a town hall meeting at Columbia University
in New York on April 10.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, McCain won 51 percent of the vote to 43 for Bush,
largely on the strength of independent and Democratic voters who
supported him in the open primary. But he couldn't sustain his
momentum two weeks later in the March 7 Super Tuesday primaries and
suspended his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's deal also names state Sen. John Schwarz co-chairman
of Michigan's national convention delegation. Schwarz headed up
McCain's Michigan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement followed two meetings and numerous telephone
conversations between Schwarz and Engler. It ''recognizes that
McCain won Michigan,'' said Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a commonsense solution,'' said Engler. ''It puts
Governor Bush back on track to win Michigan in November, and that's
the bottom line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
