<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. charges eight online pharmacies violate consumer protectionlaws  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- New Jersey announced Thursday it has sued
eight online pharmacies, most of which specialize in selling
Viagra, charging that the operators failed to tell consumers that
they are not licensed to practice in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative lawsuits also charged that the drug sales
were done by ''virtual'' doctor visits via the pharmacies' Web
sites that fall short of New Jersey standards.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pharmacies and pharmacists must follow state laws whether they
do business in New Jersey neighborhoods or on the Internet,'' state
Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Viagra, an anti-impotence drug that one of the
Web sites described as ''one of the defining drugs of the '90s,''
many of the eight pharmacies promoted the hair growth drug Propecia
and the weight-loss drug Xenical.
</P>
<P>
   Undercover investigators from the state Division of Consumer
Affairs made a total of about a dozen purchases, ranging from $100
to $300, from the pharmacies, agency spokeswoman Jennifer Salvato
said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, investigators ordering Viagra mentioned that they
were taking other medications indicating a heart condition, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Heart patients who take nitroglycerin for chest pain are warned
not to use Viagra, since the combination can trigger a dangerous
drop in blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't even come back with questions for the person. The
prescription was just filled,'' Salvato said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency chose not to charge the pharmacies for lacking New
Jersey licenses, only with failing to tell that to consumers. Asked
why, Salvato said officials cited ''prosecutorial discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Affairs Director Mark S. Herr will hear the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach operators of the cyber drugstores on Thursday
were unsuccessful:
</P>
<P>
   --AmericanMedicine.com Inc., of Pittsburgh, posted a notice on
its Web site that it was being renovated and not currently
operating. No phone listing could be found.
</P>
<P>
   --Sites operated by ClickThruPharmacy.com Inc., of Miami, could
not be accessed and no phone listing could be found.
</P>
<P>
   --A phone listing for Confimed.com LLC of Seattle rang unanswered
and its Web site said: ''At the present time, we cannot fill orders
for patients. We will notify you when we can ship orders. We are
making changes to the web site to better protect your health and to
comply with Federal &AMP; State Regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   --An e-mail sent to Kwikmed Inc., of Phoenix, through its Web
site was not returned and no phone listing could be found.
</P>
<P>
   --A phone message at The Pill Box Inc. of San Antonio was not
immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   --No phone listing could be found for Private Medical Services,
of Miami Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   --Sites operated by SafeWeb Medical Inc., of Miami, could not be
accessed, and no phone listing could be found.
</P>
<P>
   --A phone message left at the Phoenix office of Viapro Inc. was
not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Pharmacy can be called at 1-800-242-5846 to
determine if a person is a licensed pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can check on the registration and disciplinary history
of doctors at the state Division of Consumer Affairs Web site:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.state.nj.us/lps/ca/director.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
