<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Threat Suspect Denied Bail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- A judge denied bail Thursday for a Canadian man
of Egyptian origin who police suspect made a threatening phone call
to the Israeli consulate and who has been linked to a cache of
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Ayman Bondok, 23, was charged with extortion and possessing
explosives when arrested March 9 with Kim St. Louis, 31, who also
was charged with possessing explosives. She has been released on
bail.
</P>
<P>
   After the Israeli consulate received the threatening phone call
in early March, police received a tip about explosives in a
Montreal apartment. Police found the explosives and counterfeit
money in a March 4 search of the apartment and arrested the
occupant, Tarek Adealy Khafagy, an Egyptian refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Khafagy denied any knowledge of the explosives and counterfeit
money or the threatening phone call. Police investigators later
said they believed Bondok made the call and also provided the tip
about the explosives in Khafagy's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after her arrest, St. Louis said Bondok may have
been trying to frame Khafagy due to a family feud back in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Khafagy was granted bail last week and faces a preliminary
hearing in his case on April 25.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of Bondok's attorney, the judge imposed a
publication ban on Thursday's bail hearing that prohibited details
of the evidence from being reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
