<DOCNO> APW20000330.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penn State Tries To Spoil UConn  </HEADLINE>
By KEN BERGER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Andrea Garner had the whole gang over to her
house for a Final Four party, and Penn State coach Rene Portland
didn't mind one bit. In fact, she sounded like quite the party
animal.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this is Penn State's first trip to the Final Four,
Portland sees no reason to feel like the oddball. She refuses to
let her players fear top-ranked and heavily favored Connecticut in
their semifinal matchup Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Those who like the stars to remain exactly in alignment might be
rooting for a UConn-Tennessee matchup for the national
championship. Portland knows there are two games to be played
before that.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went to Andrea's house last night. We could have said we
were tired and we want to go home, but I want them to be excited
and I want to point things out to them,'' Portland said Thursday as
the Lady Lions (30-4) prepared to take on UConn (34-1). ''It's
almost like your wedding day. It's such a big day, and sometimes
the bride doesn't remember it.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are the brides right now. Remember everything that's
happening, keep a smile on your face, take great pictures and when
it's time to say, 'I do,' get to work.'''
</P>
<P>
   Beating UConn is quite a task, but Portland and Penn State are
not new to upsets. The Lady Lions have knocked off third-seeded
Iowa State and top-seeded Louisiana Tech on their way to
Philadelphia. Before this year, they'd upset 17 opponents ranked
ahead of them in Portland's 19 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't read too much about the matchups as far as UConn and
Tennessee goes,'' Garner said. ''I know we're not going to let them
get there easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland, who coached St. Joseph's in the 1970s, brought her
team to the old Fieldhouse on 54th and City Line for practice
Wednesday. Afterward, the Lady Lions convened at Garner's house.
The center, who was born in Philly, is a cousin of former
Philadelphia Eagles running back Charlie Garner.
</P>
<P>
   Though Portland has the relaxed demeanor of a winner -- she won
three straight national titles playing for Cathy Rush at Immaculata
-- her players could be showing some of the classic signs of ''First
Timers Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'm still in shock a little bit,'' said guard Helen
Darling, whose matchup against Sue Bird could be a key to the
outcome. ''We came in and there were a lot of people outside
waiting for us and cheering for us. I'm really happy and excited
that we were able top make it here, and I'm just looking forward to
what else the Final Four brings.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Lady Lions are still in shock at 9:30 p.m. EST Friday
night, they'll be in big trouble. The Huskies, playing in their
fourth Final Four, are not easily intimidated -- and they can sense
if an opponent is ''just happy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn holds another advantage, having beaten Penn State 87-74 in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is March, and it is different,'' said Shea Ralph, the
Huskies' vocal leader. ''They have been practicing and getting
better, and so have we.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams held open practice for fans and the media Thursday,
but that isn't real practice. They work out on their own at
selected sites away from the circus-like atmosphere of the host
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ralph was shouting encouragement to teammates, slapping
five with a vengeance and taking her head fakes very seriously. It
was an interesting snapshot of how determined the Huskies are to
add a national championship trophy to the one they captured in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   UConn beat Tennessee for the championship in '95, but lost to
the Lady Vols in the national semifinals in '96 and the regional
championship in '97.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not looking to that Tennessee matchup yet,'' Ralph
said. ''I know I've heard a lot about it and there's been a lot
written about it. For so many years now it's been a tradition,
UConn and Tennessee. I've heard that it's been voted the
second-biggest rivalry or something on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not everything on the Internet is true, it is safe to say
that UConn is used to this kind of attention. They get it every
time the ball goes up in the air at their raucous arena in
hoops-crazy Storrs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very comfortable in this position,'' Ralph said. ''A
lot of us have been in this position most of our lives. ... Going
into this tournament, I think I'd rather be sitting in our locker
room than any other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
