<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corzine apologizes for remarks about Italian-Americans  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Jon S. Corzine's U.S. Senate campaign
stumbled Thursday as he apologized for offending Italian-Americans
who said he made remarks that perpetuate the stereotype that they
are involved with organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Without admitting he made the remarks, the former Wall Street
executive apologized for offending anyone and said he wouldn't do
it again.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never intended to cause embarrassment. I never intended to
offend,'' Corzine said Thursday at a news conference where he
accepted the endorsement of the Unite garment workers' union. ''I
shouldn't have said what I am reported to have said, and if I did,
I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who said he is of Italian descent, was backed Thursday
by Italian-American politicians who said the remarks were not
intentional slurs, but was denounced by civil rights groups and
other Italian-Americans, including his primary opponent, former
Gov. Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am proud of my background,'' said Florio, who is facing
Corzine in the Democratic Senate primary on June 6 in a state where
one out of four Democrats is Italian-American.
</P>
<P>
   To make ''derogatory stereotypes of whole classifications of
people is at a minimum insensitive and at a maximum is callously
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Manny Alfano, chairman of the Italian-American One Voice
Committee, demanded an apology from Corzine for ''ethnic slurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfano said Corzine made the first offensive remark several
months ago at a Newark restaurant, where Corzine was seeking the
support of six prominent Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano, who was not at the meeting, said that upon being
introduced to a lawyer named David Stein, Corzine remarked, ''Who
is Dave Stein? He's not Italian, is he? Oh, I guess he's your
Jewish lawyer who is here to get the rest of you out of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfano said the second remark occurred two weeks ago when
Corzine met an Italian-American contractor and quipped, ''Oh, you
make cement shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine campaign manager Steven Goldstein said the candidate
''never, ever'' uttered the alleged reference to the ''Jewish
lawyer.'' Stein, the lawyer, said Thursday he did meet with Corzine
four to six months ago but does not recall the comment.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine didn't dispute the remarks about Italian-Americans,
although he said he doesn't remember the exact wording. He did not
say in what context he meant the remarks, and Goldstein did not
return telephone calls to elaborate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman Sachs, is locked in a
hard-hitting battle with Florio for the Democratic nomination to
succeed retiring Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. A Quinnipiac College
poll released on Wednesday found him trailing Florio 2-to-1,
despite the $4 million he has already spent to get his name known
in a state where Florio, the former governor, enjoys widespread
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano said Thursday that he has not yet decided who to support
in the campaign, but said the Italian-American stereotypes had to
end.
</P>
<P>
   ''This constant barrage of mob movies ... people think they can
say anything to Italians and we're not going to be offended,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of four national Italian-American groups said
Corzine's comments showed ''both insensitivity and arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Corzine has shown his obvious and incredible disrespect to
Italian-Americans in New Jersey, the home of Ellis Island where
millions of Italian immigrants arrived and later settled,'' said a
statement by groups that included the Italian American Democratic
Leadership Council and the Order Sons of Italy in America.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine found support Thursday from Italian-American politicians
like U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli and Assembly Minority Leader
Joseph Doria, who accused the Florio campaign of trying to distract
the press from the issues. The New York Times first printed the
remarks in Thursday editions.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're trying to make an issue of a slur, a political issue
and that's not right,'' said Doria. ''In the end, it is not an
issue that should be the central issue of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't control what Mr. Corzine says,'' said Florio
spokesman Walter Fields, who added that the campaign first learned
of the remarks from the Times.
</P>
<P>
   Doria and more than 20 other Italian-American politicians later
signed a statement of support for Corzine, saying they accepted his
apology as ''sincere and heartfelt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
