<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton on congressional GOP: 'No shame'  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton accused Republican
congressional leaders on Thursday of sabotaging his hopes of
securing a nuclear weapons pact with India and Pakistan. ''They
have no guilt and no shame,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During a trip to South Asia last week, Clinton failed to make
any arms control deals. India and Pakistan both refused to reverse
their nuclear weapons programs, and Pakistan's military leaders
refused even to promise a quick return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of the nuclear rivalry between India and
Pakistan, Clinton has called that region among the world's most
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told a Democratic audience in Manhattan that upon his
return last week he was angered by Republican criticism that he did
not ''get anything'' for his trip.
</P>
<P>
   Such criticism ignores a critical fact, he said: ''I lost all
leverage I had when the Republican Senate defeated the ratification
of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is real gall, man,'' Clinton said to applause. ''That
requires a lot of moxie, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Laughing, Clinton continued: ''One of their great strengths, by
the way, is they have no guilt and no shame. I mean, they'll say
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations subcommittee on Near Eastern and South Asian affairs, has
called Clinton's trip ''a bust.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Whip Tom DeLay has also said Clinton has little
to show for his week of diplomacy in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said Thursday that GOP criticism of Clinton's trip was
''pretty muted'' and consisted of ''disappointment that he wouldn't
use the authority he had.'' He said he had worked hard the last two
years to give Clinton waiver authority to lift economic sanctions
on India and ''the president goes to India and hardly lifts any
sanctions at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a relationship that is ripe for growth and instead we
got a trip that was mostly symbolic,'' Brownback said.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., questioned the importance of the test ban treaty
rejected by the Senate last year compared with an arms control pact
with India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''These countries have already signed and broken a nuclear
non-proliferation treaty,'' Czwartacki said. ''It's hard to believe
that more paper is the answer. I think this president needs more of
an emphasis on diplomacy and less emphasis on photo-op foreign
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear testing in 1998 -- first by India and then by Pakistan --
shook the Indian subcontinent and the world. Since then, both
countries have tested both medium range and short range missiles,
Pakistan as recently as last month.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Clinton lost a bitter, 51-48 vote for ratification of
the test ban treaty. Only four Senate Republicans voted for the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The United States thus became the first nuclear power to
specifically reject the 154-nation agreement on ending nuclear
weapons testing, and Clinton called the vote ''reckless
partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   The president had campaigned hard for the treaty, saying it was
a vital gesture to countries with nuclear aspirations. The United
States has voluntarily stopped the kind of testing covered by the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was in New York for a full day of fund raising and to
campaign for his plan to extend and reform the Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Republican leaders in Congress don't care
about shoring up the Medicare and Social Security systems, because
they want those federal programs to go private. He attacked
Republican tax cut proposals as shortsighted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wont have any money to help Social Security and Medicare
when the Baby Boomers retire, but that's OK with them because they
want to privatize them,'' Clinton said. ''And I think it's a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Revamping Medicare, the federal health care program for the
elderly, is a major element of the president's domestic legislative
agenda for his final year in office. He wants to add coverage for
prescription drugs that would be available to all; Republicans want
to target that coverage to the neediest elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also worked in plugs for the New York Senate candidacy
of his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and the presidential bid of
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want Al Gore to be president because he's been the best vice
president in history and I love him,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
