<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DiFrancesco proposes 'smart gun' law, eventual ban on sale of oldhandguns  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- With a coalition of antigun and school
groups and Democrats behind him, Republican Senate President Donald
DiFrancesco has decided it is time to give gun control another shot
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco on Thursday unveiled legislation to mandate the sale
of so-called ''smart guns'' equipped with sensor technology that
disables the gun unless the owner is holding it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill leaves open when the mandate would take effect. Rather
than pick a date, the bill specifies that a three-year clock would
be started once the state attorney general certifies that handguns
with sensor technology are commercially available.
</P>
<P>
   Once the mandate does take effect, only such guns could be sold
in New Jersey. Gun dealers would be prohibited from selling any
conventional handguns, new or used. The bill would not interfere
with private transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a similar bill from DiFrancesco last year, but
it was opposed by Democrats and scuttled by the state Assembly.
DiFrancesco this time has a coalition that includes the state PTA,
child-advocacy groups and Ceasefire New Jersey, the leading
gun-control lobby.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco said he had not yet consulted Assembly Speaker Jack
Collins on the proposal, and Collins promptly issued a news
statement denouncing the measure as ''political opportunism.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Republican legislative leaders have said they intend to run
for governor in 2001, and Collins' sharp statement Thursday broke
the polite distance they have been keeping.
</P>
<P>
   Collins last year shepherded an alternate bill through the
Assembly mandating trigger locks on new guns and funding a state
study of smart guns.
</P>
<P>
   ''The text of this latest smart gun proposal may have been
altered to appease certain individuals, but the basic fact that
smart gun technology still does not exist remains unchanged,''
Collins said. He said the technology was ''promising'' and that he
would lead efforts to mandate such guns once they were available.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Miller, head of Ceasefire New Jersey, praised DiFrancesco
for his ''courage and commitment.'' He said his organization
decided to ally with DiFrancesco on this measure because it
provides a clearer point at which to start the three-year clock to
institute the mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Ross of the Association of New Jersey Rifle &AMP; Pistol Clubs
denounced DiFrancesco's bill as a political maneuver that could
endanger lives. ''(The bill) would put untested firearms on the
market that could actually be hurtful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said smart guns should be a choice, not a mandate. ''It is
like someone is being told the only car they can buy would be a
BMW, and they can't buy any other car in the state,'' she said.
''It is actually going to end up to be a ban because there will be
no other firearms available in this state once these firearms
(rules) go into effect.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco's bill would require the bullet-mark
''fingerprinting'' of every firearm sold in New Jersey so police
would have records enabling them to trace handguns used in a crime.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco's bill would also prohibit anyone from getting a gun
permit until they are 21. Current law permits gun permits at age
18.
</P>
<P>
   Collins agreed with the age change but added a political dig,
noting in his news statement that this change was approved by the
Assembly in a previous session and scuttled by the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 2110 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helms, U.N. Security Council Spar  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Jesse Helms, playing host to the U.N.
Security Council, appealed to delegates Thursday to ''disagree
agreeably and proceed in friendship.'' Council members matched the
conservative Foreign Relations Committee chairman in civility, but
still bristled at U.S. terms for a U.N. overhaul and reduced
American payments.
</P>
<P>
   All 15 members of the Security Council --five permanent and 10
rotating members -- showed up for the unprecedented daylong
gathering, arranged by Helms, R-N.C., after he became the first
American lawmaker to address the Security Council at U.N.
headquarters in New York in January.
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon session billed as a ''roundtable discussion,''
delegate after delegate said they supported some form of U.N.
overhaul to make the organization more effective. But U.S. mandated
terms, tying future U.S. payments to some of the changes, drew
criticism -- the strongest from top U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
   They all spoke in English. At the United Nations, they usually
speak in their native language.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't like it -- withholding money that is due,'' said Peter
Van Walsum, the Netherlands representative. He said that while most
of the 188 countries in the United Nations wanted improvements in
the system, ''we do not like to do so under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   British delegate Jeremy Greenstock said that the United States
must understand that it should view its contribution as an
investment and, ''like any good investment, it is going to take
some risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fowler, Canada's delegate, said, ''Not only is the United
Nations not perfect. It will never be perfect. It is not
Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations puts back U.S. dues at $1.7 billion but the
United States calculates it at closer to $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year voted to pay $926 million of the arrears over
three years, with a $100 million first installment. But to get the
balance, the United Nations must meet about a dozen conditions
drafted by Helms and Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, the panel's
senior Democrat. Those terms generally have not been well received
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   They include a reduction the U.S. share of the U.N. peacekeeping
budget from the current 31 percent to 25 percent and of the regular
budget from 25 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, one of the fiercest of congressional critics of the
United Nations, played the part of cordial host as he showed the
delegates around the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   He welcomed the delegates in the ornate but relatively small Old
Senate Chamber -- used from 1810 to 1859 -- with a pointed civics
lesson on the active role of the Senate in foreign policy-making.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it has been suggested to you that the president alone
speaks for the United States in foreign affairs. And in most of the
nations of the world -- even the great democracies -- that is indeed
the case,'' Helms said. ''Not so the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms cited the Senate's power to ratify treaties, confirm
ambassadors and provide funds for foreign operations.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the delegates joined senators for lunch in the richly
finished room that was the setting for the Senate Army-McCarthy
hearings in the 1950s and the Senate Watergate hearings in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In a toast, Biden said he hoped the visit in addition to
promoting better understanding would show Security Council members
''how disorganized we are -- and how many different voices we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The current Security Council president, Bangladesh Ambassador
Anwarul Chowdhury, toasted the Senate in exchange, saying both
organizations ''seek the understanding and realization that the
United Nations is the most-needed organization in today's world.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at the State Department, the delegates stood before the
flags of their countries and were greeted by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, a former U.S. ambassador to the United Nations
herself.
</P>
<P>
   At the afternoon session, a long square table covered with green
cloth allowed Security Council members and senators to sit
together. ''I hope that we can agree to disagree agreeably, and
proceed in friendship in a search for common ground,'' said Helms.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Yingfan, the Chinese delegate, said China supports U.N.
overhauls as does the United States. But, noting the enormous
influence of the United States, he said that, ''We must make it
more effective not just for the few but for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to peackeeeping, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, told delegates: ''Don't take
on more than you can do.'' He cited being ''heavily involved in
Bosnia and in Kosovo'' while eyeing other engagements.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings were designated as unofficial -- and delegates were
invited individually and made their own way here.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, President Clinton, who was in New York, called
U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke during the middle of a meeting to
ask him how it was going. Clinton ''wanted to say how pleased he
was by the fact that they were here,'' said Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
