<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Blocks S.F. Chronicle Sale  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal judge on Thursday temporarily
blocked the Hearst Corp.'s $660 million purchase of the San
Francisco Chronicle and said he was concerned that San Francisco
may become a one-newspaper city.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the U.S. Justice Department approved the sale, U.S.
District Judge Vaughn Walker issued a temporary restraining order
against it. He said a private antitrust suit had raised doubts
about the survival of Hearst's 120-year-old San Francisco Examiner
after the Chronicle changes hands.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst announced March 17 that it was transferring ownership of
the Examiner, the Chronicle's longtime rival, to owners of the
Independent, a local free-distribution paper. Hearst said it agreed
to subsidize the owners with $66 million over three years after
fruitless contacts with 80 potential buyers, including the nation's
major newspaper publishers.
</P>
<P>
   But political consultant Clint Reilly, who sued to stop Hearst
from buying the Chronicle, argued that the subsidy was far too
small to keep the Examiner alive and would leave Hearst with a
local newspaper monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle is the largest newspaper in Northern California
and the 13th-largest in the nation, with circulation of 456,000
compared to the Examiner's 107,000.
</P>
<P>
   After a 40-minute hearing, Walker said Reilly had raised a
significant enough issue to delay the purchase until April 13, when
a hearing is scheduled on a preliminary injunction that would stay
in effect until the suit went to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Serious questions have been raised about ''the continuing
viability of the Examiner as an independent newspaper'' under new
ownership, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   The two newspaper deals had been scheduled to close Friday, but
Walker said the Chronicle and Examiner have been publishing under a
joint operating agreement since 1965 and would suffer little
hardship by waiting another two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosch, lawyer for the Chronicle Publishing Co., argued that
the antitrust laws didn't require Hearst to provide any subsidy or
any guarantee that the Examiner would survive.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this enterprise cannot support itself, your honor, then it
ought to go under,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst lawyer Gary Halling told Walker that Hearst agreed to the
''absurd'' idea of a subsidy in order to keep in the good graces of
the community.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one has come forward willing to take the Examiner even if
we gave it to them,'' Halling said.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent's publisher, Ted Fang, has announced plans to
switch the Examiner from afternoon to morning publication in August
and compete with the Hearst-owned Chronicle, which has offered jobs
to the Examiner's current staff.
</P>
<P>
   Under a joint operating agreement, which was scheduled to run
through 2005, the Examiner and Chronicle have combined their
business operations and split profits 50-50 while maintaining
separate editorial staffs. The sale would terminate the JOA.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco remains one of 47 cities in the nation with two or
more dailies.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said Thursday that its concerns about
competition were satisfied by Hearst's agreement to transfer the
Examiner to owners who would continue daily publication.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the first time in 35 years, San Francisco will have two
independent daily newspapers,'' said Antitrust Division head Joel
Klein. ''Consumers, such as advertisers and readers, will obtain
the benefits of full competition between two daily morning
papers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reilly, who ran unsuccessfully for mayor last fall and also
bid unsuccessfully for the Examiner, contended the terms of the
deal guaranteed failure for the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said experts in newspaper operations and finance have
advised him that a subsidy of at least $250 million was needed to
make the Examiner a viable competitor. He accused Hearst of using
the joint operating agreement to fend off other bidders for the
Chronicle, who offered far less than $660 million because they
would have had to assume the Chronicle's obligations under the JOA.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Executive Editor Matthew Wilson said the delay has
stirred anxiety in his newsroom. ''I think all of us here at the
paper wish that this would speed up and move on,'' he said. ''It's
been a long number of months for us, waiting for the paper to
sell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
