<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Co. Settles Racial Charge  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A New York mortgage company settled federal
charges Thursday that it singled out black women for higher loan
prices and approved loans for low-income homeowners who would have
difficulty repaying.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Funding Corporation of Woodbury made a quarter of its
annual loans in minority neighborhoods in New York City, where
between 1996 and 1999 it violated housing laws by charging black
women higher broker fees than white men who had similar financial
circumstances, the Federal Trade Commission and the Housing and
Justice departments charged.
</P>
<P>
   The company also approved loans without regard to borrowers'
ability to repay, burdening homeowners with debt and exposing them
to an increased risk of defaulting on their loans, said Jodie
Bernstein, director of the FTC's consumer protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ''Delta targeted these low-income homeowners for high monthly
payments, turning the American dream of home ownership into a
nightmare,'' Bernstein said in a statement. ''That's a dangerous
policy for borrowers because it could lead to the loss of thousands
of dollars and even their home.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was also charged with paying kickbacks and unearned
fees to brokers to induce them to refer loan applicants to Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the company must revise its lending
practices and is banned from any discriminatory actions. Consumers
harmed by the company's violations may be compensated by two funds
totaling more than $12 million that were created in a separate
settlement with the New York State Banking Department in September.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by Delta, the company said that it has not
violated any law. President and CEO Hugh Miller said the company
was ''pleased to have resolved all outstanding issues'' with the
federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who earlier in the day told a
Senate panel that his agency will propose new laws to fight home
lending abuses, said homeowners should not be burdened with unfair
mortgage costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lenders and mortgage brokers are put on notice by this
settlement agreement that HUD and the federal government are
prepared to fight for borrowers who are being victimized by
predatory mortgage lending practices,'' Cuomo said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is subject to approval by the U.S. District Court.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission Web site: http://www.ftc.gov
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development Web site:
http://www.hud.gov/news.html
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Justice Web site: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
