<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Leader Targets Corruption  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Responding to a spate of corruption
scandals in Congress, President Andres Pastrana on Thursday
proposed a national referendum to combat the ''dark cancer'' of
graft.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally televised address, he urged Colombians to
support the referendum to be submitted to Congress next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, dishonest and corrupt practices against the
budget belonging to all Colombians continue, like a dark cancer, to
eat away at the country's morale,'' Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
   Although graft and the use of public money for political favors
has been rampant in all branches of government, Pastrana's ballot
would focus on cleaning up the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Voters would be asked about proposals to punish corrupt
lawmakers, reform campaign finances and make politicians' voting
records public, among other measures. The government hopes to hold
the referendum by October.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, of the Conservative Party, was elected in part on
promises to clean up government following the scandal-plagued
administration of his Liberal Party predecessor, President Ernesto
Samper.
</P>
<P>
   Congress can veto the referendum plan, but Pastrana said he was
confident lawmakers would go along. There was no immediate reaction
from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Although accustomed to almost daily reports of corruption,
Colombians were disgusted last week when allegations arose of fraud
and kickbacks in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged misuse of $2.5 million dollars in contracts for
unrealized work and exorbitant decorations led to the resignations
this week of three senior lawmakers from leadership posts, and the
arrests of two congressional staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Charges also surfaced in the Senate, as the attorney general
this week suspended the body's chief executive officer on suspicion
of handing out phony contracts.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, police arrested a senior health ministry official
after catching him in a restaurant demanding a bribe in return for
a government contract.
</P>
<P>
   The recent cases are tiny in financial terms compared to huge
corruption scandals, including one involving tens of millions of
dollars in apparently phony public pensions, that have come to
light during Pastrana's 19 months in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
