<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrian Media: Next Move is Israel's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Official Syrian media on Thursday
rejected President Clinton's remark that Syria must take the next
step toward peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said this week that he told Syrian President Hafez Assad
in Geneva on Sunday about the options for a peace accord with
Israel, ''so the ball is in his court now.'' The meeting aimed --
but failed -- to bring the resumption of Israeli-Syrian peace talks
that stalled in January.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Baath newspaper, the mouthpiece of Syria's ruling Baath
party, countered that since the peace process was launched in 1991,
''the ball has never been in the Syrian court because Syria has
clearly announced that it opts for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Syrian newspapers are closely controlled and reflect the
government's views.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa briefed EU ambassadors to
Syria on the Geneva meeting, saying the talks had started
''cordially,'' the official Syrian Arab News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''But when President Clinton told President Assad that Israel
wants full sovereignty over the Jordan River waters and Tiberias
(Sea of Galilee) ... President Assad categorically rejected it,''
al-Sharaa told the EU diplomats, according to SANA.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has hinted he would give back
all of the Golan except land bordering the Sea of Galilee -- a major
water source -- that Damascus also claims.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa was quoted as saying Assad would not ''relinquish the
right of the people and the country, whatever time it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Barak, with his known obstinacy, hesitation and lack of an
in-depth decision-making spirit, has torpedoed a great achievement
that could have been reached by the summit,'' said an editorial by
the director general of SANA, Fayez Sayegh, in Wednesday's
Al-Thawra.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Baath newspaper on Thursday urged the United States not to
abandon the process, saying it was not deadlocked despite the
summit's failure.
</P>
<P>
   In Tel Aviv, Barak all but eulogized U.S.-led efforts to hammer
out a peace agreement between Israel and Syria, but said he is not
closing the door on the possibility of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said, ''Of course it would have been preferable'' to have
an agreement with Syria that would ensure quiet on Israel's
northern border when it pulls out of southern Lebanon in July. But
he insisted that even without a deal, he would go through with the
pullout plans from the occupied zone Israel has held there since
1985.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon and Israel wants it to
ensure Hezbollah guerrillas do not conduct cross-border attacks.
Syria opposes a unilateral withdrawal, saying it wants it as part
of a complete deal settling the Golan issue as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
