<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
Mary Fowler Brennan
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mary Fowler Brennan, wife of the late Supreme
Court Justice William J. Brennan, died Tuesday of cancer. She was
83.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brennan, a 40-year Supreme Court employee, worked for
nearly 26 years as Brennan's secretary. After the death of the
justice's first wife, he and his longtime secretary were married in
1983 -- her last day as a court employee.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan died in 1997 at age 91. He had retired in 1990 after a
34-year tenure on the nation's highest court.
</P>
<P>
Leonora G. Edwards
</P>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) -- Leonora G. Edwards, whose husband
sailed the last whaling voyage from New Bedford, died Tuesday. She
was 103.
</P>
<P>
   She was the widow of Capt. Joseph F. Edwards, who began his
whaling career aboard a square-rigged vessel commanded by his
brother in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   By 1918, as the commander of the Charles W. Morgan, one of New
Bedford's most famous whaling ships, Edwards took a year-long sperm
whaling expedition off Brazil and the West Indies even as WWI
German U-boats dotted the seas. He went on to lead whaling voyages
across the globe. In 1927 he commanded the last expedition in
America from what was once the world's busiest whaling port.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her life, Edwards shared her whaling ties with the
Whaling Museum and took part in its oral history program. She was a
member of the Boston Marine Society and the Descendants of Whaling
Masters.
</P>
<P>
Rudolf Kirchschlaeger
</P>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Former President Rudolf Kirchschlaeger,
who fathered the deal that led to Austria's independence after 10
years of occupation following World War II, died Thursday of a
heart attack. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Kirchschlaeger represented his country during the Austrian
Neutrality Pact negotiations in 1955, which led to the pullout of
Allied and Soviet troops. He served as president from 1974 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In his final interview, Kirchschlaeger lamented Austria's recent
isolation after the election of a far-right party whose leader was
linked to statements sympathetic to Nazi policies.
</P>
<P>
   From 1967 to 1970, Kirschlaeger served as ambassador to then
Czechoslovakia. During the ''Prague Spring,'' Kirchschlaeger left
the doors of the embassy open to people trying to flee Soviet
troops.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first presidential election in 1974, and six years
later, won more than 80 percent of the vote in winning his bid for
a second term.
</P>
<P>
Lily Simha Hood
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- French Quarter pianist and chanteuse Lily
Simha Hood, whose fans included Tennessee Williams, died March 24
of kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   She was cagey about revealing her age, and her husband asked
that the secret remain with her death.
</P>
<P>
   Her musical career began on a whim. After dinner one night in
1976, the Hoods and a friend stopped at Lafitte's Blacksmith Shop,
a Bourbon Street bar across from their house. Mrs. Hood played a
few tunes on the piano for her friend and was hired on the spot,
even though she wasn't looking for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, ''Miss Lily'' had a crowd of regulars including Tennessee
Williams, who would bring in a songbook for her to sing from.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hood never formally studied the piano and never learned to
read music. She was self-taught and learned by listening. She
performed at Lafitte's for 16 years, but health problems ended her
career about seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
Frances Gray Patton
</P>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Frances Gray Patton, best-known for her 1954
novel ''Good Morning, Miss Dove,'' died Tuesday. She was 94.
</P>
<P>
   The book was translated into 10 languages and became a movie
starring Jennifer Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Patton's short stories appeared in The New Yorker and Harper's,
among other prominent national publications.
</P>
<P>
   Patton, who taught creative writing at Duke and University of
North Carolina, published three short story collections, and she
once had a contract with The New Yorker for a series of 29 stories.
</P>
<P>
   She was known in the literary community for supporting and
encouraging fellow writers. She was honored for her contributions
by the North Carolina Writers Conference.
</P>
<P>
J. David Watson
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM (AP) -- J. David Watson, an advice columnist who
answered questions both serious and comical from readers of the
Winston-Salem Journal for 15 years, died Wednesday of a heart
attack. He was 51.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, known as Sam, the Straight-Answer Man, could handle even
the most arcane question.
</P>
<P>
   He received hundreds of letters and telephone calls a week, most
involving serious questions about finances, law or city government.
</P>
<P>
   Other readers wanted to know why people have hair but animals
have fur, or why they couldn't drive naked.
</P>
<P>
   If Watson didn't know the answer, he and his staff did whatever
it took to find it.
</P>
<P>
   He began his newspaper career in Hickory before joining the Twin
City Sentinel in Winston-Salem in 1974. He moved to the Journal in
1985 when the Sentinel folded.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is survived by his wife, Sharon; two sons, Aaron and
Evan; and his parents, Mr. and Mrs. J.D. Watson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 2227 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
