<DOCNO> APW20000330.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Class-Action Suit Against Bank OK'd  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A federal judge on Thursday granted a motion
requesting class-action status for a discrimination lawsuit filed
against the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago. The bank plans to
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, U.S. District Judge William Hibbler said the
class could include black employees who worked below the level of
officer from 1964 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in February 1998, alleges that the federal bank
refused to promote qualified black employees. It also claims that
those employees received lower wages, were denied training and were
degraded by on-the-job racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Stein, the lawyer representing the more than 34 employees
included so far in the lawsuit, said the class could now grow to
include more than 2,000 employees in the bank's district. The
district includes offices in Peoria, Detroit and Milwaukee, as well
as parts of Indiana and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling ''allows us to reach back to 1964 to examine
the practices and policies of the Federal Reserve Bank for the last
35 years,'' Stein said Thursday. ''We know we're going to find the
skeletons and the evidence on the trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lapinski, a spokesman for the Federal Reserve, said the bank
plans to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were very disappointed with the ruling, we don't agree with
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to more than $25 million in damages, the lawsuit
seeks lost wages and 10 percent of the bank's net worth.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve of Chicago is a branch of the
Washington-based Federal Reserve and handles such things as check
processing for the Midwest region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
