<HEADLINE> Penguins 4, Capitals 3, OT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hans Jonsson scored 2:25 into overtime to give
the Pittsburgh Penguins a 4-3 victory over the Washington Capitals
on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Washington earned a point for the regulation tie to pull even
with New Jersey for the Eastern Conference lead. The Capitals and
Devils both have five regular-season games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson beat goalie Olaf Kolzig with a hard shot from between
the circles to finish a 3-on-2 rush. Jonsson was the trailer on the
play and took a good centering pass from Martin Straka.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's Chris Simon scored his 29th goal of the season with
6:08 left in the third period to force overtime. The Capitals are
18-2-3 in their last 23 home games and 29-8-5 overall since Jan.1.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh played without Jaromir Jagr, the NHL's leading
scorer, who was sidelined for a second straight game because of a
bruised back.
</P>
<P>
   Washington wasted numerous scoring chances throughout the game,
missing several in a wide-open first period when it had 16 shots.
The Capitals held a 35-32 overall advantage in shots, but had
trouble beating goalie Ron Tugnutt (29 saves).
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Halpern gave the Capitals a 1-0 at 5:18 of the first
period, knocking in the rebound of Ulf Dahlen's shot. Dahlen swung
out from behind the net with Pittsburgh defenseman Jiri Slegr on
his left arm and somehow got off a shot that bounced off goalie Ron
Tugnutt and over to Halpern.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's Alexei Kovalev tied it with a power-play goal at
15:16 of the period. Richard Zednik gave the Capitals a 2-1 lead 43
seconds later following a pass from Joe Murphy on a 2-on-1 rush.
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy was hit with an unsportsmanlike conduct call on the
goal, and Robert Lang tied it with an extra-man goal 1:04 later.
Washington's penalty-kiling unit entered the game tied for fourth
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Josef Beranek gave Pittsburgh a 3-2 lead with the team's third
power-play goal with 9:20 left in the third period. Beranek sneaked
in from Kolzig's left side and knocked a loose puck into the net.
</P>
</TEXT>
