<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Car Bomb Kills Four  </HEADLINE>
By CESAR GARCIA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A powerful truck bomb exploded in a
tourist town west of the capital on Thursday, killing four people
and injuring at least 14 others, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's explosion ripped through the town square in Cachipay,
a getaway location for capital residents just 25 miles from Bogota.
It was the second fatal car bombing in the area in less than a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have blamed both attacks on the country's largest
leftist insurgency, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or
FARC. The rebel group has not claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Television images showed the town offices in ruins and debris
scattered about the square. On the street lay the twisted hulk of
the vehicle that exploded, a small truck loaded with soft drinks,
according to witnesses interviewed on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ''The FARC is bringing back memories in Colombia of the days of
Pablo Escobar,'' national police operations director Gen. Alfonso
Arellano told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The late former head of the Medellin cocaine cartel, Escobar
waged a campaign of bombings and assassinations a decade ago to
avoid his extradition to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Officials blame the FARC for a car bomb that exploded Sunday in
Girardot, a major tourist town just to the south. That explosion
near a marketplace killed a police cadet and injured 16 bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials and Colombia's Defense Minister, Luis Ramirez,
said the attacks could be linked to a rebel extortion scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors in Cundinamarca State, where both Cachipay and Girardot
are located, have complained of FARC threats of violence if they
refuse to hand over 10 percent of their town budgets to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel violence has continued unabated in Colombia despite the
opening of peace talks 14 months ago between the FARC and the
government of President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   A rebel attack on a remote northern town last weekend left 21
police officers and eight civilians dead, including the mayor and
two young children.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculate the guerrillas are stepping up violence
in an attempt to strengthen their hand in the peace talks. But
recent rebel violence has been widely repudiated by Colombians.
</P>
<P>
   A car bomb exploded in Bogota in November, killing eight
passers-by and injuring 45. Many believe that attack was carried
out by mafias trying to pressure the government against extraditing
drug suspects to the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 2239 </TRAILER>
