<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nike Ends Brown University Contract  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID RISING, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Nike is terminating its contract to
provide hockey equipment to Brown University, fearing the school
might try to make it comply with guidelines of a group pushing for
better working conditions in clothing factories.
</P>
<P>
   Nike said it objects to being held to the code of conduct
outlined by the Workers Rights Consortium, of which Brown was a
founding member, because the company disagrees with the group's
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''The WRC is based on a 'gotcha' monitoring technique,'' Simon
Pestridge, Nike's labor practices manager, said. He said they go to
factories and report on what they find, rather than work with
factories to effect change.
</P>
<P>
   He said the WRC's definition of a ''living wage'' is too vague.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no way we can commit to a document that is not
finished,'' Pestridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown notified Nike in late January that it wanted to
renegotiate its contract with the Beaverton, Ore., company, to
require it to comply with Brown's code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's code is not unlike Nike's, Vada Manager, Nike's director
of global issues management, said. But because the school is a
founding member of the WRC, Nike's lawyers said the school could
try and impose the WRC's code on Nike, Manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was the first school involved with the WRC to ask for a
renegotiation of its contract with Nike, Manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Nike were in the middle of a three-year contract, in
which Nike provided the men's and women's hockey teams with skates,
gloves, pads, and other goods under the Nike and Bauer labels. Nike
has no other contracts with Brown, Manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown spokesman Mark Nickel could not be reached for comment.
Sports information director Christopher Humm declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''They market mainly to college-aged kids ... and if Nike pulled
out from Brown they'd get a lot of criticism,'' Maria Roeper of the
WRC said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 2245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000330.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Milan indictment stirs passions of supporters, detractors  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Embarrassment or martyr?
</P>
<P>
   Those widely varying descriptions of Camden Mayor Milton Milan
emerged Thursday after the leader of New Jersey's poorest city was
indicted on corruption charges linking him to the Philadelphia mob.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, 37, was charged in a 19-count federal indictment with
bribery, conspiracy, extortion, money laundering, fraud and lesser
offenses. He was freed after putting up property he and his wife
own as collateral for his $150,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Ali Sloan-El, Milan's harshest critic, called
the indictment ''an embarrassment to this city.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were in his shoes, I would have stepped out,'' he said.
''My position is a long time ago he should have stepped down.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said he is preparing memos to his fellow council members
urging them to take unspecified action against Milan, although he
stopped short of saying he would seek the mayor's ouster.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan-El said the criminal charges will make it even harder for
the economically struggling city to attract new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''That weighs across the state and across the nation against
us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The potential impact on the city's fitful efforts to redevelop
itself was also on Gov. Christie Whitman's mind Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Camden has been a troubled city for years and we have put lots
of money, lots of time and attention into that city, and this kind
of disruption to the process of government is very, very
concerning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, you're innocent until proven guilty. He has turned
himself in, but you cannot ignore the severity of these charges and
the disruption that it will cause in a city that is already very,
very troubled,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fulbrook, president of the Cooper-Grant Neighborhood
Association, cited testimony from a recently completed drug trial
that named Milan as a drug customer and dealer in the 1980s before
he was elected to office.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question was, did he leave that lifestyle in the past, or
did he bring that with him to the city council and the mayor's
office,'' Fulbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges made public Thursday did not involve narcotics, and
Greg Reinert, a spokesman for the Camden County Prosecutor's
Office, said he knew of no pending drug-related case or
investigation involving Milan. The statute of limitations on
narcotics activity is five years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Walker, who served as assistant city business
administrator under Milan until last June, said he and other city
workers saw no obvious signs of corruption on the mayor's part.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ''There was always a lot of speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a drumbeat of negative publicity emerging from the drug
trial and the federal grand jury probe that culminated in
Thursday's indictments, Milan's supporters cautioned against a rush
to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Gilbert ''Whip'' Wilson said the mayor should be
presumed innocent until charges are proven.
</P>
<P>
   ''An indictment does not prove guilt,'' Wilson said. ''He has to
go through the system like anybody else. I'm a retired police
officer and I believe in innocent until proven guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was flanked by supporters, and bystanders walked up to
shake his hand as he strode with reporters and cameramen the two
blocks from his City Hall office to the courthouse to surrender at
midmorning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Edwin Martinez of the Door of Salvation Church in
Camden lent his support to the embattled mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm standing here as a pastor to let him know I'm by his
side,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   He said many other ministers in Camden, particularly in its
sizable Hispanic community, still support Milan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here because he needs us now,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Camden resident Royal Upshaw watched the Milan procession make
its way to the courthouse, then went to get his hair cut at a
barber shop on Spruce Street. He said he has supported Milan since
he took office, but isn't sure what to make of the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't feel too good about it,'' he said. ''The man did some
good things for the city. The streets are cleaner than they were,
and we've gotten some new businesses. We're doing better with him
than we were under the last three or four mayors.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, the former assistant business administrator, said
regardless of the outcome of the legal case against Milan, the case
should serve as a wake-up call to Camden residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly will clearly encourage all of us as residents of
Camden to review the standards by which we judge our elected
leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-30-00 2247 </TRAILER>
