<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Liquor CEO Charged in Scam  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The former chief operating officer of the U.S.
subsidiary of the world's No. 2 liquor company was charged in
Manhattan with diverting more than $15 million from the company
into offshore bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Valdes was charged in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
with conspiracy and money laundering in connection with the scheme
to steal from Domecq Importers Inc. of Old Greenwich, Conn., from
the late 1980s to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, a former president and vice president of sales
pleaded guilty to charges in connection with the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege that they managed to divert approximately
$15.6 million out of Domecq Importers Inc. with help from outside
vendors of advertising, display materials and other services.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Valdes and the others convinced the
vendors to bill Domecq Importers for goods never produced or
services never performed. Once the bills were paid, the vendors
then agreed to issue checks to shell corporations controlled by
Valdes and co-conspirators, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The checks were usually deposited in offshore accounts so income
tax could be evaded, the government alleged.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes worked at Domecq Importers between 1984 and 1996, holding
numerous jobs related to finance. In 1995, he became the company's
vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, Domecq Importers Inc. has been a U.S. subsidiary of
Allied Domecq PLC, the world's second-largest liquor company behind
Britain's Diageo, whose brands include Tanqueray gin and Guinness
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Domecq is based in London and employs more than 70,000
people worldwide. The U.S. subsidiary imports and distributes
numerous brands of liquor, including Sauza tequila, Courvoisier
cognac and Beefeater gin.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Valdes could face up to 20 years in prison and as
much as $500,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Valdes did not immediately return a telephone
message seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 2258 </TRAILER>
