<DOCNO> APW20000330.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Residents Fear Eruption  </HEADLINE>
By KAORI HITOMI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- Roads began cracking Friday as fissures grew
on the flanks of a snow-capped Japanese volcano, signs of magma
swelling below the earth. Experts warned a major eruption could
come at any time.
</P>
<P>
   More than 11,000 people have been forced to leave their homes
near Mount Usu on the northern Japanese island of Hokkaido. They've
been warned not to venture back.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything in the house is probably upsidedown,'' said
Masanori Ueyama, a 66-year-old farmer. ''I'm very, very anxious to
see what is happening in my house and in my field.''
</P>
<P>
   Intense earthquake activity went into a fourth day Friday.
Thousands of quakes have been registered around the 2,416-foot
mountain, 475 miles north of Tokyo. While tremors were less
frequent by Thursday evening, officials said they were gaining in
intensity because of the movement of magma underground.
</P>
<P>
   But the appearance of fissures was seen as particularly ominous.
The location of the cracks indicate an eruption may come from
somewhere other than the volcano's current crater.
</P>
<P>
   The meteorological agency issued an emergency warning Friday to
announce that cracks on the mountain are increasing in number and
growing in length, splitting roads in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Observers aboard a military helicopter found that magma had
pushed open cracks on the volcano's western slope and near its base
Thursday. One fissure on the western slope stretched 100 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that an eruption would melt the snow on the volcano's
flanks and cause mudslides, authorities ordered the evacuation of
4,137 homes in this town at the volcano's base and two others --
Sobetsu and Abuta. Together, the towns have a population of 51,300.
</P>
<P>
   Sanitation was becoming a problem as residents taken to shelters
were unable to take baths, and everyday necessities were running
low, said Yoshio Nagasaki, mayor of Abuta.
</P>
<P>
   ''The longer the duration of the wait, the harder it becomes,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The area is known for a scenic lake and hot spring resorts, but
hotel owners began turning tourists away Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Residential areas near the volcano were deserted except for
police cars blocking the roads, town officials checking for
stragglers and abandoned dogs scampering about the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, an emergency task force was set up at Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi's residence. Some 3,000 army troops in Hokkaido were
on standby.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is one of the world's most eruption-prone countries, with
86 active volcanoes, according to Japan's meteorological agency.
The agency describes an active volcano as one that has erupted at
least once over the last 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Usu last erupted in 1977 and mudslides caused by eruptions
that continued into the following year left two people dead and
destroyed nearly 200 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe an eruption of Usu would probably be similar to
Mount Unzen in southern Japan in 1991, when several eruptions sent
avalanches of hot rocks sweeping down, killing 43 people and
leaving nearly 2,300 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Japan's Meteorological Agency site,
http://www.kishou.go.jp/english/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-30-00 2301 </TRAILER>
