<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, March 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Dad's Visa Attempt Hits Snag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's father asked for a visa today to come to the
United States and take the boy back to Cuba. The attempt hit a procedural snag,
however, when the State Department told the father's lawyer that applications
must be submitted to the U.S. diplomatic mission in Havana. Discussions between
immigration officials and the boy's Miami relatives, meanwhile, ended without a
resolution. The talks were set to resume Monday. The Immigration and
Naturalization Service had warned that it would revoke Elian's right to stay in
the United States unless the relatives promised to turn him over if their legal
appeals were rejected. But after today's meeting, the INS pushed back the
deadline for a second time to at least Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate Looking At Gas Tax Rollback
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate took a halting step today toward acting on
legislation that would temporarily roll back 4.3 cents of the federal gas tax.
The measure has little chance of House passage and does not offer much relief
for motorists coping with spiraling prices at the pump. Republicans led by
Majority Leader Trent Lott are making the issue prime fodder for this election
year, referring to it as the ''Gore tax'' because Vice President Al Gore cast
the tie-breaking 1993 Senate vote to make it law. GOP presidential candidate
George W. Bush favors ''efforts to lower gas prices'' but has not taken a stand
on the temporary repeal, spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Approves $13 Billion Measure
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved a $13 billion measure today for the
Pentagon, Colombia and recovery from Hurricane Floyd after refusing to threaten
European allies with a pullout of U.S. peacekeepers from Kosovo. The Senate
Appropriations Committee plans to write a roughly $6 billion version of the bill
next week, despite long-running opposition by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss. But Lott is under growing pressure to reverse himself. The legislation
provides money for popular causes like American soldiers and drug-fighting
overseas and road-building, natural disaster recovery and farmers at home.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
eBay Reveals Federal Investigations
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Online auction company eBay Inc. revealed in federal
filings today it is the subject of at least three local and federal
investigations into its business practices. EBay said in a filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission that the Justice Department last week
subpoenaed documents relating to an investigation begun in 1997 of Sotheby's and
Christie's of alleged price-fixing in commissions. The auction houses, which
control 95 percent of the $4 billion worldwide auction market, have said they
are cooperating with prosecutors, and news reports have said the auction houses
are being scrutinized for failing to charge fees to their wealthiest clients.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arabs Mark Annual Protest Day
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinians from the West Bank and Gaza joined with
Israeli Arabs on Thursday to demonstrate on Land Day, the annual protest of
Israel's confiscation of Arab land. At least 20 people were injured in clashes
with Israeli police and soldiers. The most violent confrontation came in the
Israeli Arab town of Sakhnin, where police said about 400 demonstrators broke
through a fence surrounding an Israeli army base.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo's main share index fell Friday after an overnight decline
on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average dropped 182.15 points to 20,259.35. In
New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 38.47 to 10,980.25 at Thursday's
finish. The Nasdaq composite index closed at 4,457.89, down 186.78, or 4.0
percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Penguins Defeat Capitals 4-3, OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hans Jonsson scored 2:25 into overtime to give the
Pittsburgh Penguins a 4-3 victory over the Washington Capitals tonight.
Washington earned a point for the regulation tie to pull even with New Jersey
for the Eastern Conference. The Capitals and Devils both have five
regular-season games remaining. Jonsson beat goalie Olaf Kolzig with a hard shot
from between the circles to finish a 3-on-2 rush. Jonsson was the trailer on the
play and took a good centering pass from Martin Straka.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wake Forest Wins NIT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wake Forest players hugged at center court, their midseason
struggles a distant memory as they celebrated the NIT championship. Robert
O'Kelley, the tournament MVP, made five 3-pointers and finished with 19 points
to lead Wake Forest to a 71-61 victory over Notre Dame in the final of the
National Invitation Tournament at Madison Square Garden tonight. Craig Dawson
added 13 points for the Demon Deacons (22-14), who won their first NIT final in
the first game between the schools. Notre Dame's Troy Murphy finished with 20
points on 8-for-16 shooting.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
