<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-30 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Cyclist Kidnapped, Again  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Retired Colombian cycling hero Oliverio
Rincon was abducted for the second time this year by leftist
guerrillas, authorities said Thursday. He was later freed after 24
hours in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Rincon's previous, monthlong kidnapping -- and the abduction
earlier this month of the country's best-known cyclist, Luis
Alberto ''Lucho'' Herrera -- outraged sports fans and athletes in a
country where kidnapping has become a thriving industry.
</P>
<P>
   Rincon was released Thursday evening in his car, which he drove
to an army base 30 miles from where he was abducted a day earlier
in central Boyaca State, army anti-kidnapping chief Col. Jesus
Bohorquez told Radionet Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Bohorquez did not provide details, and Rincon had yet to make
any statements.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old athlete -- one of Colombia's top cyclists of the
1990s -- was seized Wednesday along with his family by armed men who
intercepted his car as he drove along a country road with his wife,
mother-in-law and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Two men wearing ski masks and waving pistols forced Rincon's
Ford Explorer off the road near Duitama, his hometown in Boyaca,
state police commander Col. Pedro Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   The men then boarded the car and drove for several hours into a
mountainous region dominated by the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, or FARC, the country's largest leftist insurgency,
Ramirez told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Rincon was told a rebel commander wanted to speak with him, but
was given no more details, the police chief added. Police have had
no direct contact with the kidnappers, and based their account
largely on information provided by Rincon's wife, Gilma Rincon.
</P>
<P>
   Gilma Rincon, her children and mother were released Thursday
morning in Duitama.
</P>
<P>
   ''They treated us well and when I said goodbye the men told me
not to worry,'' Gilma Rincon told Colombia's Caracol Radio
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She said the kidnappers -- who identified themselves as members
of FARC -- had not made any demands and had promised not to hurt her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Rincon spent 10 days as captive of another leftist
guerrilla group, reportedly the smaller National Liberation Army,
or ELN. He was released Jan. 30, the same day hundreds of Colombian
athletes marched in Bogota to demand his freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Rincon said he had not paid a ransom, the most common objective
of the roughly 3,000 kidnappings committed annually in the South
American nation, mostly by rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Rincon gained national famed for racing in major international
events including the Tour de France, Tour of Italy and Tour of
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Herrera was kidnapped by guerrillas earlier this month and
released the next day following a nationwide outcry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
